WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.480
[Amit Varma]: On December 6, 1992, a group of young men climbed on top of a mosque in Ayodhya and

00:00:11.480 --> 00:00:13.680
[Amit Varma]: demolished a part of India.

00:00:13.680 --> 00:00:17.720
[Amit Varma]: It was a symbolic moment for our country, but I'd argue that it wasn't a seminal

00:00:17.720 --> 00:00:18.720
[Amit Varma]: one.

00:00:18.720 --> 00:00:19.720
[Amit Varma]: It wasn't a turning point.

00:00:19.720 --> 00:00:23.640
[Amit Varma]: There were forces that happened to be gathering strength at that point and what was destroyed

00:00:23.640 --> 00:00:26.320
[Amit Varma]: that day would have been destroyed anyway.

00:00:26.320 --> 00:00:30.120
[Amit Varma]: There was a cultural movement that had been on the rise for a century.

00:00:30.120 --> 00:00:35.040
[Amit Varma]: There was a political movement that was on the upswing and about to become unstoppable.

00:00:35.040 --> 00:00:40.520
[Amit Varma]: December 6, 1992 was just one milestone in the journey that has brought us to December

00:00:40.520 --> 00:00:41.960
[Amit Varma]: 6, 2020.

00:00:41.960 --> 00:00:47.960
[Amit Varma]: In these 28 years, our politics has changed, our society has changed, our country has changed.

00:00:47.960 --> 00:00:54.400
[Amit Varma]: And it's worth looking back at how all this happened.

00:00:54.400 --> 00:00:59.800
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral

00:00:59.800 --> 00:01:00.800
[Unknown]: science.

