[Guest]: Thank you very much, Amit.

00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:04.880
[Amit Varma]: You know, before we start, and I must say I enjoyed reading your book enormously, tons

00:04:04.880 --> 00:04:07.360
[Amit Varma]: of insights in there for someone like me.

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:09.520
[Amit Varma]: Let's talk a bit about your personal journey though.

00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:13.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, this is of course, your second biography, your first one was of D. V. Narsimha Rao.

00:04:13.040 --> 00:04:17.120
[Amit Varma]: But let's even sort of go a little further back in time, you know, what did you want

00:04:17.120 --> 00:04:18.120
[Amit Varma]: to do when you were growing up?

00:04:18.120 --> 00:04:22.200
[Amit Varma]: You've described yourself elsewhere as a child of liberalization in the sense that your dad

00:04:22.200 --> 00:04:26.280
[Amit Varma]: shifted from a PSU to a private sector company and all of that.

00:04:26.280 --> 00:04:28.040
[Amit Varma]: So tell me about the young Vinay.

00:04:28.040 --> 00:04:29.040
[Amit Varma]: What was he like?

00:04:29.040 --> 00:04:30.160
[Amit Varma]: What did he want to do?

00:04:30.160 --> 00:04:33.040
[Amit Varma]: What were the different sort of routes you took through your life?

00:04:33.040 --> 00:04:42.480
[Guest]: Well, Amit, when I had to apply for a master's degree or PhD, you have to write these personal

00:04:42.480 --> 00:04:43.480
[Guest]: statements, right?

00:04:43.480 --> 00:04:48.320
[Guest]: And I realized when it came to my personal statement that there wasn't a narrative.

00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:50.720
[Guest]: I was just kind of following instinct.

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:55.520
[Unknown]: So I think your listeners won't get like, when I write my books, I make sure there's

00:04:55.520 --> 00:04:56.520
[Unknown]: a narrative, right?

00:04:56.520 --> 00:05:01.520
[Guest]: Like Vajpayee is born and then Advani is born and then they kind of move up with the arc

00:05:01.520 --> 00:05:02.520
[Unknown]: of history.

00:05:02.520 --> 00:05:04.800
[Unknown]: Now, unfortunately, that's not the case with me.

00:05:04.800 --> 00:05:07.920
[Guest]: So you know, to give you a sense, I'm 37.

00:05:07.920 --> 00:05:11.040
[Guest]: So I'm a child of the 1990s.

00:05:11.040 --> 00:05:15.640
[Guest]: And you know, my father had, you know, he worked for Ex-Im Bank, which was a PSU.

00:05:15.640 --> 00:05:19.480
[Guest]: And then he left in the early 90s to start off on his own as a consultant.

00:05:19.480 --> 00:05:25.680
[Guest]: And I remember it was a very dislocating time for all of us, you know, that in Nehruvian

00:05:25.680 --> 00:05:29.880
[Guest]: India, if you are a government employee, you know, you had a nice house, you know, you

00:05:29.880 --> 00:05:34.840
[Guest]: had like a car and a driver, it was all as long as you're in government service, it's

00:05:34.840 --> 00:05:39.240
[Guest]: a pretty comfy life, I think prior to 91, then he made it out on his own and you know,

00:05:39.240 --> 00:05:42.360
[Guest]: this was a rough and tumble of the early private sector.

00:05:42.360 --> 00:05:45.440
[Guest]: And I still remember, you know, we didn't have a car and okay, whatever, but you know,

00:05:45.440 --> 00:05:51.560
[Guest]: when you're a kid, you know, people kids talk, they make jokes, you know, it's a it's a thing.

00:05:51.560 --> 00:05:57.080
[Guest]: And so it stayed with me and I couldn't quite understand it or I couldn't quite make sense

00:05:57.080 --> 00:06:01.120
[Guest]: of it at that time, but I knew that there was a shift, for example, I remember sometime

00:06:01.120 --> 00:06:02.120
[Guest]: around 95.

00:06:02.120 --> 00:06:06.120
[Guest]: So I'm, you know, born and brought up in Bandra, I'm from Bandra.

00:06:06.120 --> 00:06:11.200
[Guest]: And I remember McDonald's coming for the first time, you know, in Linking Road.

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:12.200
[Guest]: And we all went there.

00:06:12.200 --> 00:06:17.680
[Guest]: And there was this huge line, you know, and it was so long a line that they had dedicated,

00:06:17.680 --> 00:06:20.800
[Unknown]: you know, servers to come with the menu.

00:06:20.800 --> 00:06:24.160
[Guest]: And so you can order while you're in that line, and that line kind of sneaked through

00:06:24.160 --> 00:06:25.160
[Guest]: Linking Road.

00:06:25.160 --> 00:06:30.320
[Guest]: Then again, like I couldn't mix and I remember Baba Sehgal and you know, that kind of thing.

00:06:30.320 --> 00:06:34.400
[Guest]: And again, you know, it's not that I could make sense of it at that time.

00:06:34.400 --> 00:06:39.040
[Guest]: But I remember looking back, there was something dislocating about it, you know, and it took

00:06:39.040 --> 00:06:43.840
[Guest]: me a while to realize that my immediate story is also the largest story of many Indians

00:06:43.840 --> 00:06:44.840
[Guest]: during that period.

00:06:44.840 --> 00:06:50.800
[Guest]: Then the other sort of, again, in the early 90s, you know, something that I grew up with

00:06:50.800 --> 00:06:54.160
[Guest]: was the rise of the BJP, you know, in 95.

00:06:54.160 --> 00:06:59.840
[Guest]: The Shiv Sena BJP comes to power for the first time in Maharashtra, where I was, and it ended

00:06:59.840 --> 00:07:02.160
[Unknown]: basically a total hegemony of the Congress.

00:07:02.160 --> 00:07:07.000
[Unknown]: So even the non-Congress governments in Maharashtra until then was broadly splinter groups, broadly,

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:08.000
[Guest]: you know.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:12.880
[Guest]: And I remember very clearly the Bombay riots, you know, immediately after the demolition

00:07:12.880 --> 00:07:15.880
[Guest]: of Babri Masjid whose anniversary is right now.

00:07:15.880 --> 00:07:19.800
[Guest]: So this is, you know, just soon after December 6, 92.

00:07:19.800 --> 00:07:24.240
[Guest]: And I remember, you know, we were on this side of the Mahim Creek in Bandra Reclamation.

00:07:24.240 --> 00:07:29.240
[Guest]: And I remember we could all get on to the top of our building and look at the timber

00:07:29.240 --> 00:07:33.080
[Guest]: yards owned by Muslims on the other side of the creek burning.

00:07:33.080 --> 00:07:36.440
[Guest]: And again, I couldn't, you know, this, like, you know, whatever, I was a kid.

00:07:36.440 --> 00:07:39.840
[Guest]: So none of this kind of, you know, made sense to me at that time.

00:07:39.840 --> 00:07:44.040
[Guest]: But looking back, I think some of it may have lingered, you know, and my first book was

00:07:44.040 --> 00:07:47.200
[Guest]: definitely a way to make sense of liberalization.

00:07:47.200 --> 00:07:51.920
[Guest]: And I focused on a person, Narasimha Rao, and sort of the core of the argument of the

00:07:51.920 --> 00:07:54.760
[Guest]: book is that liberalization wasn't fated to happen.

00:07:54.760 --> 00:07:59.280
[Guest]: You know, McDonald's, it wasn't an inevitable march of history that McDonald's would open

00:07:59.280 --> 00:08:00.280
[Guest]: in Linky Grove.

00:08:00.280 --> 00:08:05.640
[Guest]: But it was, there was a lot of political maneuvering, right, done by the Prime Minister of the day

00:08:05.640 --> 00:08:08.920
[Guest]: that allowed it to happen against the arc of history.

00:08:08.920 --> 00:08:12.240
[Guest]: So in some sense, I was pushing against those who say that with the collapse of the Soviet

00:08:12.240 --> 00:08:18.080
[Guest]: Union, you know, with, you know, the decline of the Indian economy, you know, this was

00:08:18.080 --> 00:08:19.080
[Guest]: inevitable.

00:08:19.080 --> 00:08:22.960
[Guest]: I, you know, and so that was the argument for that book.

00:08:22.960 --> 00:08:27.200
[Guest]: And for this book, you know, I guess, you know, I was looking a little more at Hindu

00:08:27.200 --> 00:08:30.160
[Guest]: nationalism, a little less as a biography.

00:08:30.160 --> 00:08:35.280
[Guest]: So as you've read, I mean, firstly, it's a biography of a relationship, right?

00:08:35.280 --> 00:08:39.840
[Guest]: It's not just a biography and the relationship itself is a symbol for the larger question

00:08:39.840 --> 00:08:44.800
[Guest]: why the BJP wins, like what is the Hindu nationalism and why the BJP wins.

00:08:44.800 --> 00:08:50.280
[Guest]: So in that sense, this is more of a kind of a classically academic or scholarly question,

00:08:50.280 --> 00:08:53.840
[Guest]: which is, you know, what explains the hundred year story of the BJP.

00:08:53.840 --> 00:09:00.920
[Guest]: But even so, I can, you know, I do sense looking back that, you know, that it's not a coincidence

00:09:00.920 --> 00:09:03.680
[Guest]: that these are my two books and I was a child of the 90s.

00:09:03.680 --> 00:09:07.720
[Amit Varma]: No, no, that's fascinating and you brought memories stumbling back because when McDonald's

00:09:07.720 --> 00:09:11.920
[Amit Varma]: opened here, I remember sort of being in an auto going through Linking Road and realizing

00:09:11.920 --> 00:09:14.040
[Amit Varma]: that the line to McDonald's started in Khar.

00:09:14.040 --> 00:09:18.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that was because I was part of the line, that was part of the...

00:09:18.240 --> 00:09:22.720
[Amit Varma]: Well, you alone didn't make it stretch all the way to Khar, but yeah, you were one of

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:27.720
[Amit Varma]: the sort of unwashed masses, you know, and I mean, I didn't join the line that day, but

00:09:27.720 --> 00:09:29.480
[Amit Varma]: I joined the line some other day.

00:09:29.480 --> 00:09:33.960
[Guest]: Also Amit, it's actually the washed masses because, you know, McDonald's at that time

00:09:33.960 --> 00:09:35.800
[Unknown]: was an upper class thing.

00:09:35.800 --> 00:09:39.880
[Unknown]: You know, it's not, it was an upper middle class idea, whereas in the United States,

00:09:39.880 --> 00:09:43.760
[Guest]: the people who go to McDonald's tend to be poorer, right, generally.

00:09:43.760 --> 00:09:48.120
[Guest]: In that time period, you were looking at that line, it was the aspiration for upper middle

00:09:48.120 --> 00:09:49.120
[Guest]: class India.

00:09:49.120 --> 00:09:54.400
[Amit Varma]: Well, you know, if I have to quibble with that trivial point, I could also say that

00:09:54.400 --> 00:09:59.000
[Amit Varma]: number one, you know, people down the line might consider it offensive that you are implying

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:05.080
[Amit Varma]: that they don't wash and that washing, you know, goes up in frequency with the classes.

00:10:05.080 --> 00:10:10.440
[Amit Varma]: And also, you know, if a future biographer of yours is to, you know, eventually investigate

00:10:10.440 --> 00:10:15.440
[Amit Varma]: your life, I'm sure he'll, in hindsight, stick a narrative to it, just as you know, all biographies

00:10:15.440 --> 00:10:16.440
[Amit Varma]: have to have.

00:10:16.440 --> 00:10:18.600
[Amit Varma]: And a little bit of that is emerging now.

00:10:18.600 --> 00:10:22.480
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, taking off from what you just said, I sort of have a question there.

00:10:22.480 --> 00:10:26.960
[Amit Varma]: As you said in your first book, one of the points that you were making is that liberalization

00:10:26.960 --> 00:10:29.760
[Amit Varma]: wasn't inevitable, the things that happened weren't inevitable.

00:10:29.760 --> 00:10:35.400
[Amit Varma]: Now, one of my frequent bugbears often is that we don't think probabilistically about

00:10:35.400 --> 00:10:40.520
[Amit Varma]: the world in the sense that whenever something has happened, we assume that it was inevitable.

00:10:40.520 --> 00:10:45.760
[Amit Varma]: While obviously, at any given point in time, we only have a sea of probabilities ahead

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:46.760
[Amit Varma]: of us.

00:10:46.760 --> 00:10:49.600
[Amit Varma]: But in hindsight, there is an inevitability.

00:10:49.600 --> 00:10:55.000
[Amit Varma]: And that can lead us to underplay both the role of chance and the role of individuals.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:11:01.400
[Amit Varma]: Like, you know, there's one sort of common strand in history that you must have grappled

00:11:01.400 --> 00:11:05.360
[Amit Varma]: with about how, you know, there's no such thing as a great man theory of history.

00:11:05.360 --> 00:11:09.600
[Amit Varma]: And it's all, you know, there are larger currents which determine how the world's move.

00:11:09.600 --> 00:11:14.160
[Amit Varma]: But the more I read of history and including much of what is in this book, it just strikes

00:11:14.160 --> 00:11:19.920
[Amit Varma]: me that chance events really make so much of a difference, like you've brought up various

00:11:19.920 --> 00:11:23.400
[Amit Varma]: counterfactuals in your book, which we'll discuss when we get to it.

00:11:23.400 --> 00:11:26.960
[Amit Varma]: And it seems that the history of the country could have been different had we proceeded

00:11:26.960 --> 00:11:29.240
[Amit Varma]: down a slightly different line.

00:11:29.240 --> 00:11:30.560
[Amit Varma]: So what is your sense of this?

00:11:30.560 --> 00:11:32.720
[Amit Varma]: And this is really a dual question.

00:11:32.720 --> 00:11:37.680
[Amit Varma]: One is that there are, I suppose, different academic approaches to history.

00:11:37.680 --> 00:11:44.160
[Amit Varma]: And is it then you sometimes find that you have to set those aside when you are actually,

00:11:44.160 --> 00:11:48.640
[Amit Varma]: you know, performing the task of writing history or doing history as it were.

00:11:48.640 --> 00:11:52.040
[Amit Varma]: And what are sort of your views on all this?

00:11:52.040 --> 00:11:57.600
[Amit Varma]: I mean, would you also tend to say that chance is actually the biggest determinate, you know,

00:11:57.600 --> 00:11:58.600
[Guest]: of what really happens?

00:11:58.600 --> 00:12:00.440
[Guest]: Well, that's a very good question, Amit.

00:12:00.440 --> 00:12:05.480
[Guest]: And as you can see, in both this book, as well as the Narsimha Rao book, I spend a lot

00:12:05.480 --> 00:12:09.880
[Guest]: of time playing up the role of events and individuals, right?

00:12:09.880 --> 00:12:12.280
[Guest]: I wouldn't call it chance alone, right?

00:12:12.280 --> 00:12:16.480
[Unknown]: Because events happen for a variety of like, let's take emergency, it's not luck.

00:12:16.480 --> 00:12:21.080
[Guest]: But as you read in the book, the emergency has played a huge role in socializing the

00:12:21.080 --> 00:12:27.400
[Guest]: RSS and BJP of that era, note I mean of that era, right, into respecting civil liberties,

00:12:27.400 --> 00:12:31.320
[Unknown]: you know, because they realize that, look, if we put people in jail, they can also put

00:12:31.320 --> 00:12:36.120
[Guest]: us in jail, you know, and the law is what kind of comes in between that, or, you know,

00:12:36.120 --> 00:12:39.920
[Guest]: in the book itself, I point out the murder of Mahatma Gandhi.

00:12:39.920 --> 00:12:45.120
[Guest]: And I'm quite clear that the institutions of Hindu nationalism, namely Hindu Mahasabha

00:12:45.120 --> 00:12:47.680
[Guest]: at the time and RSS didn't play a role.

00:12:47.680 --> 00:12:53.120
[Unknown]: But the ideology totally did in the sense that the RSS criticism of Gandhi was shared

00:12:53.120 --> 00:12:54.120
[Guest]: by Godse.

00:12:54.120 --> 00:12:55.120
[Unknown]: 100%.

00:12:55.120 --> 00:12:56.120
[Unknown]: Right?

00:12:56.120 --> 00:12:59.720
[Guest]: It's just that the RSS didn't want to take any violent action, you know, to act on that

00:12:59.720 --> 00:13:00.720
[Guest]: inference.

00:13:00.720 --> 00:13:06.120
[Guest]: But as a consequence, the Indian state came down very hard on the RSS, very, very hard.

00:13:06.120 --> 00:13:12.040
[Unknown]: Even today, even today, almost what 70 years later, the RSS remembers that period between

00:13:12.040 --> 00:13:18.040
[Guest]: February 1948, and I think July 1949, as its most traumatic period, all the pracharats

00:13:18.040 --> 00:13:22.040
[Guest]: were thrown in jail, the head of the RSS, Bulwarkar was thrown in jail.

00:13:22.040 --> 00:13:26.680
[Guest]: And you know, it's sort of, it pushes the RSS, which until that time was an anti-political

00:13:26.680 --> 00:13:32.400
[Guest]: organization, which was critical of electoral politics into creating a political party,

00:13:32.400 --> 00:13:36.520
[Guest]: the Jansan, which is a precursor of the BJP, as political insurance.

00:13:36.520 --> 00:13:37.520
[Guest]: Right?

00:13:37.520 --> 00:13:42.000
[Guest]: So that's, again, just one example to show exactly the point you're making.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:45.080
[Guest]: At the same time, I mean, I am, you know, I'm a trained academic, right?

00:13:45.080 --> 00:13:49.240
[Unknown]: Like I have like, you know, like, you know, given that academics don't make much money,

00:13:49.240 --> 00:13:53.520
[Guest]: I tell my larger family, look, I have five degrees, you know, and that's taught me something

00:13:53.520 --> 00:13:57.920
[Guest]: and it's taught me that structure, demographics also make a difference, right?

00:13:57.920 --> 00:14:04.080
[Guest]: So to give you one example, I point out that a lot of events in the 1980s, Rath Yatra,

00:14:04.080 --> 00:14:07.160
[Guest]: for example, helped in the mobilization of the BJP.

00:14:07.160 --> 00:14:12.840
[Guest]: But fundamentally, the rise of the BJP began as a set of demographic anxieties, right,

00:14:12.840 --> 00:14:14.400
[Guest]: which are bottom up.

00:14:14.400 --> 00:14:19.480
[Guest]: So for example, Hindu fear of all castes because of the Khalistan movement, because Khalistanis

00:14:19.480 --> 00:14:22.600
[Guest]: were targeting Hindus as Hindus, right?

00:14:22.600 --> 00:14:27.280
[Guest]: And the upper caste North Indian fears because of the extension of OBC reservation in Northern

00:14:27.280 --> 00:14:29.200
[Guest]: Indian states, right?

00:14:29.200 --> 00:14:34.880
[Guest]: All this worry that Saudi petrodollars is going to fuel conversions in India, exemplified

00:14:34.880 --> 00:14:40.560
[Guest]: by the controversy surrounding the 1981 Meenakshi Kurang conversions in Tamil Nadu, a small

00:14:40.560 --> 00:14:42.000
[Guest]: town in Tamil Nadu.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.600
[Unknown]: So these are not just events and individuals, right?

00:14:44.600 --> 00:14:48.160
[Guest]: These are like larger forces that are reshaping India.

00:14:48.160 --> 00:14:54.480
[Guest]: And I think that, I mean, I'd love to discuss this, that my dual training as a journalist

00:14:54.480 --> 00:14:59.760
[Guest]: and an academic makes me alive to both, you know, and this book is both, you know, so

00:14:59.760 --> 00:15:04.560
[Unknown]: if a journalist reads it, what she or he will find nice about the book is it talks about

00:15:04.560 --> 00:15:08.440
[Unknown]: like these larger structural stories that journalists don't focus on, right?

00:15:08.440 --> 00:15:12.720
[Guest]: And in academics, what they like is that it focuses on events and individuals which normally

00:15:12.720 --> 00:15:13.720
[Guest]: they don't focus on.

00:15:13.720 --> 00:15:19.120
[Guest]: And I think it's a serious error on the part of academics that they don't do this.

00:15:19.120 --> 00:15:23.160
[Guest]: And you know, I mean, I'm not a historian, I'm a political scientist, right?

00:15:23.160 --> 00:15:26.680
[Guest]: So this, I mean, I'm looking at a hundred year political history of the BJP, but my

00:15:26.680 --> 00:15:28.760
[Guest]: training is as a political scientist.

00:15:28.760 --> 00:15:30.760
[Unknown]: So I'm interested in causation, right?

00:15:30.760 --> 00:15:32.480
[Unknown]: I'm not just interested in narration.

00:15:32.480 --> 00:15:38.200
[Guest]: So the end of the book, as you'll see, I give you a set of arguments for why, what Hindu

00:15:38.200 --> 00:15:39.200
[Guest]: nationalism is.

00:15:39.200 --> 00:15:44.200
[Guest]: Look, it's not fascist, it's majoritarian, and also why the BJP wins, right?

00:15:44.200 --> 00:15:48.600
[Guest]: And the 1980s itself, I give you a complex set of causal arguments because causation

00:15:48.600 --> 00:15:49.600
[Guest]: matters to me.

00:15:49.600 --> 00:15:54.360
[Guest]: And if causation matters to you, like, you know, what causes the rise of the BJP rather

00:15:54.360 --> 00:15:58.760
[Guest]: than just give a description of the BJP and say, you know, like I keep telling my students

00:15:58.760 --> 00:16:03.080
[Guest]: that, you know, when you're explaining anything, it can't be a Gujarati thali with like a hundred

00:16:03.080 --> 00:16:04.080
[Guest]: explanations, right?

00:16:04.080 --> 00:16:09.320
[Guest]: You have to say that, look, the BJP rose because of A and B and not C and D. That's very important

00:16:09.320 --> 00:16:10.320
[Guest]: for me, right?

00:16:10.320 --> 00:16:13.320
[Guest]: That you also have to exclude the arguments that you don't think work.

00:16:13.320 --> 00:16:17.560
[Guest]: Otherwise, it's a bit of a cop out to say that, look, there's a bit of everything, right?

00:16:17.560 --> 00:16:21.800
[Unknown]: But if you have that kind of mentality, then you should be open that, look, occasionally

00:16:21.800 --> 00:16:26.160
[Guest]: events matter, occasionally individuals matter, occasionally structures matter, right?

00:16:26.160 --> 00:16:31.320
[Guest]: Like to give you another example, unrelated to India, I mean, let's look at the Brexit,

00:16:31.320 --> 00:16:32.320
[Guest]: right?

00:16:32.320 --> 00:16:35.360
[Guest]: The decision of the United Kingdom to leave the European Union.

00:16:35.360 --> 00:16:39.640
[Guest]: A lot of that is explained through personalities, you know, the personalities of the times.

00:16:39.640 --> 00:16:44.800
[Guest]: Just looking at these larger structural reasons, globalization, decline of white working class

00:16:44.800 --> 00:16:47.520
[Guest]: pride, you won't get Brexit.

00:16:47.520 --> 00:16:52.560
[Guest]: And if you are a social scientist who is honest or wants to be honest about not like peddling

00:16:52.560 --> 00:16:58.040
[Guest]: your pet disciplinary lens, but finding an answer to the truth, you have to be kind of

00:16:58.040 --> 00:17:01.160
[Guest]: ecumenical about the approaches that you use.

00:17:01.160 --> 00:17:02.160
[Guest]: That's how I came to it.

00:17:02.160 --> 00:17:07.120
[Guest]: I mean, in fact, I would say that, you know, I began my career as a lawyer, in the sense

00:17:07.120 --> 00:17:10.840
[Guest]: I studied at National Law School, Bangalore and Harvard Law School.

00:17:10.840 --> 00:17:14.720
[Guest]: And I then, you know, worked as a journalist with Indian Express, I would say the best

00:17:14.720 --> 00:17:17.080
[Guest]: political newspaper in India in English.

00:17:17.080 --> 00:17:18.900
[Guest]: And then I've also been an academic.

00:17:18.900 --> 00:17:24.800
[Guest]: So I luckily for me, like this three careers that I've had, has given me, you know, a bullshit

00:17:24.800 --> 00:17:30.720
[Guest]: detector about what is what any of those sort of professions can add value.

00:17:30.720 --> 00:17:35.840
[Guest]: And what is just the added the added ingredients to the profession that has nothing to do with

00:17:35.840 --> 00:17:37.560
[Guest]: actual value, right?

00:17:37.560 --> 00:17:42.440
[Guest]: So for example, lawyers are trained to write petitions in a certain kind of way.

00:17:42.440 --> 00:17:46.280
[Unknown]: Now, it's not very well written, it's not very logical, if you look at, you know, Supreme

00:17:46.280 --> 00:17:48.360
[Guest]: Court judgments, they're not well written.

00:17:48.360 --> 00:17:52.520
[Guest]: But one of the reasons they're written using a lot of jargon is to prevent non lawyers

00:17:52.520 --> 00:17:53.520
[Guest]: from writing it.

00:17:53.520 --> 00:17:57.400
[Guest]: Otherwise, the lawyers, why would you go to a lawyer, you can write your own petition,

00:17:57.400 --> 00:17:58.400
[Guest]: right?

00:17:58.400 --> 00:18:03.360
[Guest]: Academia is like that, you have like entire disciplines like to focus on jargon, because

00:18:03.360 --> 00:18:06.400
[Unknown]: if they, you know, if they were very clear about what they were trying to say, people

00:18:06.400 --> 00:18:10.040
[Guest]: will say, why are we paying this, you know, why are we paying the salary?

00:18:10.040 --> 00:18:15.480
[Guest]: So it's given me I think, luckily for me, I and so I don't have to, you know, put myself

00:18:15.480 --> 00:18:16.480
[Unknown]: in a box that way.

00:18:16.480 --> 00:18:19.920
[Unknown]: I mean, and I'm very proud of that, I think you're like that, you know, somebody says,

00:18:19.920 --> 00:18:20.920
[Guest]: are you a blogger?

00:18:20.920 --> 00:18:21.920
[Guest]: Are you an advertising?

00:18:21.920 --> 00:18:22.920
[Guest]: Are you a podcaster?

00:18:22.920 --> 00:18:26.280
[Guest]: You know, I don't think you think of yourself that way.

00:18:26.280 --> 00:18:27.280
[Guest]: And that's quite liberating.

00:18:27.280 --> 00:18:28.280
[Guest]: You know,

00:18:28.280 --> 00:18:31.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, in retrospect, at least in my case, it seems like a feature and not a bug.

00:18:31.960 --> 00:18:37.000
[Amit Varma]: But at the time, who knows, I do intend to, you know, explore more of your personal journey.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:39.960
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, we'll get deep into the book as well.

00:18:39.960 --> 00:18:44.840
[Amit Varma]: But before that, you know, there's a question I'd save for, you know, in part of in my list

00:18:44.840 --> 00:18:48.980
[Amit Varma]: of closing questions, which are more broad, but it kind of comes up.

00:18:48.980 --> 00:18:50.320
[Amit Varma]: So I'll mention it again.

00:18:50.320 --> 00:18:53.800
[Amit Varma]: And this actually goes contrary to the last point that I raised.

00:18:53.800 --> 00:18:59.320
[Amit Varma]: And it's a question about whether there is something specific in the drift of political

00:18:59.320 --> 00:19:02.120
[Amit Varma]: movements that is inevitable.

00:19:02.120 --> 00:19:07.880
[Amit Varma]: And the question sort of struck me first, when I was reading about what happened right

00:19:07.880 --> 00:19:13.120
[Amit Varma]: after Gandhiji's assassination, where, you know, obviously, Godse had once been part

00:19:13.120 --> 00:19:15.280
[Amit Varma]: of the RSS, but not for a long time.

00:19:15.280 --> 00:19:18.520
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, it's very clear, the RSS had no role to play.

00:19:18.520 --> 00:19:21.960
[Amit Varma]: And secondly, while the RSS was banned, the Hindu Mahasabha wasn't banned, partly because

00:19:21.960 --> 00:19:25.880
[Amit Varma]: of course, Shamab Prasad Mukherjee was in the cabinet, but also because the past that

00:19:25.880 --> 00:19:30.440
[Amit Varma]: we realized that even though these people were in the Hindu Mahasabha, they were a sort

00:19:30.440 --> 00:19:33.320
[Amit Varma]: of an extremist faction of it.

00:19:33.320 --> 00:19:37.520
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you know, there's no need to blame the whole party or the movement for

00:19:37.520 --> 00:19:38.520
[Amit Varma]: it.

00:19:38.520 --> 00:19:43.440
[Amit Varma]: But when I look at modern times, what also appears to me to be the case is that within

00:19:43.440 --> 00:19:50.480
[Amit Varma]: the BJP also, you have sort of this move towards the extremes in the sense that you get from

00:19:50.480 --> 00:19:56.520
[Amit Varma]: Shamab Prasad to Vajpayee to Advani to Modi to Shah to perhaps Adityanath and so on.

00:19:56.520 --> 00:20:01.440
[Amit Varma]: And this seems to be a drift that, you know, when you think about it is perfectly rational,

00:20:01.440 --> 00:20:05.600
[Amit Varma]: because you can't whip up your foot soldiers with moderation, you whip them up with by

00:20:05.600 --> 00:20:09.880
[Amit Varma]: getting more and more extreme, even within a party, that's perhaps how you compete.

00:20:09.880 --> 00:20:14.760
[Amit Varma]: Even within social media, when you look at how ideological echo chambers are formed,

00:20:14.760 --> 00:20:19.320
[Amit Varma]: and what you need to raise your, to signal your virtue in those echo chambers that you

00:20:19.320 --> 00:20:24.160
[Amit Varma]: belong to, it seems that a drift towards extremism is inevitable.

00:20:24.160 --> 00:20:30.440
[Amit Varma]: So in any ideological party or group, do you think the drift towards extremism is inevitable?

00:20:30.440 --> 00:20:35.060
[Amit Varma]: Or am I just or is it just the availability heuristic that these examples are coming to

00:20:35.060 --> 00:20:36.060
[Amit Varma]: my mind?

00:20:36.060 --> 00:20:37.060
[Guest]: Because I've just read your book?

00:20:37.060 --> 00:20:39.720
[Guest]: No, no, you're definitely on to something, right?

00:20:39.720 --> 00:20:43.680
[Guest]: Which is that that has been the general trajectory you see of the BJP.

00:20:43.680 --> 00:20:44.680
[Guest]: So I think that's like a fact.

00:20:44.680 --> 00:20:45.680
[Guest]: Right?

00:20:45.680 --> 00:20:47.560
[Guest]: So let's just see why that is the case.

00:20:47.560 --> 00:20:52.040
[Guest]: One is I don't think it's a, it's a constant move towards extremism, because even in this

00:20:52.040 --> 00:20:55.200
[Guest]: 100 year history, you've had a lot of ups and downs, right?

00:20:55.200 --> 00:21:02.200
[Guest]: So to give you an example, between 1986 and 1995, or 1994, the BJP was in a more quote

00:21:02.200 --> 00:21:04.560
[Guest]: unquote extremist or radical mode.

00:21:04.560 --> 00:21:10.480
[Guest]: But after that, between 95, 96, all the way to I would say even 2014, it was in a much

00:21:10.480 --> 00:21:12.360
[Unknown]: more moderate mode, right?

00:21:12.360 --> 00:21:15.280
[Unknown]: So you do have a little bit of a yin and yang, right?

00:21:15.280 --> 00:21:19.960
[Guest]: And I argue that a lot of that has to do with electoral politics, in the sense that you're

00:21:19.960 --> 00:21:22.840
[Guest]: trying to understand what the mood is of the voter.

00:21:22.840 --> 00:21:24.440
[Guest]: So you have these ups and downs.

00:21:24.440 --> 00:21:31.520
[Guest]: So that said, I think that this general trajectory you're talking about, about the BJP or Janssang

00:21:31.520 --> 00:21:36.720
[Guest]: BJP has a lot to do Amit with, you know, and I make this point repeatedly in the book that

00:21:36.720 --> 00:21:44.640
[Guest]: the, especially after the murder of the Mahatma, Hindu nationalism is on back foot, you know,

00:21:44.640 --> 00:21:49.560
[Guest]: it is untouchable, you know, nobody wants to, you know, have anything to do with it.

00:21:49.560 --> 00:21:55.480
[Guest]: And so I think that is the period that socializes Vajpayee and Advani, you know, that between,

00:21:55.480 --> 00:21:59.640
[Guest]: you know, after the murder of the Mahatma, Hindu nationalism has to always kind of, you

00:21:59.640 --> 00:22:05.400
[Guest]: know, whatever its private feelings, right, it has to kind of merge with the larger parliamentary

00:22:05.400 --> 00:22:07.240
[Guest]: opposition.

00:22:07.240 --> 00:22:12.680
[Guest]: And I think today you have a very different majority that Narendra Modi enjoys, like at

00:22:12.680 --> 00:22:17.440
[Guest]: the height of his power, Vajpayee only had 170 to 180 seats, right?

00:22:17.440 --> 00:22:18.440
[Guest]: Something like that.

00:22:18.440 --> 00:22:24.880
[Guest]: This is in the, you know, the 98 and 99 elections, Narendra Modi has a clear majority, he doesn't

00:22:24.880 --> 00:22:28.960
[Guest]: need the Shiv Sena, he doesn't need the Akali, he doesn't need a simple ally.

00:22:28.960 --> 00:22:34.960
[Guest]: A lot of it has to do with that background and really to understand Advani and Vajpayee,

00:22:34.960 --> 00:22:41.400
[Guest]: you have to understand that the circumstances that they were doing politics in broadly required

00:22:41.400 --> 00:22:44.360
[Guest]: a Hindu nationalism that had to appear moderate, right?

00:22:44.360 --> 00:22:48.720
[Guest]: There were, of course, exceptions like the Rath Yatra, etc, etc.

00:22:48.720 --> 00:22:50.840
[Guest]: I think those times have changed now.

00:22:50.840 --> 00:22:55.760
[Guest]: So I won't, you know, and who knows, you know, in the future, if you have certain demographic

00:22:55.760 --> 00:23:02.000
[Guest]: changes, where the Hindu voter is much less radical, you may have a much less radical

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:03.000
[Guest]: Hindu politics.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:07.440
[Guest]: Because you've seen that before, Amit, like, you know, I argue in the book that the 1920s

00:23:07.440 --> 00:23:12.720
[Guest]: were a period where you had Hindu and Muslim anxiety and sort of the core argument of the

00:23:12.720 --> 00:23:16.520
[Guest]: book is that it's driven by the introduction of elections, right?

00:23:16.520 --> 00:23:21.760
[Guest]: But what you have is a moderate Hindu leader, namely Mohandas Gandhi, who is a Hindu leader,

00:23:21.760 --> 00:23:22.760
[Guest]: right?

00:23:22.760 --> 00:23:27.400
[Guest]: And I can't stress that enough, when he passes away in 1948, when he's murdered, Mohamad Ali

00:23:27.400 --> 00:23:32.200
[Guest]: Jinnah now in Pakistan famously says a great leader of the Hindu community has died, right?

00:23:32.200 --> 00:23:36.480
[Guest]: I mean, Gandhi's language, his dress was a, you know, all of that was Hindu, except he

00:23:36.480 --> 00:23:37.480
[Guest]: wasn't anti-Muslim.

00:23:37.480 --> 00:23:41.960
[Guest]: That was and he was able to moderate those fears, right?

00:23:41.960 --> 00:23:46.720
[Guest]: But in 1980s, you know, when you had Hindu anxiety, once again, in the air, you didn't

00:23:46.720 --> 00:23:48.640
[Guest]: have a moderate Hindu leader, right?

00:23:48.640 --> 00:23:53.040
[Guest]: So therefore, you have you ended up with much more radicalization, and that just goes back

00:23:53.040 --> 00:23:57.240
[Guest]: to the first thing we were discussing, Amit, that, you know, to understand politics, you

00:23:57.240 --> 00:24:01.160
[Guest]: have to, it's a complex game, you have to understand this interaction between, you know,

00:24:01.160 --> 00:24:07.120
[Guest]: so the nature of the voter matters, but leaders can often sort of tamper that down or exaggerate

00:24:07.120 --> 00:24:08.120
[Guest]: it.

00:24:08.120 --> 00:24:09.560
[Guest]: And there's no simple answer to that question.

00:24:09.560 --> 00:24:14.800
[Guest]: And you have to look at focus at particular events to see what is going on there.

00:24:14.800 --> 00:24:18.040
[Amit Varma]: So just kind of thinking aloud and carrying on from there, you know, while you point out

00:24:18.040 --> 00:24:24.800
[Amit Varma]: that there was an ebb and flow from say, the 80s onwards, until now, it is also the case

00:24:24.800 --> 00:24:29.320
[Amit Varma]: that that ebb and flow might have been in the politics itself, that is in the supply

00:24:29.320 --> 00:24:34.600
[Amit Varma]: side of the political marketplace, but in the demand side of the marketplace, it just

00:24:34.600 --> 00:24:38.960
[Amit Varma]: continued down the road of extremism in the sense of the reason Vajpayee was replaced

00:24:38.960 --> 00:24:44.280
[Amit Varma]: was because he didn't get that he was moving towards this moderate path of Gandhi and socialism

00:24:44.280 --> 00:24:48.640
[Amit Varma]: as he called it, and then, you know, after 84, he had to be replaced because they did

00:24:48.640 --> 00:24:49.800
[Amit Varma]: so badly.

00:24:49.800 --> 00:24:54.960
[Amit Varma]: And you know, then Advani was forced to take the party in the sort of other direction.

00:24:54.960 --> 00:24:59.920
[Amit Varma]: And I'm also struck by this interesting Amit Shah quote from your book where Amit Shah

00:24:59.920 --> 00:25:06.040
[Amit Varma]: in 2019 is asked about the difference between the pair of Atal Bihari Vajpayee and LK Advani

00:25:06.040 --> 00:25:08.040
[Amit Varma]: and himself and Narendra Modi.

00:25:08.040 --> 00:25:12.640
[Amit Varma]: And you quote him as saying, quote, they never believed that fully waving the Hindutva flag

00:25:12.640 --> 00:25:14.000
[Amit Varma]: could win them votes.

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:17.040
[Amit Varma]: This is a difference between us and them, stop quote.

00:25:17.040 --> 00:25:23.000
[Amit Varma]: So in a sense, you know, even the move towards Hindutva that, you know, Advani and Vajpayee

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:29.920
[Amit Varma]: seem to go towards seems kind of reactive to what they feel will win them votes, and

00:25:29.920 --> 00:25:35.520
[Amit Varma]: a correction of the previous mistake at not recognizing that, whereas, you know, Shah's

00:25:35.520 --> 00:25:42.280
[Amit Varma]: drift seems to be that he and Modi are more of true believers and those guys were so so

00:25:42.280 --> 00:25:47.560
[Guest]: any I think that's right, but that still goes to the demand, at least in part amid the demand

00:25:47.560 --> 00:25:52.920
[Guest]: side part of the argument, look, the creation of a unified Hindu vote bank today, right,

00:25:52.920 --> 00:25:59.080
[Guest]: which is that is really the big story of 21st century India, where the BJP is not an upper

00:25:59.080 --> 00:26:03.160
[Unknown]: class party, because an upper class party could get 20% of the votes, right?

00:26:03.160 --> 00:26:06.960
[Unknown]: Many of my left liberal friends go on and on about how and I'm saying, look, if it's

00:26:06.960 --> 00:26:10.200
[Unknown]: up, I think they don't know if it's an upper class party that you're not going to win a

00:26:10.200 --> 00:26:11.880
[Unknown]: single election in India.

00:26:11.880 --> 00:26:16.120
[Guest]: You can't, you know, and if you wear a mask for 100 years, you end up with an OBC prime

00:26:16.120 --> 00:26:18.240
[Guest]: minister and a Dalit president.

00:26:18.240 --> 00:26:24.720
[Guest]: And that consolidation that the BJP is having, for example, in the 2019 elections, Modi won

00:26:24.720 --> 00:26:30.360
[Guest]: more Dalit, OBC and tribal than anyone else, right than anyone else with a plurality than

00:26:30.360 --> 00:26:31.360
[Guest]: anyone else.

00:26:31.360 --> 00:26:36.280
[Guest]: This is the big story to me of the 20th of the late 20th and early 20th century, because

00:26:36.280 --> 00:26:40.520
[Unknown]: that changes the nature radically changes the nature of politics, including the supply

00:26:40.520 --> 00:26:46.240
[Guest]: side, you know, a lot of the supply of politics in India is premised on the fact that no group

00:26:46.240 --> 00:26:51.960
[Guest]: in no voting group in India is more than 15-16%, you know, and a lot of the politics is based

00:26:51.960 --> 00:26:57.320
[Guest]: on that presumption and the kind of internal party coalitions you can get or external coalitions.

00:26:57.320 --> 00:27:02.040
[Guest]: Now, given that, you know, that social reality is changing in India, you're going to get

00:27:02.040 --> 00:27:03.640
[Guest]: a very different form of politics.

00:27:03.640 --> 00:27:08.480
[Guest]: Part of the reason that social reality has changed is a hundred year project of the RSS

00:27:08.480 --> 00:27:13.600
[Guest]: because as I point out, you know, from the 1920s itself, Savarkar understands that the

00:27:13.600 --> 00:27:17.760
[Guest]: social unification of Hindus has an immediate electoral benefit.

00:27:17.760 --> 00:27:23.480
[Guest]: So in other words, political individualism, right, can be used if you have a social majority.

00:27:23.480 --> 00:27:25.000
[Guest]: He understands that, right.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:28.160
[Guest]: So part of it is the work of the RSS, etc, etc.

00:27:28.160 --> 00:27:32.800
[Guest]: But part of it, I mean, they are ground up forces like urbanization, right, where you

00:27:32.800 --> 00:27:38.400
[Guest]: have, you know, Hindus of various castes moving from the village to the city, and their caste

00:27:38.400 --> 00:27:42.920
[Guest]: identity gets diluted just a little bit, but their religious identity gets heightened,

00:27:42.920 --> 00:27:47.560
[Guest]: you know, you're seeing that, and that is not, that is likely to be a modernization

00:27:47.560 --> 00:27:51.360
[Guest]: story, which is a bottom-up story rather than just top-down, right.

00:27:51.360 --> 00:27:56.240
[Unknown]: And so while I hear you, right, that leaders matter, I mean, I mean, you know, this is

00:27:56.240 --> 00:27:58.120
[Guest]: my second kind of biography.

00:27:58.120 --> 00:28:04.240
[Guest]: But in this book, I'm much more alive to the fact that, you know, the story of Hindu nationalism

00:28:04.240 --> 00:28:10.200
[Guest]: is a story of Indians and of Indians changing as much as it is a supply-side story.

00:28:10.200 --> 00:28:13.720
[Amit Varma]: So I'm fascinated by something you just said, which is, of course, I mean, one is a truism

00:28:13.720 --> 00:28:18.240
[Amit Varma]: that caste identities do get diluted a little bit when you come to cities, because larger

00:28:18.240 --> 00:28:22.040
[Amit Varma]: economic networks, greater costs of discrimination and all of that.

00:28:22.040 --> 00:28:25.640
[Amit Varma]: But you also said that religious identities get heightened.

00:28:25.640 --> 00:28:26.640
[Amit Varma]: Now why is that?

00:28:26.640 --> 00:28:31.960
[Amit Varma]: Is that sort of because of the ghettoization that can sometimes happen within cities or,

00:28:31.960 --> 00:28:33.520
[Guest]: you know, can you explain that for me?

00:28:33.520 --> 00:28:37.840
[Guest]: You know, Amit, one of the things I take very seriously as a researcher is that if you haven't

00:28:37.840 --> 00:28:40.800
[Guest]: researched something, don't give gyaan, you know.

00:28:40.800 --> 00:28:45.720
[Guest]: And this is something that I have as a kind of background music in the book, right.

00:28:45.720 --> 00:28:47.440
[Guest]: And it's based on secondary sources.

00:28:47.440 --> 00:28:51.640
[Unknown]: It's not primary work that I did, like I did like about 200 interviews.

00:28:51.640 --> 00:28:56.000
[Guest]: You know, I did a lot of archival work, both, you know, the party archives as well.

00:28:56.000 --> 00:28:59.840
[Guest]: But this is something that, and frankly, I don't think there's very good material to

00:28:59.840 --> 00:29:01.320
[Guest]: understand what you said.

00:29:01.320 --> 00:29:04.200
[Guest]: It's a reality that is unfolding in our eyes.

00:29:04.200 --> 00:29:08.480
[Guest]: So I have some access to secondary literature, but I, you know, I would rather like, you

00:29:08.480 --> 00:29:13.640
[Guest]: know, tell the listener something that I know confidently rather than speculate, you know.

00:29:13.640 --> 00:29:15.440
[Guest]: So I can sense it.

00:29:15.440 --> 00:29:19.400
[Unknown]: And I think we, you know, academics typically take about 10, 15 years after you send something

00:29:19.400 --> 00:29:21.720
[Unknown]: to come up with the answer.

00:29:21.720 --> 00:29:27.400
[Guest]: But I think it's the big question in India today, you know, which is the social basis

00:29:27.400 --> 00:29:30.200
[Guest]: for the dominance of the BJP.

00:29:30.200 --> 00:29:35.360
[Guest]: And too many people who tend to portray Modi as just a fascist, you know, as just like,

00:29:35.360 --> 00:29:39.800
[Guest]: you know, an event manager, they miss that this is the raw power of Hindu nationalism.

00:29:39.800 --> 00:29:44.120
[Guest]: And I think, you know, maybe this is the next project that I focus on, which is to look

00:29:44.120 --> 00:29:48.000
[Guest]: at the social basis of Hindu political unity as it were.

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:52.160
[Guest]: But at least for me, I mean, it's a bit early for me to sort of speak confidently.

00:29:52.160 --> 00:29:53.160
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough.

00:29:53.160 --> 00:29:58.200
[Amit Varma]: I'll take this opportunity to book a session with you in advance for 2035.

00:29:58.200 --> 00:30:01.800
[Amit Varma]: So when you have figured this out, kindly, kindly come on my show.

00:30:01.800 --> 00:30:05.840
[Amit Varma]: And let us all know, let's now you know, after these little digressions, and we'll come back

00:30:05.840 --> 00:30:08.320
[Amit Varma]: to this to discuss all of this in much more detail.

00:30:08.320 --> 00:30:12.360
[Amit Varma]: I want to go back to your personal life, because it strikes me that, you know, the work one

00:30:12.360 --> 00:30:16.200
[Amit Varma]: does is shaped by the training that one gets and the experiences one has.

00:30:16.200 --> 00:30:19.960
[Amit Varma]: And that in turn, then, you know, the work one does shapes one as a person.

00:30:19.960 --> 00:30:24.400
[Amit Varma]: So now you've done all these different things, you're first trained in law, then you go into

00:30:24.400 --> 00:30:27.640
[Amit Varma]: journalism, then you go into political science and all of this.

00:30:27.640 --> 00:30:29.560
[Amit Varma]: Then you write these books.

00:30:29.560 --> 00:30:32.120
[Amit Varma]: What's been the impetus behind all of this?

00:30:32.120 --> 00:30:37.040
[Amit Varma]: Like, have there been these big problems driving you or have you just moved on from interest

00:30:37.040 --> 00:30:40.280
[Amit Varma]: to interest at different points in time when you've fallen in love with something else

00:30:40.280 --> 00:30:41.280
[Amit Varma]: to do?

00:30:41.280 --> 00:30:42.640
[Amit Varma]: Like, why did you become a journalist?

00:30:42.640 --> 00:30:44.800
[Amit Varma]: Why did you then stop being a journalist?

00:30:44.800 --> 00:30:46.040
[Amit Varma]: Give me a sense of that journey.

00:30:46.040 --> 00:30:47.520
[Guest]: Oh, it's love and passion.

00:30:47.520 --> 00:30:50.400
[Guest]: I mean, you know, it's not like logically done.

00:30:50.400 --> 00:30:54.400
[Guest]: So for example, after this book, and already like it's not sales wise doing very, very

00:30:54.400 --> 00:30:58.400
[Guest]: well, even though it's been only a week, there'll be tremendous pressure on me to write on like

00:30:58.400 --> 00:30:59.960
[Guest]: Sonia Gandhi or something like that.

00:30:59.960 --> 00:31:03.840
[Guest]: And look, if I don't have passion about it, or if I don't see a light at the end of the

00:31:03.840 --> 00:31:08.040
[Guest]: tunnel, I just know because here's the thing, you know, when you when the book comes out,

00:31:08.040 --> 00:31:11.960
[Guest]: you know, I keep telling my students also, you get all this publicity, you know, you

00:31:11.960 --> 00:31:16.760
[Guest]: get to come on podcast show, but that's really like one month of fun for three years of like

00:31:16.760 --> 00:31:18.120
[Guest]: really boring work.

00:31:18.120 --> 00:31:23.000
[Guest]: So unless you're driven by passion, you know, for the subject itself, you can't sustain

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:27.560
[Guest]: yourself and also, I mean, readers come to know, you know, they come to know very quickly

00:31:27.560 --> 00:31:31.560
[Unknown]: whether you're trying to sell them a lemon, or you're actually passionate about a subject,

00:31:31.560 --> 00:31:36.280
[Unknown]: you know, and even if people disagree, they realize that you're genuinely motivated, they

00:31:36.280 --> 00:31:40.440
[Guest]: can't read us again, and readers can sense this very well, you know.

00:31:40.440 --> 00:31:46.040
[Guest]: So I've always, I mean, at least the way I've seen myself is that if I like an idea, I try

00:31:46.040 --> 00:31:47.040
[Guest]: to do it.

00:31:47.040 --> 00:31:51.720
[Guest]: For example, you know, given my academic career, you know, the logical pressure should be I

00:31:51.720 --> 00:31:55.920
[Guest]: should, you know, publish in obscure journals, you know, I should that kind of thing.

00:31:55.920 --> 00:31:59.360
[Guest]: But if it doesn't give me happiness, I find I'm not very good at it.

00:31:59.360 --> 00:32:03.640
[Guest]: So I might as well do something I'm passionate about, because I can sustain myself and I'm

00:32:03.640 --> 00:32:04.640
[Guest]: good at it.

00:32:04.640 --> 00:32:05.640
[Guest]: Right?

00:32:05.640 --> 00:32:09.080
[Guest]: I think, you know, I went into National Law School Bangalore, because, you know, frankly,

00:32:09.080 --> 00:32:12.920
[Guest]: after my 12th standard, I didn't, you know, the first question from middle class background

00:32:12.920 --> 00:32:13.920
[Guest]: is, do you want to be an engineer?

00:32:13.920 --> 00:32:14.920
[Unknown]: Do you want to be a doctor?

00:32:14.920 --> 00:32:15.920
[Unknown]: Right?

00:32:15.920 --> 00:32:18.680
[Unknown]: And, you know, if you don't want to be any of this, you know, how about a chartered accountant,

00:32:18.680 --> 00:32:21.760
[Guest]: right, give you a little bit of added flavor to your life.

00:32:21.760 --> 00:32:23.600
[Guest]: And I didn't want to be any of this, right.

00:32:23.600 --> 00:32:28.920
[Guest]: And then my dad, who was, you know, totally chilled out on the matter, he got the National

00:32:28.920 --> 00:32:33.280
[Guest]: Law School Bangalore entrance test, and it had a lot of GK, you know, quiz questions.

00:32:33.280 --> 00:32:35.000
[Guest]: And I always like quizzing and stuff like that.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:38.880
[Guest]: I said, Look, if the entrance test is any judge, this is what I want to do, you know,

00:32:38.880 --> 00:32:39.880
[Guest]: so I did it.

00:32:39.880 --> 00:32:45.000
[Guest]: But I always thought of it as a good undergraduate degree, and I was kind of a refuge from, you

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:48.080
[Guest]: know, being forced to become an engineer in some sense.

00:32:48.080 --> 00:32:51.840
[Guest]: And the benefit of National Law School Bangalore is that by the time I joined it, thanks to

00:32:51.840 --> 00:32:56.440
[Guest]: liberalization, etc, there were these fancy corporate law jobs, which at that time were

00:32:56.440 --> 00:33:00.840
[Guest]: giving something like a lakh a month at that time, right, or maybe a little less.

00:33:00.840 --> 00:33:04.760
[Guest]: And so that gave me confidence that look, even if I fool around with this that I don't

00:33:04.760 --> 00:33:07.960
[Unknown]: want to do, I'll, you know, maybe I won't get a great corporate law job, maybe I won't

00:33:07.960 --> 00:33:11.040
[Guest]: be unhappy, but it gives a sense of security, right.

00:33:11.040 --> 00:33:14.560
[Guest]: And these kinds of security is very important when you want to, you know, pick especially

00:33:14.560 --> 00:33:15.920
[Guest]: in India.

00:33:15.920 --> 00:33:20.360
[Guest]: So I finished law, and I've done quite a few internships when I was in National Law School

00:33:20.360 --> 00:33:21.360
[Guest]: Bangalore.

00:33:21.360 --> 00:33:25.480
[Guest]: And, I mean, I'd gone to court and all and I'd worked, I'd done a corporate law internship,

00:33:25.480 --> 00:33:30.080
[Guest]: I'd done an education internship, then none of it really excited me, you know, and I think

00:33:30.080 --> 00:33:34.400
[Unknown]: I must really thank my parents that, you know, that, you know, when relatives or friends

00:33:34.400 --> 00:33:36.600
[Guest]: would ask, what do you want to do?

00:33:36.600 --> 00:33:40.640
[Guest]: And I didn't have an answer, it did not make my parents anxious, you know, they just let

00:33:40.640 --> 00:33:42.520
[Unknown]: me kind of breathe.

00:33:42.520 --> 00:33:48.200
[Guest]: But the one thing that law taught me, I mean, was the focus on getting facts and sequence

00:33:48.200 --> 00:33:49.200
[Guest]: right.

00:33:49.200 --> 00:33:53.800
[Guest]: For example, you just pointed out, you know, the way I asked the question, who killed Mahatma

00:33:53.800 --> 00:33:54.800
[Unknown]: Gandhi?

00:33:54.800 --> 00:33:55.800
[Guest]: Right?

00:33:55.800 --> 00:34:00.040
[Guest]: Now, it's like, my legal training has hugely helped that, which is to look at the judgments,

00:34:00.040 --> 00:34:01.040
[Guest]: right?

00:34:01.040 --> 00:34:05.600
[Guest]: To make an assessment of the difference between Hindu Mahasabha and RSS, right?

00:34:05.600 --> 00:34:08.360
[Guest]: And Savarkar, because that's a separate question, right?

00:34:08.360 --> 00:34:13.320
[Guest]: And look at the various, you know, forum in which Savarkar was judged, right, including

00:34:13.320 --> 00:34:16.800
[Guest]: in 1966, much after his death, etc, etc.

00:34:16.800 --> 00:34:20.520
[Guest]: That is definitely my legal training, you know, and I'm proud that both this book and

00:34:20.520 --> 00:34:25.480
[Guest]: the Naseem Arao book is broadly bulletproof, in that you can't, you know, that no, I'm

00:34:25.480 --> 00:34:29.400
[Guest]: sure you have disagreements, Amit, about the book, but there aren't facts there that you

00:34:29.400 --> 00:34:34.240
[Guest]: will, you know, easy bloopers, easy facts, all of that is the obsession with legal training.

00:34:34.240 --> 00:34:37.760
[Guest]: And to give you an example, I mean, lots of people read drafts of this book, including

00:34:37.760 --> 00:34:40.160
[Guest]: four or five of my close law friends.

00:34:40.160 --> 00:34:44.200
[Guest]: And these are friends who charge like 60,000 rupees for an hour of reading, you know, that's

00:34:44.200 --> 00:34:49.920
[Guest]: basically, so their eye is very, very good for detail, you know, and I would say I'm

00:34:49.920 --> 00:34:56.000
[Guest]: a bad version of that, which is that I don't, you know, my value is not 60,000 rupees for

00:34:56.000 --> 00:35:01.280
[Guest]: an hour of reading, but certainly an eye for the detail of the text, getting the facts

00:35:01.280 --> 00:35:06.080
[Guest]: right, crossing the T's, dotting the I's, and look, you know, as controversial a topic

00:35:06.080 --> 00:35:10.440
[Guest]: like this, Amit, it's very important, because ultimately, it's what builds credibility with

00:35:10.440 --> 00:35:15.200
[Guest]: the reader, which is, to me, everything about writing a book, that I think my legal training

00:35:15.200 --> 00:35:16.200
[Guest]: is very good.

00:35:16.200 --> 00:35:18.080
[Guest]: I ran away from the law and etc, etc.

00:35:18.080 --> 00:35:23.000
[Guest]: But if I could give my view to it, it's an obsession with facts, obsession with getting

00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:29.640
[Guest]: it right, you know, an obsession with exercising judgment on facts that are not 100%, because

00:35:29.640 --> 00:35:34.080
[Guest]: lawyers sometimes have to reconstruct a little bit based on a preponderance of evidence,

00:35:34.080 --> 00:35:35.080
[Guest]: right?

00:35:35.080 --> 00:35:38.840
[Guest]: So I noticed that sensibility is very much a lawyer's sensibility.

00:35:38.840 --> 00:35:43.520
[Guest]: That said, I hope Amit, you know, you can tell your listeners that I don't write like

00:35:43.520 --> 00:35:48.040
[Guest]: a lawyer, I hope you can say that, that comes from my journalism, I spent a couple of years

00:35:48.040 --> 00:35:50.400
[Guest]: working for Indian Express.

00:35:50.400 --> 00:35:52.960
[Guest]: And I was editing a lot of people's work.

00:35:52.960 --> 00:35:57.960
[Guest]: So that part of the book, which is that, you know, you open the book, and then I want you

00:35:57.960 --> 00:36:02.120
[Guest]: to kind of not put the book down, that's my name, right.

00:36:02.120 --> 00:36:05.200
[Guest]: And all of that comes from journalism, for sure.

00:36:05.200 --> 00:36:09.600
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, I mean, I will, in fact, tell my listeners that this is a wonderfully readable

00:36:09.600 --> 00:36:10.600
[Amit Varma]: book.

00:36:10.600 --> 00:36:15.600
[Amit Varma]: And indeed, you know, unputdownable for me, I did read it in sort of two stretches.

00:36:15.600 --> 00:36:19.680
[Amit Varma]: My other question is that this book is also very interesting, because it's simultaneously

00:36:19.680 --> 00:36:24.120
[Amit Varma]: a work of history and journalism, in the sense that it's covering a political movement that's

00:36:24.120 --> 00:36:25.820
[Amit Varma]: been 100 years in the making.

00:36:25.820 --> 00:36:29.420
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, that political movement is at its peak now.

00:36:29.420 --> 00:36:33.200
[Amit Varma]: And some of his protagonists are at their peak now, though, of course, it's, you know,

00:36:33.200 --> 00:36:38.200
[Amit Varma]: it's a book about the BJP before Modi, but yet he does play a significant part, sort

00:36:38.200 --> 00:36:39.600
[Amit Varma]: of towards the end of it.

00:36:39.600 --> 00:36:43.680
[Amit Varma]: Now, you know, in terms of you've already spoken about how your legal training helped

00:36:43.680 --> 00:36:50.560
[Amit Varma]: you in the work that you did, and in the rigor that that gave you, now give me a sense of

00:36:50.560 --> 00:36:54.560
[Amit Varma]: how you went about doing this book and how journalistic rigor and academic rigor came

00:36:54.560 --> 00:36:55.560
[Amit Varma]: together.

00:36:55.560 --> 00:36:59.920
[Amit Varma]: And what is, you know, in your process of writing the book, how different was it from

00:36:59.920 --> 00:37:04.480
[Amit Varma]: how a pure journalist would approach it or a pure academic would approach it, though

00:37:04.480 --> 00:37:07.680
[Amit Varma]: one could argue that in these days, neither of them can be pure, but you get what I'm

00:37:07.680 --> 00:37:08.680
[Guest]: saying?

00:37:08.680 --> 00:37:09.680
[Guest]: Yeah, no.

00:37:09.680 --> 00:37:14.640
[Guest]: So let me first begin by saying that, I think journalism really taught me two things, which

00:37:14.640 --> 00:37:17.560
[Guest]: has helped me in this book and the previous one.

00:37:17.560 --> 00:37:23.200
[Guest]: The first thing Amit is that it taught me to, it really taught me that the story is

00:37:23.200 --> 00:37:27.320
[Guest]: more important than you are, right, or that story is more important than I am.

00:37:27.320 --> 00:37:31.000
[Guest]: And this is something that academics don't get, that the reality is not created in their

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:35.800
[Guest]: mind, in their university, in their ivory tower, there is a reality out there and, you

00:37:35.800 --> 00:37:40.960
[Guest]: know, we have a variety of tools to try to understand that reality, make sense of that.

00:37:40.960 --> 00:37:44.200
[Guest]: We have to be very humble, very, very humble about that.

00:37:44.200 --> 00:37:49.200
[Guest]: And so I told myself that, look, if I'm writing a book on a BJP, my view on the BJP is irrelevant,

00:37:49.200 --> 00:37:50.200
[Guest]: right?

00:37:50.200 --> 00:37:54.160
[Guest]: And frankly, it's irrelevant to the reader, that's not why the reader is paying this money

00:37:54.160 --> 00:37:55.160
[Guest]: and reading the book.

00:37:55.160 --> 00:37:58.680
[Guest]: And that the phenomena is bigger than I am.

00:37:58.680 --> 00:38:03.440
[Guest]: So to give you a very simple manifestation of that, the only person who has a bigger

00:38:03.440 --> 00:38:06.320
[Guest]: ego than a source is the secretary of the source.

00:38:06.320 --> 00:38:09.560
[Guest]: And you know, we use a little bit of power, but we'll kind of make you know, and if you're

00:38:09.560 --> 00:38:13.760
[Guest]: the kind of person who bristles at that, you know, who doesn't like the fact that some

00:38:13.760 --> 00:38:18.600
[Guest]: junior functionary is making you wait for like two and a half hours, you know, in a

00:38:18.600 --> 00:38:22.000
[Guest]: smelly empty room, then you shouldn't be in this business.

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:26.560
[Guest]: And I learned that from journalism a lot, you know, I also learned Amit, because when

00:38:26.560 --> 00:38:31.560
[Guest]: I worked for Indian Express, Shekhar Gupta was the editor-in-chief.

00:38:31.560 --> 00:38:37.480
[Guest]: And I'm sure many of your listeners see Cut the Clutter, which is his iconic show right

00:38:37.480 --> 00:38:38.480
[Guest]: now.

00:38:38.480 --> 00:38:42.000
[Guest]: But he used to do that with us, we were all junior journalists there, and he used to kind

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:46.360
[Guest]: of just walk into the newsroom and tell us story after story after story, you know.

00:38:46.360 --> 00:38:51.480
[Guest]: And I think that really taught me that, look, there is a way in which you can tell deeper

00:38:51.480 --> 00:38:55.960
[Guest]: truths about Indian politics through an anecdotal story style.

00:38:55.960 --> 00:39:00.160
[Guest]: And he really taught me the importance of having a worm's eye view, you know, that he

00:39:00.160 --> 00:39:03.440
[Guest]: was in the room when Charan Singh was doing X, that kind of thing.

00:39:03.440 --> 00:39:07.400
[Guest]: And of course, it doesn't tell you much, but it also tells you a lot of things.

00:39:07.400 --> 00:39:11.480
[Guest]: In contrast to academia, it's very refreshing, it gives a freshness to it.

00:39:11.480 --> 00:39:14.720
[Guest]: And it gives a sense that, you know, something that you asked Amit right in the beginning

00:39:14.720 --> 00:39:20.040
[Guest]: that the moment matters, that in any given moment, you know, what will happen next is

00:39:20.040 --> 00:39:21.040
[Guest]: not fated.

00:39:21.040 --> 00:39:26.360
[Guest]: Sab likha hua nahi hai, you know, and he really, a story is really that, right, that A happened

00:39:26.360 --> 00:39:30.040
[Guest]: and B happened and C happened, and A and B and C need not follow chronologically.

00:39:30.040 --> 00:39:32.800
[Guest]: If they did, then it's not a story, you know.

00:39:32.800 --> 00:39:38.280
[Guest]: So I think both that, I think Express and journalism taught me to respect that the story

00:39:38.280 --> 00:39:43.000
[Guest]: is bigger than you and your prejudices, and the reader frankly doesn't care about me,

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:44.000
[Guest]: you know, who am I?

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:47.280
[Guest]: And that's why in the main body of the book, I don't use the word I at all.

00:39:47.280 --> 00:39:52.120
[Unknown]: I don't, you know, and I know that, like, lots of people are taught to do this nowadays.

00:39:52.120 --> 00:39:55.880
[Guest]: And I realized that then you're just writing for five of your friends, you know, then just

00:39:55.880 --> 00:39:59.280
[Guest]: send a private email, what are you writing a book for?

00:39:59.280 --> 00:40:03.840
[Guest]: So I think it's, and looking back, I just, when I teach, I keep pushing this on my students

00:40:03.840 --> 00:40:06.240
[Guest]: that, look, it's a hard thing to tell people, right?

00:40:06.240 --> 00:40:08.600
[Guest]: You are irrelevant, your story is relevant.

00:40:08.600 --> 00:40:13.240
[Guest]: And the second thing is, I think Shekhar Gupta taught me that to see politics like a worm,

00:40:13.240 --> 00:40:15.440
[Guest]: you know, from the ground level.

00:40:15.440 --> 00:40:17.680
[Guest]: And that mattered hugely to me, right?

00:40:17.680 --> 00:40:22.240
[Guest]: That said, I think, journalists tend to be very bad readers of text.

00:40:22.240 --> 00:40:23.640
[Guest]: So they're very good interviewers.

00:40:23.640 --> 00:40:28.560
[Guest]: But you know, when it comes to archives, when it comes to looking at text, when it comes

00:40:28.560 --> 00:40:32.920
[Guest]: to even reading newspapers, one of the things I do in this book is from the late 19th century

00:40:32.920 --> 00:40:38.800
[Guest]: itself, I refer to a lot of newspapers, journalists don't typically do that very well.

00:40:38.800 --> 00:40:43.600
[Guest]: And two is, I mean, I think journalists have a phobia from structural explanations.

00:40:43.600 --> 00:40:47.840
[Guest]: For them, everything is, you know, it goes the other extreme, everything is about like

00:40:47.840 --> 00:40:52.040
[Guest]: the person, you know, like, it's all about Vajpayee, or it's all about Advani, right?

00:40:52.040 --> 00:40:56.400
[Guest]: Or it's all about the particular head of the RSS at that time, rather than these boundaries,

00:40:56.400 --> 00:40:58.840
[Guest]: structural forces that also matter.

00:40:58.840 --> 00:41:01.280
[Unknown]: So I think academia has definitely taught me that.

00:41:01.280 --> 00:41:06.080
[Guest]: And I studied at Princeton University, which is, I would say one of the most boring places

00:41:06.080 --> 00:41:07.080
[Guest]: on earth.

00:41:07.080 --> 00:41:11.400
[Guest]: And looking back, you know, it's not a party town, at least for graduate students, it's

00:41:11.400 --> 00:41:12.400
[Guest]: really boring.

00:41:12.400 --> 00:41:17.600
[Guest]: It's like, not very close to a big city also, maybe New York is about an hour and a half

00:41:17.600 --> 00:41:18.600
[Guest]: away, two hours away.

00:41:18.600 --> 00:41:23.920
[Guest]: But what Princeton really taught me is that you got to take like academia, not as a as

00:41:23.920 --> 00:41:26.880
[Guest]: a social event, but like as a professional thing.

00:41:26.880 --> 00:41:30.960
[Guest]: I think some people I know, coming to academia, because you know, they can wear like nice

00:41:30.960 --> 00:41:34.680
[Guest]: kurtas and they can wear it, you know, it's a, it's an act of being, right?

00:41:34.680 --> 00:41:38.320
[Guest]: Why would you want to kind of wear a tie and sell soap somewhere you should.

00:41:38.320 --> 00:41:43.400
[Guest]: And Princeton just drove that out of me, that it's a brutal place like you have, like academia

00:41:43.400 --> 00:41:47.760
[Guest]: is about producing, it's about writing books, it's about writing articles, it's about going

00:41:47.760 --> 00:41:53.340
[Guest]: to the archives, it's about creating data in a thoroughly unromantic way, you know,

00:41:53.340 --> 00:41:56.880
[Guest]: so it totally took out the romance from from academia.

00:41:56.880 --> 00:42:00.600
[Guest]: And I would say that, on balance, it's a very good thing, you know, because this kind of

00:42:00.600 --> 00:42:05.200
[Unknown]: stuff is hard work, and if you don't have the appetite for that, then you end up making

00:42:05.200 --> 00:42:06.200
[Amit Varma]: mistakes.

00:42:06.200 --> 00:42:10.840
[Amit Varma]: No, no, I love your book, not only for his fluid prose, but also for what you just said

00:42:10.840 --> 00:42:13.480
[Amit Varma]: that I couldn't make out where you stood on any of the issues.

00:42:13.480 --> 00:42:14.840
[Amit Varma]: And I didn't really care.

00:42:14.840 --> 00:42:18.520
[Amit Varma]: Because the story was sort of riveting enough to keep me going.

00:42:18.520 --> 00:42:23.880
[Amit Varma]: Now, before we actually get to the book, one sort of final question, which sort of intrigues

00:42:23.880 --> 00:42:29.040
[Amit Varma]: me because knowledge management is also something that I think about a fair bit, which is that,

00:42:29.040 --> 00:42:33.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, do you have specific systems of knowledge management?

00:42:33.280 --> 00:42:36.880
[Amit Varma]: Because you're doing a lot of archival work, you're, you know, you're digging up a lot

00:42:36.880 --> 00:42:43.800
[Amit Varma]: of old sources as academics would at the same time, you're interviewing many people and,

00:42:43.800 --> 00:42:46.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, so how do you organize all of that material?

00:42:46.840 --> 00:42:49.520
[Amit Varma]: When does narrative sort of start to take shape?

00:42:49.520 --> 00:42:55.000
[Amit Varma]: How do you avoid the danger, which you clearly have of having a preset narrative in your

00:42:55.000 --> 00:42:58.640
[Guest]: head and then just finding the stuff that fits that?

00:42:58.640 --> 00:43:03.520
[Guest]: You know, these are questions that I obsess about endlessly, because the process creates

00:43:03.520 --> 00:43:04.520
[Guest]: the product.

00:43:04.520 --> 00:43:07.640
[Guest]: I mean, you know, there are very few mistakes in this book, because I created a process,

00:43:07.640 --> 00:43:09.360
[Guest]: what you call knowledge management.

00:43:09.360 --> 00:43:10.920
[Guest]: And there's no shortcut to that.

00:43:10.920 --> 00:43:14.880
[Unknown]: There's just no, it's not that it, you know, this, I think, Arundhati Roy said that, you

00:43:14.880 --> 00:43:18.720
[Guest]: know, when she began writing God of Small Things, she kind of began and then she ended,

00:43:18.720 --> 00:43:19.720
[Guest]: right?

00:43:19.720 --> 00:43:20.720
[Guest]: I don't think that works for most people.

00:43:20.720 --> 00:43:24.720
[Guest]: I go over, I see mistakes, so you create a process.

00:43:24.720 --> 00:43:28.800
[Guest]: For me, looking back, I mean, you know, when it happened, it happened intuitively, I would

00:43:28.800 --> 00:43:32.320
[Guest]: divide my knowledge management process into three phases.

00:43:32.320 --> 00:43:35.600
[Guest]: The first phase is that I had this idea, right?

00:43:35.600 --> 00:43:40.760
[Unknown]: And I began reading a lot around it, keeping an open mind, but reading what others have

00:43:40.760 --> 00:43:41.760
[Unknown]: written about it.

00:43:41.760 --> 00:43:45.760
[Guest]: So, for example, after the Nassim Rao book, you know, I said, maybe I should think about

00:43:45.760 --> 00:43:46.760
[Guest]: Vajpayee.

00:43:46.760 --> 00:43:50.960
[Guest]: And then I said, look, if you work on Vajpayee, I very quickly realized that Vajpayee and

00:43:50.960 --> 00:43:53.200
[Guest]: Advani were two sides of the same coin.

00:43:53.200 --> 00:43:58.200
[Guest]: So I was open enough that, okay, I was initially interested in Vajpayee, and initially I bought

00:43:58.200 --> 00:44:01.200
[Guest]: this idea that Vajpayee was this grand figure, right?

00:44:01.200 --> 00:44:06.320
[Guest]: Which, look, he is, but I just, you know, the book, as you've read, is also critical

00:44:06.320 --> 00:44:07.320
[Guest]: of him.

00:44:07.320 --> 00:44:08.320
[Unknown]: You know, it's not...

00:44:08.320 --> 00:44:12.480
[Unknown]: So while he is this grand figure, he's a man who's highly complex, he has a lot of contradictions

00:44:12.480 --> 00:44:13.480
[Guest]: within him.

00:44:13.480 --> 00:44:17.760
[Unknown]: So I'm glad I did that, which is I very quickly realized that it's actually a Jugalbandi story

00:44:17.760 --> 00:44:19.440
[Guest]: of Vajpayee and Advani.

00:44:19.440 --> 00:44:24.040
[Guest]: And then I realized, Amit, that unlike in the case of Nassim Rao, who I think was single-handedly

00:44:24.040 --> 00:44:29.840
[Unknown]: responsible for liberalization, Vajpayee and Advani's relationship cannot be understood

00:44:29.840 --> 00:44:33.440
[Guest]: without the context, which is the movement, which is Hindu nationalism.

00:44:33.440 --> 00:44:38.760
[Guest]: And the rise of Vajpayee and Advani mirrors the rise of Hindu nationalism, so then that's

00:44:38.760 --> 00:44:40.320
[Guest]: what became the structure of the book.

00:44:40.320 --> 00:44:44.960
[Guest]: But that was in my first phase of research where I'm kind of thinking about the idea

00:44:44.960 --> 00:44:49.520
[Guest]: and I'm reading and constantly modifying what this original idea should be.

00:44:49.520 --> 00:44:53.680
[Guest]: So while teaching, for example, Amit, I taught three courses at Ashoka University that had

00:44:53.680 --> 00:44:58.240
[Guest]: to do with parts of this, of Hindu nationalism, so that at least I could read what other people

00:44:58.240 --> 00:44:59.240
[Guest]: had written about it.

00:44:59.240 --> 00:45:03.520
[Guest]: That took, I would say, about a year or about seven, eight months, where I'm just talking,

00:45:03.520 --> 00:45:08.040
[Guest]: I'm meeting for lunch, many of the people who have come on your podcast, like Pratap

00:45:08.040 --> 00:45:12.760
[Guest]: Bhanu Mehta, for example, and I'm just shooting the breeze, you know, I'm like thinking about

00:45:12.760 --> 00:45:15.840
[Guest]: it and you know, when you're thinking about academic questions, you're both asking, is

00:45:15.840 --> 00:45:17.520
[Guest]: it a serious question?

00:45:17.520 --> 00:45:18.520
[Guest]: Is it a fun question?

00:45:18.520 --> 00:45:19.520
[Guest]: And is it a doable question?

00:45:19.520 --> 00:45:20.520
[Guest]: The doable is really important.

00:45:20.520 --> 00:45:25.320
[Guest]: I mean, I have like the best research question, but I may not have sources, nobody may be

00:45:25.320 --> 00:45:26.320
[Guest]: willing to open up.

00:45:26.320 --> 00:45:30.240
[Unknown]: Archives may be not there, in which case you should abandon the question, right?

00:45:30.240 --> 00:45:31.240
[Guest]: So I spent about a year.

00:45:31.240 --> 00:45:35.280
[Guest]: And at the end of that, Amit, I did something that I learned for the Nassim Mara book.

00:45:35.280 --> 00:45:38.360
[Guest]: I wrote a draft table of contents for the book.

00:45:38.360 --> 00:45:42.640
[Guest]: I said, look, it'll be 300 pages, each chapter will be 30 pages, and I wrote it.

00:45:42.640 --> 00:45:44.520
[Guest]: Now, this sounds absurd, right?

00:45:44.520 --> 00:45:49.880
[Guest]: But what it did is immediately from this abstract idea, the book became like a physical thing.

00:45:49.880 --> 00:45:52.760
[Guest]: And I said, look, ultimately, I have a physical thing.

00:45:52.760 --> 00:45:55.400
[Guest]: Ultimately, it has to be 30 pages.

00:45:55.400 --> 00:45:59.400
[Guest]: And I remember, you know, somebody telling me this when I was doing my PhD, that, you

00:45:59.400 --> 00:46:04.560
[Guest]: know, the biggest advice he gave was think in chapters, which is a nice advice, because

00:46:04.560 --> 00:46:08.840
[Guest]: otherwise you have the romance of an idea without how do you actually execute it, right?

00:46:08.840 --> 00:46:13.040
[Guest]: Now, the key here, Amit, is something that you pointed out, which is that you shouldn't

00:46:13.040 --> 00:46:15.320
[Guest]: be too wedded to your initial ideas.

00:46:15.320 --> 00:46:18.920
[Guest]: So while I wrote this table of contents, which is like a rough structure of what the book

00:46:18.920 --> 00:46:23.840
[Guest]: is going to look like, I was very comfortable that the moment I found more evidence, I should

00:46:23.840 --> 00:46:26.720
[Guest]: change chapters, remove them, etc, etc, right?

00:46:26.720 --> 00:46:30.960
[Guest]: Now, having done that, Amit, what I did was that I went to the second phase, which is

00:46:30.960 --> 00:46:35.720
[Guest]: I would call research, which is I started both reading secondary material, which is

00:46:35.720 --> 00:46:39.440
[Guest]: books and articles written by others, and fitting them into these chapters.

00:46:39.440 --> 00:46:42.400
[Guest]: So I used to have separate Word documents for each chapter.

00:46:42.400 --> 00:46:45.160
[Guest]: And then I have Word documents for sections within each chapter.

00:46:45.160 --> 00:46:47.840
[Guest]: Now, why this is helpful, Amit, is two ways.

00:46:47.840 --> 00:46:51.760
[Guest]: One is that when you're going to the archive, you're looking for something, right?

00:46:51.760 --> 00:46:55.800
[Guest]: Otherwise, you know, you see, you know, you see, like, you know, 6000 pages, you don't

00:46:55.800 --> 00:46:58.160
[Guest]: know which needle to look in the haystack, right?

00:46:58.160 --> 00:47:00.360
[Guest]: So you go in with a hypothesis.

00:47:00.360 --> 00:47:03.720
[Unknown]: And second is that when I'm reading something, I'm immediately being productive and say,

00:47:03.720 --> 00:47:07.560
[Guest]: okay, you know, this has come in this chapter, or this is going to come in this space, which

00:47:07.560 --> 00:47:10.080
[Guest]: is quite, you know, so it saves a lot of time.

00:47:10.080 --> 00:47:15.440
[Guest]: Otherwise, I realized, Amit, from the time I was doing my PhD, that because research

00:47:15.440 --> 00:47:20.280
[Guest]: tends to be open ended, you could spend 50% of your time researching on something that

00:47:20.280 --> 00:47:22.320
[Guest]: is only 10% of the book.

00:47:22.320 --> 00:47:25.360
[Guest]: And some of that quote, unquote, wastage is inevitable.

00:47:25.360 --> 00:47:26.360
[Unknown]: That's what happens.

00:47:26.360 --> 00:47:28.880
[Unknown]: You have to go down some blind alleys when you're doing research.

00:47:28.880 --> 00:47:32.000
[Guest]: But you should avoid going down too many blind alleys, right?

00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:36.120
[Guest]: That said, the biggest problem of this approach is that you may end up with a predetermined

00:47:36.120 --> 00:47:37.120
[Guest]: outcome.

00:47:37.120 --> 00:47:40.640
[Guest]: So you know, to use the popular phrase, when it comes to writing, you should be happy to

00:47:40.640 --> 00:47:41.640
[Guest]: kill your babies.

00:47:41.640 --> 00:47:44.920
[Guest]: The moment you realize, you know, you may have this great idea, you may have spent a

00:47:44.920 --> 00:47:48.840
[Guest]: month kind of telling yourself, yeah, this is how the BJP work.

00:47:48.840 --> 00:47:54.440
[Guest]: But if an evidence points otherwise, you have to say, I'm sorry, I was wrong, you know.

00:47:54.440 --> 00:47:59.160
[Unknown]: And if you don't do that, then the reader is able to smell very quickly is your opinions

00:47:59.160 --> 00:48:03.880
[Guest]: and conclusions driven from the evidence you provide, or are you trying to sell me something

00:48:03.880 --> 00:48:09.080
[Guest]: and in this age amid the post fact world, everybody is using facts to actually sell

00:48:09.080 --> 00:48:10.080
[Guest]: an agenda.

00:48:10.080 --> 00:48:13.720
[Guest]: And I think readers are totally inured from it, very irritated with it.

00:48:13.720 --> 00:48:18.200
[Guest]: So I was very, very sensitive that the moment the evidence or somebody told me something,

00:48:18.200 --> 00:48:23.280
[Guest]: some archive, some newspaper gave me a slightly different view, I should present it like to

00:48:23.280 --> 00:48:24.280
[Unknown]: give you one example.

00:48:24.280 --> 00:48:29.280
[Unknown]: You know, I came in with the standard view that, you know, Vajpayee the moderate, Advani

00:48:29.280 --> 00:48:30.280
[Unknown]: the hardliner.

00:48:30.280 --> 00:48:34.240
[Guest]: And I very quickly realized that Advani's background is exceedingly complex.

00:48:34.240 --> 00:48:38.240
[Guest]: He's like most of the listeners of this podcast, a Macaulay Putra, somebody who speaks English

00:48:38.240 --> 00:48:39.240
[Guest]: as the first language.

00:48:39.240 --> 00:48:45.360
[Guest]: He grew up to enormous wealth in Karachi, his family had a game room, huge house, they

00:48:45.360 --> 00:48:49.080
[Guest]: had a Victoria horse driven carriage, you know, he was playing tennis when someone told

00:48:49.080 --> 00:48:53.320
[Guest]: him about the RSS, who joins the RSS after a tennis game.

00:48:53.320 --> 00:48:57.840
[Unknown]: And he wouldn't have joined RSS had it not been for the looming catastrophe of partition,

00:48:57.840 --> 00:49:04.320
[Guest]: which splits his hometown and makes his rich family near poverty, enter near poverty.

00:49:04.320 --> 00:49:08.520
[Guest]: So immediately when I realized that, I realized that I had to change this original idea of

00:49:08.520 --> 00:49:14.880
[Guest]: a classic jugalbandhi between a moderate and a hardliner, because it was much more complex.

00:49:14.880 --> 00:49:19.200
[Guest]: So that's again, I think something where journalism has helped me saying that you can't be wedded

00:49:19.200 --> 00:49:20.200
[Guest]: to your own ideas.

00:49:20.200 --> 00:49:26.040
[Guest]: If this is the famous John Maynard Keynes line, when the facts change, I change my mind,

00:49:26.040 --> 00:49:27.720
[Guest]: what do you do, sir?

00:49:27.720 --> 00:49:32.000
[Guest]: So that's the second stage, Amit, which is research.

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:38.280
[Guest]: And then what I have learned to do is to start writing quicker rather than later.

00:49:38.280 --> 00:49:42.920
[Guest]: Because there is this sense I realized that perfection is the enemy of production.

00:49:42.920 --> 00:49:46.880
[Guest]: And a lot of academics and researchers are saying that, look, I have to now read four

00:49:46.880 --> 00:49:51.320
[Guest]: more books before I start writing, or I have to look at interview three more people before

00:49:51.320 --> 00:49:52.320
[Guest]: I start writing.

00:49:52.320 --> 00:49:53.320
[Guest]: That will never happen.

00:49:53.320 --> 00:49:57.720
[Guest]: You'll spend your whole life trying to do this, this mythic sense of completion.

00:49:57.720 --> 00:50:03.520
[Guest]: So what I learned was that, and my brother who's an MBA, he works for an FMCG, he's a

00:50:03.520 --> 00:50:07.680
[Guest]: big influence on my life, and he's extremely focused on delivery.

00:50:07.680 --> 00:50:11.160
[Guest]: And he's saying, look, write the chapter, he told me, and whatever you haven't done

00:50:11.160 --> 00:50:12.960
[Guest]: research, leave it blank.

00:50:12.960 --> 00:50:16.720
[Unknown]: So that when you go for your second round of research, you're only looking to fill in

00:50:16.720 --> 00:50:17.720
[Guest]: the blank.

00:50:17.720 --> 00:50:21.840
[Unknown]: And I found that a very, very helpful technique, because right with the material you have,

00:50:21.840 --> 00:50:25.280
[Unknown]: let's say it's about 70% of the material that you should have.

00:50:25.280 --> 00:50:29.320
[Guest]: But you know, to use consultancy speak, ring fence the problem.

00:50:29.320 --> 00:50:34.120
[Guest]: So right there, the paragraphs which are hollow, and then do a second round of research, because

00:50:34.120 --> 00:50:37.840
[Guest]: once you have written, you can see the holes in the chapter.

00:50:37.840 --> 00:50:40.400
[Guest]: And when you do that, it may change even more.

00:50:40.400 --> 00:50:44.160
[Guest]: So I would broadly say that, you know, when you said knowledge management, these are the

00:50:44.160 --> 00:50:48.240
[Guest]: three different phases, and at least so far, it's helped me in good stead.

00:50:48.240 --> 00:50:53.480
[Guest]: But you know, in some cases, I have made mistakes, so hopefully the next book will be a refinement

00:50:53.480 --> 00:50:54.480
[Guest]: of this process.

00:50:54.480 --> 00:50:58.320
[Amit Varma]: No, that's a fantastic quote about perfection being the enemy of production.

00:50:58.320 --> 00:51:04.280
[Amit Varma]: You know, I teach a writing course, where I constantly sort of tell my students that,

00:51:04.280 --> 00:51:08.120
[Amit Varma]: you know, for anything you do in life, there are these two imperatives, getting it done

00:51:08.120 --> 00:51:09.360
[Amit Varma]: and getting it right.

00:51:09.360 --> 00:51:11.600
[Amit Varma]: And your first priority has to be to get it done.

00:51:11.600 --> 00:51:16.400
[Amit Varma]: And once you get it done, then you edit, edit, edit, then you chisel it down and get it right.

00:51:16.400 --> 00:51:21.040
[Amit Varma]: And very often just getting it done, the process of iteration and reiteration will get it right,

00:51:21.040 --> 00:51:22.440
[Amit Varma]: but that's the only way to do it.

00:51:22.440 --> 00:51:24.360
[Amit Varma]: So that strikes a chord with me.

00:51:24.360 --> 00:51:29.160
[Amit Varma]: My last sort of question about your working methods before we get to the book itself is,

00:51:29.160 --> 00:51:35.400
[Amit Varma]: what is the process like of then getting people to talk to you about this period of time and

00:51:35.400 --> 00:51:39.800
[Amit Varma]: some of whom I presume are people who would even in the current day be fairly important?

00:51:39.800 --> 00:51:42.480
[Amit Varma]: You know, how do you get access? how do you get their trust?

00:51:42.480 --> 00:51:47.080
[Amit Varma]: And then is there a sort of this psychological pressure that these people who have trusted

00:51:47.080 --> 00:51:50.400
[Amit Varma]: you and been so nice to you, you have to make them look good also?

00:51:50.400 --> 00:51:54.800
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, how does that whole process sort of work?

00:51:54.800 --> 00:51:59.000
[Guest]: There's no psychological pressure on me to make them look good, because their narrative

00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:01.440
[Guest]: has already made them look good.

00:52:01.440 --> 00:52:07.600
[Guest]: You know, everyone in their story is the hero or heroine of their own story.

00:52:07.600 --> 00:52:11.800
[Guest]: Some people do it obviously, some people aren't even aware that they're doing it, you know.

00:52:11.800 --> 00:52:15.320
[Guest]: So this is like, you have to deal with this and it's hard.

00:52:15.320 --> 00:52:19.640
[Unknown]: But you know, it's a hard question, because there's no simple answer to it.

00:52:19.640 --> 00:52:24.120
[Guest]: If it was simple answer, then, you know, anybody could see this podcast and become the world's

00:52:24.120 --> 00:52:25.120
[Guest]: best journalist.

00:52:25.120 --> 00:52:29.480
[Guest]: And I'm not a good journalist, but my two years in journalism made me look at the best

00:52:29.480 --> 00:52:32.480
[Guest]: and look at how they try to answer this question, right?

00:52:32.480 --> 00:52:34.480
[Guest]: Like, how do you cultivate a source?

00:52:34.480 --> 00:52:36.320
[Guest]: How do you make people trust you?

00:52:36.320 --> 00:52:40.720
[Guest]: Because in India, especially, there's no shortage of people who want to speak.

00:52:40.720 --> 00:52:41.720
[Guest]: Everybody has a story.

00:52:41.720 --> 00:52:42.720
[Guest]: Everybody wants to give gyaan.

00:52:42.720 --> 00:52:45.520
[Guest]: The issue is, do they trust you?

00:52:45.520 --> 00:52:46.520
[Guest]: That's the issue.

00:52:46.520 --> 00:52:52.120
[Guest]: And luckily for me, my first book, I had again interviewed a ton of people, and I was very

00:52:52.120 --> 00:52:53.120
[Guest]: careful about it.

00:52:53.120 --> 00:52:57.720
[Guest]: In that I sent out emails to everybody after, you know, just before the book was coming,

00:52:57.720 --> 00:53:00.440
[Guest]: saying, look, this is the paragraph you have been quoted.

00:53:00.440 --> 00:53:05.000
[Guest]: So not only did I ask their permission for their quotes, I gave them the two sentences

00:53:05.000 --> 00:53:06.920
[Guest]: above and two sentences below, right?

00:53:06.920 --> 00:53:10.760
[Guest]: And I think that, you know, this is, you know, from whether it's Prime Minister Manmohan

00:53:10.760 --> 00:53:14.680
[Guest]: Singh, or it's like the doctor of Narsimha Rao, I use the same rule.

00:53:14.680 --> 00:53:15.680
[Guest]: I didn't change that.

00:53:15.680 --> 00:53:16.680
[Guest]: Right.

00:53:16.680 --> 00:53:20.680
[Guest]: And I realized that that brings credibility, that people realize that look, speak, I don't

00:53:20.680 --> 00:53:21.680
[Guest]: record.

00:53:21.680 --> 00:53:22.680
[Guest]: So I write down.

00:53:22.680 --> 00:53:23.680
[Guest]: So I have nothing to hold on.

00:53:23.680 --> 00:53:26.600
[Guest]: So, you know, later on, if they deny, I'm screwed, right?

00:53:26.600 --> 00:53:28.480
[Guest]: They know that, that helps build trust.

00:53:28.480 --> 00:53:33.080
[Guest]: And so when really their consent happens, when I send them an email later, and they

00:53:33.080 --> 00:53:36.320
[Guest]: say, yes, quote ABC and don't quote X, Y, Z.

00:53:36.320 --> 00:53:37.320
[Guest]: And this happens all the time.

00:53:37.320 --> 00:53:41.440
[Guest]: I mean, and also people speak very freely, but seven, eight months later, when I'm actually

00:53:41.440 --> 00:53:45.840
[Guest]: sending them big quotes, things, their life circumstances have changed, and suddenly they

00:53:45.840 --> 00:53:46.840
[Guest]: develop cold feet.

00:53:46.840 --> 00:53:51.440
[Unknown]: And I think one of the things I regret in the book is the number of names I could tell

00:53:51.440 --> 00:53:55.440
[Guest]: you would add even more credibility to the book, you know, like, it would blow your mind

00:53:55.440 --> 00:53:56.440
[Guest]: up.

00:53:56.440 --> 00:53:59.840
[Guest]: But I just, and you know, I'm just, I'm just bursting to tell you that, you know, you know,

00:53:59.840 --> 00:54:03.760
[Unknown]: there are already, there are maybe about less, a little less than a hundred names that are

00:54:03.760 --> 00:54:08.400
[Guest]: quoted, but the hundred names that are not quoted, maybe even more like, you know, juicy,

00:54:08.400 --> 00:54:09.400
[Guest]: but I just can't do it.

00:54:09.400 --> 00:54:13.920
[Guest]: You know, if I do it, nobody will talk to me for my third book, nobody.

00:54:13.920 --> 00:54:19.040
[Guest]: And the other thing I've noticed that happens is that if you don't know somebody, so definitely

00:54:19.040 --> 00:54:23.520
[Guest]: my previous book added to the credibility that, look, I'm not looking for a gotcha moment,

00:54:23.520 --> 00:54:24.520
[Guest]: right?

00:54:24.520 --> 00:54:25.520
[Guest]: I'm not looking to trap you.

00:54:25.520 --> 00:54:28.080
[Guest]: And then you'll come in the newspaper, that kind of thing.

00:54:28.080 --> 00:54:32.160
[Guest]: But equally in India, somebody has to vouch for you.

00:54:32.160 --> 00:54:33.160
[Guest]: Somebody has to.

00:54:33.160 --> 00:54:37.760
[Guest]: So, you know, I meet an older person or something like that, who may not have heard of my, the

00:54:37.760 --> 00:54:41.200
[Guest]: previous book, somebody who they trust has to trust me.

00:54:41.200 --> 00:54:42.200
[Guest]: That's the only way they do it.

00:54:42.200 --> 00:54:46.600
[Guest]: Otherwise, yeah, maybe it's just an Indian trade, because that's in some sense, the heart

00:54:46.600 --> 00:54:51.480
[Guest]: of my book that Indians lack teamwork and the BJP does it well, that everybody's suspicious

00:54:51.480 --> 00:54:54.920
[Guest]: if somebody, you know, of somebody just coming and asking you questions.

00:54:54.920 --> 00:55:00.280
[Guest]: I mean, look at how rudely Indians treat salesmen, Eureka salesmen who ring your bell, right?

00:55:00.280 --> 00:55:02.080
[Guest]: And come to try to sell you something on your door.

00:55:02.080 --> 00:55:03.080
[Unknown]: We don't like it.

00:55:03.080 --> 00:55:04.080
[Guest]: We don't like strangers.

00:55:04.080 --> 00:55:06.800
[Guest]: So, you have to have somebody to vouch for you.

00:55:06.800 --> 00:55:10.680
[Guest]: And then the third thing I realized, I mean, is that you have to come for an interview

00:55:10.680 --> 00:55:11.680
[Guest]: well prepared.

00:55:11.680 --> 00:55:16.600
[Guest]: You know, you can't use the source or the interviewer for the basic material, right?

00:55:16.600 --> 00:55:17.600
[Guest]: That's important.

00:55:17.600 --> 00:55:19.280
[Guest]: Then people begin to respect you.

00:55:19.280 --> 00:55:21.640
[Guest]: They said, okay, he's come prepared, you know.

00:55:21.640 --> 00:55:25.040
[Guest]: So I would say, you know, these were some of the skills I use, but I don't, there's

00:55:25.040 --> 00:55:26.600
[Guest]: no formula for this.

00:55:26.600 --> 00:55:31.080
[Guest]: It's the same question I'm asking in any relationship with your spouse, with your friends, with

00:55:31.080 --> 00:55:32.080
[Guest]: your parents.

00:55:32.080 --> 00:55:33.080
[Guest]: How do you build trust?

00:55:33.080 --> 00:55:38.760
[Guest]: And frankly, for me, 50% is building trust with the source and 50% is building trust

00:55:38.760 --> 00:55:39.760
[Guest]: with the leader.

00:55:39.760 --> 00:55:43.560
[Unknown]: And it's actually the same thing, which is that, you know, everybody realizes that you

00:55:43.560 --> 00:55:45.000
[Unknown]: have an angle.

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:49.200
[Unknown]: Everybody realizes that you come in with biases, but be honest about it, come well prepared

00:55:49.200 --> 00:55:54.120
[Guest]: and don't try to take advantage of somebody's being nice or trusting you.

00:55:54.120 --> 00:55:57.840
[Unknown]: And then in India, that is such a deficit that even if you do a little of it, then,

00:55:57.840 --> 00:56:01.160
[Unknown]: you know, people, they want to tell you everything about your life and I actually want to leave

00:56:01.160 --> 00:56:06.560
[Guest]: for lunch, you know, so, but there's no formula for that.

00:56:06.560 --> 00:56:09.640
[Amit Varma]: And definitely that comes from my journalism, right?

00:56:09.640 --> 00:56:14.560
[Amit Varma]: Also the other thing that I sort of wanted to ask you was that comes to mind is that

00:56:14.560 --> 00:56:18.880
[Amit Varma]: you've mentioned about how, you know, perfection is the enemy of production.

00:56:18.880 --> 00:56:23.840
[Amit Varma]: So obviously your first impulse is to get it done, you know, to get it out on paper.

00:56:23.840 --> 00:56:26.800
[Amit Varma]: What's your process like after you have a first draft done?

00:56:26.800 --> 00:56:30.760
[Amit Varma]: Like one thing you mentioned is you've got paragraphs and you've got holes in them, or

00:56:30.760 --> 00:56:33.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, within a chapter, you've got holes, you know that, okay, that's where I need to

00:56:33.960 --> 00:56:35.920
[Amit Varma]: go back and get the research done.

00:56:35.920 --> 00:56:39.520
[Amit Varma]: But once you have all the material and you've gotten that first draft, what's the process

00:56:39.520 --> 00:56:40.520
[Amit Varma]: of editing like?

00:56:40.520 --> 00:56:45.840
[Amit Varma]: Do you ever end up restructuring the book itself, or the chapters themselves in significant

00:56:45.840 --> 00:56:46.840
[Amit Varma]: ways?

00:56:46.840 --> 00:56:49.320
[Amit Varma]: How much time do they take vis-a-vis one another?

00:56:49.320 --> 00:56:54.320
[Guest]: You know, Amit, I spend a lot of time thinking about the editing process because, you know,

00:56:54.320 --> 00:56:59.480
[Guest]: my wife teaches creative writing, exactly what you do, and she's drilled into me that

00:56:59.480 --> 00:57:03.960
[Guest]: look, the first draft is actually quite liberating because it's going to look nothing like the

00:57:03.960 --> 00:57:05.160
[Guest]: final draft.

00:57:05.160 --> 00:57:09.240
[Guest]: So don't worry about putting something on paper because have the confidence that it's

00:57:09.240 --> 00:57:11.920
[Guest]: only draft number 18 that is going to go.

00:57:11.920 --> 00:57:14.800
[Guest]: And there's a huge difference between draft one and draft 18.

00:57:14.800 --> 00:57:16.880
[Guest]: So that's actually quite liberating, right?

00:57:16.880 --> 00:57:20.520
[Guest]: Because otherwise, you're worried that if you put something on paper, it has to be perfect.

00:57:20.520 --> 00:57:21.520
[Guest]: It doesn't.

00:57:21.520 --> 00:57:24.480
[Guest]: And I've really learned a lot from that idea of hers.

00:57:24.480 --> 00:57:30.320
[Guest]: And it's like, I, you know, I write and look, when I think I may not, you know, you don't

00:57:30.320 --> 00:57:31.320
[Unknown]: begin at the beginning, right?

00:57:31.320 --> 00:57:34.920
[Unknown]: The human mind is not, doesn't begin a story at the beginning, you typically begin the

00:57:34.920 --> 00:57:36.240
[Unknown]: story in the middle.

00:57:36.240 --> 00:57:40.520
[Guest]: And so I write it and then only later I find out what should be the first paragraph that

00:57:40.520 --> 00:57:42.200
[Guest]: kind of draws the reader in.

00:57:42.200 --> 00:57:46.200
[Guest]: I'm sure you've done exactly this when you were in Cricinfo, Amit, that you have to edit

00:57:46.200 --> 00:57:47.200
[Guest]: other people's work.

00:57:47.200 --> 00:57:51.360
[Guest]: The material is there, but you want to kind of make the bread rise just a little bit.

00:57:51.360 --> 00:57:52.360
[Unknown]: And that's your job as an editor.

00:57:52.360 --> 00:57:57.520
[Unknown]: And I think in Express, I wasn't just a journalist, I was also like a copy editor, where I was

00:57:57.520 --> 00:58:00.120
[Guest]: editing other people's op-ed page submissions.

00:58:00.120 --> 00:58:02.440
[Guest]: So I should change the voice of that person.

00:58:02.440 --> 00:58:06.320
[Guest]: But how do I kind of have a better beginning, have a better end, right?

00:58:06.320 --> 00:58:10.240
[Guest]: George Orwell has been a huge influence on me of this.

00:58:10.240 --> 00:58:15.080
[Guest]: He has a, I think, Politics in the English Language, an extraordinary essay where he

00:58:15.080 --> 00:58:20.160
[Guest]: tells you what to avoid, which is don't use a word if it's not required, right?

00:58:20.160 --> 00:58:23.280
[Guest]: Make sure that every sentence follows from the previous one.

00:58:23.280 --> 00:58:26.400
[Guest]: And another one of my writing gurus has been V.S. Naipaul.

00:58:26.400 --> 00:58:30.880
[Guest]: And if you look at, forget his politics for just a second, but he's one of the great stylists

00:58:30.880 --> 00:58:32.880
[Guest]: of prose in the 20th century.

00:58:32.880 --> 00:58:39.200
[Guest]: He used to write very short sentences, and each sentence, he made sure that every sentence

00:58:39.200 --> 00:58:42.360
[Guest]: had a next sentence that followed from that.

00:58:42.360 --> 00:58:45.440
[Guest]: And if you remove that sentence, the paragraph would fall.

00:58:45.440 --> 00:58:46.440
[Unknown]: That was the test, right?

00:58:46.440 --> 00:58:50.560
[Unknown]: That if you have a sentence there, that maybe you can remove that sentence and it will still

00:58:50.560 --> 00:58:53.560
[Guest]: sort of tell the reader the same thing, then you should remove it.

00:58:53.560 --> 00:58:58.440
[Guest]: And that's what makes it kind of sparse and it forces you to, because what is the leader

00:58:58.440 --> 00:58:59.440
[Unknown]: getting in return?

00:58:59.440 --> 00:59:03.840
[Guest]: The leader is getting in return the confidence that every word the leader is being forced

00:59:03.840 --> 00:59:06.000
[Unknown]: to read has been worth it.

00:59:06.000 --> 00:59:12.440
[Unknown]: And the writer has spent a lot of energy not sending the reader down random rabbit holes.

00:59:12.440 --> 00:59:16.960
[Guest]: I'm not a very good writer, in a sense, I'm not a natural writer, so I'm a bit of a defensive

00:59:16.960 --> 00:59:17.960
[Guest]: writer.

00:59:17.960 --> 00:59:23.200
[Guest]: So what I try to do is use writing as a very light scaffolding so that I can tell the story.

00:59:23.200 --> 00:59:28.080
[Guest]: I also know that about myself, that look, I'm not like the world's best prose stylist.

00:59:28.080 --> 00:59:32.920
[Guest]: So I'm defensive, I use short sentences, I use active voice.

00:59:32.920 --> 00:59:38.400
[Guest]: That's another thing that George Orwell stressed on, you know, and as far as possible, if there's

00:59:38.400 --> 00:59:43.000
[Guest]: any meat, like I try to avoid starters and on three and that kind of stuff.

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:46.000
[Guest]: I give you the main course, right, in every sentence.

00:59:46.000 --> 00:59:48.840
[Guest]: And in other words, the sentence must be saying something.

00:59:48.840 --> 00:59:53.480
[Guest]: The other thing on editing I've learned a lot from BS Naipaul is that every sentence

00:59:53.480 --> 00:59:55.880
[Guest]: must be capable of a couple of meanings, right?

00:59:55.880 --> 00:59:57.360
[Guest]: That's the power of a sentence.

00:59:57.360 --> 01:00:01.040
[Guest]: You know, I'll give you one example, I mean, which is that you must have noticed that the

01:00:01.040 --> 01:00:06.840
[Guest]: book begins with an organization, a story of like an event that is being organized,

01:00:06.840 --> 01:00:13.480
[Guest]: which is the 1995 November, BJP national executive in Bombay, in Shivaji Park, etc, etc, right?

01:00:13.480 --> 01:00:14.480
[Guest]: And Mahalakshmi racecourse.

01:00:14.480 --> 01:00:18.840
[Guest]: And I spent time on the logistics, you know, that they were, you know, 10,000 people to

01:00:18.840 --> 01:00:24.080
[Guest]: be fed, these many people were coming by boat, you know, I do that through the book, right?

01:00:24.080 --> 01:00:28.920
[Guest]: But what I'm trying to do is give you the flavor of a movement that is obsessed with

01:00:28.920 --> 01:00:31.040
[Guest]: this stuff without ever saying it, right?

01:00:31.040 --> 01:00:35.040
[Guest]: Of course, I begin the story with Vajpayee Advani and Advani announcing Vajpayee's Prime

01:00:35.040 --> 01:00:39.080
[Guest]: Minister, but I deliberately spend a lot of time telling you, for example, you know, I'm

01:00:39.080 --> 01:00:40.320
[Guest]: just opening the book here.

01:00:40.320 --> 01:00:47.080
[Unknown]: And, you know, to give you this particular detail, which is that over 120,000 delegates

01:00:47.080 --> 01:00:53.760
[Guest]: attended, this is the November 1995 event, BJP event in Bombay, some even by ship from

01:00:53.760 --> 01:00:56.400
[Guest]: the Andaman and Nicobar Islands, right?

01:00:56.400 --> 01:00:58.040
[Guest]: So this sentence has two meanings.

01:00:58.040 --> 01:00:59.960
[Guest]: One is, of course, it's a fun fact.

01:00:59.960 --> 01:01:04.160
[Guest]: But the deeper point I'm taking is that these guys win because they're obsessed with this

01:01:04.160 --> 01:01:05.160
[Guest]: sort of organization.

01:01:05.160 --> 01:01:09.080
[Guest]: If I was writing a book on the Congress, I would not have this sentence.

01:01:09.080 --> 01:01:13.040
[Guest]: Congress also does organization, Congress also has events, right?

01:01:13.040 --> 01:01:17.880
[Guest]: People do come from Andaman, Nicobar Islands, but it's not central to the self, you know,

01:01:17.880 --> 01:01:22.160
[Guest]: the self-knowledge and the self-impression that the Congress has of itself.

01:01:22.160 --> 01:01:26.240
[Guest]: So that's what I mean that, you know, like a lot of sentences, if you play it right,

01:01:26.240 --> 01:01:29.920
[Guest]: you're saying something, but you're also telling them something deeper.

01:01:29.920 --> 01:01:31.440
[Guest]: And that only comes through editing.

01:01:31.440 --> 01:01:34.920
[Guest]: It only comes through like, you know, going through multiple drafts.

01:01:34.920 --> 01:01:40.280
[Unknown]: The other thing I've learned, Amit, again, this is thanks to my wife, is that I try to

01:01:40.280 --> 01:01:41.840
[Guest]: avoid cliches.

01:01:41.840 --> 01:01:47.320
[Guest]: So for example, I try to avoid saying it was a watershed moment, because a watershed actually

01:01:47.320 --> 01:01:52.160
[Guest]: is a certain visual where, you know, the river comes from the mountain and at some point

01:01:52.160 --> 01:01:57.600
[Amit Varma]: it hits a plane, and at the watershed, the river can go in multiple directions.

01:01:57.600 --> 01:02:02.840
[Guest]: So the technical use of watershed is an event, right, that can go in multiple directions,

01:02:02.840 --> 01:02:03.840
[Guest]: right?

01:02:03.840 --> 01:02:07.800
[Guest]: Whereas we use watershed today to mean an important event.

01:02:07.800 --> 01:02:08.800
[Guest]: That's not what it means.

01:02:08.800 --> 01:02:14.120
[Guest]: So if, but because it has become an overused cliche, then we keep using it without thinking.

01:02:14.120 --> 01:02:17.880
[Guest]: So the other thing I've learned is when I detect a cliche, I remove it.

01:02:17.880 --> 01:02:21.440
[Guest]: And I try to look for a synonym, or I like to look for another thing that communicates

01:02:21.440 --> 01:02:22.440
[Unknown]: it.

01:02:22.440 --> 01:02:24.440
[Guest]: And, you know, there's all these thesauruses and dictionaries online.

01:02:24.440 --> 01:02:25.880
[Guest]: So life is quite easy.

01:02:25.880 --> 01:02:30.400
[Guest]: But none of this is conceivable in the first draft, this actually happens in the 8, 9,

01:02:30.400 --> 01:02:31.400
[Guest]: 10 draft.

01:02:31.400 --> 01:02:35.920
[Guest]: And my only hope is that the reader realizes that all this effort is to make her happy,

01:02:35.920 --> 01:02:41.120
[Guest]: you know, and, and that to me, I'm very clear that, you know, I have one boss in this book,

01:02:41.120 --> 01:02:42.120
[Guest]: and that's the reader.

01:02:42.120 --> 01:02:47.320
[Amit Varma]: No, I mean, everything that you said strikes such a chord that all my writing students

01:02:47.320 --> 01:02:52.840
[Amit Varma]: and listeners of this podcast will be wondering if I sat down in advance and all of this,

01:02:52.840 --> 01:02:56.000
[Amit Varma]: but then, you know, as you said, your wife is a writing teacher, for example, you know,

01:02:56.000 --> 01:02:59.640
[Amit Varma]: when I used to be an editor in Pragati and elsewhere, whenever someone new would write

01:02:59.640 --> 01:03:03.560
[Amit Varma]: for me, I'd first make them read politics in the English language.

01:03:03.560 --> 01:03:04.560
[Unknown]: It's just a seminal.

01:03:04.560 --> 01:03:09.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's not fixed at all.

01:03:09.000 --> 01:03:13.880
[Amit Varma]: And Orwell's essays, in fact, you know, what I consistently cite as my desert island book,

01:03:13.880 --> 01:03:14.960
[Amit Varma]: it's a masterpiece.

01:03:14.960 --> 01:03:18.760
[Amit Varma]: And it's an interesting bit of trivia for you, since you mentioned active voice.

01:03:18.760 --> 01:03:24.440
[Amit Varma]: In his essay politics in the English language, Orwell warns against using passive voice twice.

01:03:24.440 --> 01:03:26.680
[Amit Varma]: And one of those times he does it in passive voice.

01:03:26.680 --> 01:03:27.680
[Amit Varma]: Oh, wow.

01:03:27.680 --> 01:03:28.680
[Amit Varma]: I didn't know that.

01:03:28.680 --> 01:03:29.680
[Amit Varma]: I did not know that.

01:03:29.680 --> 01:03:30.680
[Amit Varma]: Wow.

01:03:30.680 --> 01:03:34.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's just a moment of irony, which I, and even what, you know, what you said about

01:03:34.040 --> 01:03:37.280
[Amit Varma]: cliches, the interesting thing about, and of course, cliches are bad, because they don't

01:03:37.280 --> 01:03:41.640
[Amit Varma]: invoke a fresh image and the reader's eyes glaze over, but they can also be inaccurate.

01:03:41.640 --> 01:03:45.680
[Amit Varma]: Like you said, watershed moment, and the cricketing example of that would be the ball sped to

01:03:45.680 --> 01:03:47.800
[Amit Varma]: the boundary, like a tracer bullet.

01:03:47.800 --> 01:03:51.520
[Amit Varma]: And if anyone's actually seen a tracer bullet, they don't go the way Ravi Shastri thinks

01:03:51.520 --> 01:03:52.520
[Guest]: they go.

01:03:52.520 --> 01:03:53.520
[Guest]: That's exactly right.

01:03:53.520 --> 01:04:00.720
[Guest]: And what that does, Amit, is what you mentioned, that if you're trying to communicate something

01:04:00.720 --> 01:04:06.640
[Guest]: using a fresh image, the reader's eye doesn't glaze over, the reader pauses to see, right?

01:04:06.640 --> 01:04:10.920
[Guest]: And then the image has that double power, you know, so from a diluted image, you end

01:04:10.920 --> 01:04:14.720
[Guest]: up with a very concentrated image, because the reader hasn't heard that before, right?

01:04:14.720 --> 01:04:19.680
[Guest]: So you know, just what would you say, just as an exercise, that if the ball went very

01:04:19.680 --> 01:04:24.520
[Guest]: fast to the boundary, what would be a fresh image that communicates exactly what the ball

01:04:24.520 --> 01:04:25.520
[Guest]: did?

01:04:25.520 --> 01:04:26.520
[Guest]: You know, because you're the cricket man.

01:04:26.520 --> 01:04:30.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, well, right now, I can't think of something offhand, because I'd actually have to see

01:04:30.760 --> 01:04:31.760
[Amit Varma]: it.

01:04:31.760 --> 01:04:33.280
[Amit Varma]: I don't want to comment on a hypothetical ball.

01:04:33.280 --> 01:04:37.840
[Amit Varma]: But the classic example I give is that sometimes an adjective in a particular context can be

01:04:37.840 --> 01:04:38.840
[Amit Varma]: a cliche.

01:04:38.840 --> 01:04:41.760
[Amit Varma]: For example, all cover drives will be described as elegant.

01:04:41.760 --> 01:04:46.000
[Amit Varma]: But the point is that you can say that Virat Kohli played an elegant cover drive, or Rahul

01:04:46.000 --> 01:04:47.560
[Amit Varma]: Rawat did, or Mark Waugh did.

01:04:47.560 --> 01:04:51.520
[Amit Varma]: And the truth is, it's accurate, because all the cover drives are elegant.

01:04:51.520 --> 01:04:55.440
[Amit Varma]: But it doesn't convey the particulars, they're very different from each other.

01:04:55.440 --> 01:04:57.880
[Guest]: And that's a writer's job to get to the heart of the difference.

01:04:57.880 --> 01:04:58.880
[Guest]: Absolutely.

01:04:58.880 --> 01:05:02.600
[Guest]: In fact, I try as much as possible to avoid adjectives and adverbs.

01:05:02.600 --> 01:05:08.080
[Guest]: You know, describe it, you know, don't say that he ran quickly, right?

01:05:08.080 --> 01:05:12.280
[Guest]: Don't say that, you know, when he ran, the floor was creaking, or the floor made a lot

01:05:12.280 --> 01:05:14.560
[Unknown]: of noise, something like that.

01:05:14.560 --> 01:05:18.480
[Guest]: So I tried, again, this is all defensive writing, because, you know, if you're a great writer,

01:05:18.480 --> 01:05:22.680
[Guest]: you don't need to be told all this, you have an intuitive rhythm, I know I don't.

01:05:22.680 --> 01:05:27.760
[Unknown]: So I and again, when I in my first draft, and I'm sure it's the same with you Amit,

01:05:27.760 --> 01:05:29.040
[Unknown]: we write like we talk.

01:05:29.040 --> 01:05:34.120
[Guest]: So we use cliches, you know, when we speak, our first reaction is imprecise.

01:05:34.120 --> 01:05:40.200
[Guest]: But in all the further edits, I move it further and further away from the original bad way

01:05:40.200 --> 01:05:42.720
[Guest]: in which I try to communicate it.

01:05:42.720 --> 01:05:48.640
[Guest]: So in that sense, it's a it is highly constructed, you know, that that sense of that sense of

01:05:48.640 --> 01:05:50.800
[Guest]: sentences that I try at least to incorporate.

01:05:50.800 --> 01:05:56.680
[Guest]: By the way, thanks for this Amit, because I obsess hugely about the writing process.

01:05:56.680 --> 01:05:57.680
[Guest]: Right.

01:05:57.680 --> 01:06:02.560
[Guest]: And it's very, very important for me that a book like this is read, you know, far beyond

01:06:02.560 --> 01:06:08.520
[Guest]: the confines of, or even the people who see this podcast, we don't want a very small intelligent

01:06:08.520 --> 01:06:11.520
[Guest]: subset of policymakers or people interested in policy.

01:06:11.520 --> 01:06:13.520
[Guest]: So I wanted to be even broader, right.

01:06:13.520 --> 01:06:18.440
[Guest]: And at least so far, we're able to do it that, you know, right now on Amazon, I'm competing

01:06:18.440 --> 01:06:21.440
[Guest]: with like word power made easy and Dale Carnegie, right.

01:06:21.440 --> 01:06:27.080
[Guest]: And to do that, especially for a topic that is this difficult, that you have to obsess

01:06:27.080 --> 01:06:29.680
[Guest]: extra on the writing style.

01:06:29.680 --> 01:06:30.680
[Amit Varma]: No question.

01:06:30.680 --> 01:06:34.520
[Amit Varma]: But you know, that's especially important, because, you know, one thing again, my last

01:06:34.520 --> 01:06:38.080
[Amit Varma]: compliment of your book, because I don't want to embarrass you, but, you know, Orwell once

01:06:38.080 --> 01:06:41.680
[Amit Varma]: said good prose is like a windowpane, which means you should not notice it, it is just

01:06:41.680 --> 01:06:43.680
[Amit Varma]: meant to show you what's on the other side.

01:06:43.680 --> 01:06:47.440
[Amit Varma]: And that's one of the qualities of your book to being a writer myself, I actually noticed

01:06:47.440 --> 01:06:51.680
[Amit Varma]: quite a few superb sentences, which you came up with, but in a writerly sense, they don't

01:06:51.680 --> 01:06:52.960
[Amit Varma]: draw attention to themselves.

01:06:52.960 --> 01:06:57.360
[Amit Varma]: But I noticed that maybe I'll get the chance to quote a couple of them as we go along.

01:06:57.360 --> 01:07:00.640
[Amit Varma]: And the other thing that you said is also resonant with me, because one of the things

01:07:00.640 --> 01:07:07.000
[Amit Varma]: that I sort of emphasize when I talk about writing is that, especially in India, the

01:07:07.000 --> 01:07:10.440
[Amit Varma]: way we speak English, we've internalized a lot of bad habits.

01:07:10.440 --> 01:07:14.760
[Amit Varma]: And the first task is to become mindful of them, and eliminate them.

01:07:14.760 --> 01:07:19.800
[Amit Varma]: So in fact, one of the exercises I give my writing students is to write a specific piece,

01:07:19.800 --> 01:07:26.000
[Amit Varma]: whatever the theme is, but without using adjectives or adverbs, which they complain about a lot

01:07:26.000 --> 01:07:30.920
[Guest]: This is why EV Amit, I think we are on like a little, literally like 100% the same mind

01:07:30.920 --> 01:07:31.920
[Guest]: on this.

01:07:31.920 --> 01:07:32.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah.

01:07:32.920 --> 01:07:33.920
[Amit Varma]: Verbs are your best friend.

01:07:33.920 --> 01:07:38.720
[Amit Varma]: On that note, we will take to, you know, give you an active voice sentence, we will take

01:07:38.720 --> 01:07:43.360
[Unknown]: a commercial break now.

01:07:43.360 --> 01:07:47.520
[Amit Varma]: As many of you know, I'll soon be coming out with a four volume anthology of the seen and

01:07:47.520 --> 01:07:53.160
[Amit Varma]: the unseen books organized around the themes of politics, history, economics, and society

