01:08:47.400 --> 01:08:51.160
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene and the unseen I'm chatting with Vinay Sitapati about his wonderful

01:08:51.160 --> 01:08:59.160
[Amit Varma]: book Jugalbandi about the BJP before Narendra Modi and honestly tons of insight even on

01:08:59.160 --> 01:09:02.720
[Amit Varma]: the current BJP all of which comes from the context that we get.

01:09:02.720 --> 01:09:08.200
[Amit Varma]: So I kind of want to go to the context that you sort of set in the start of the book about

01:09:08.200 --> 01:09:13.740
[Amit Varma]: Hindu nationalism and the Hindu movement itself, where you point out that what any nationalism

01:09:13.740 --> 01:09:20.600
[Amit Varma]: has to contend with is thinking of people, territory, state, and you speak about how

01:09:20.600 --> 01:09:24.840
[Amit Varma]: they were notions of Hindu territory from the Vishnu Purana onwards.

01:09:24.840 --> 01:09:29.800
[Amit Varma]: But you know, as far as the Hindu people were concerned, there's no canonical book or institution.

01:09:29.800 --> 01:09:34.440
[Amit Varma]: You just have a bunch of, you know, a plethora of cultural practices as you put it.

01:09:34.440 --> 01:09:37.720
[Amit Varma]: And you know, of course, there are arguments about historians, whether there was an actual

01:09:37.720 --> 01:09:44.440
[Amit Varma]: Hindu consciousness till our colonial overlords came and sort of spread that narrative.

01:09:44.440 --> 01:09:47.800
[Amit Varma]: Now, you know, and the closest thing that came to a Hindu state was, of course, Shivaji's

01:09:47.800 --> 01:09:48.800
[Amit Varma]: Maratha Kingdom.

01:09:48.800 --> 01:09:52.560
[Amit Varma]: Now, I want to sort of go to 1906 and 1909.

01:09:52.560 --> 01:09:55.920
[Amit Varma]: And one of the very interesting things that you point out, and again, it's an event in

01:09:55.920 --> 01:10:00.920
[Amit Varma]: history that has massive consequences and has literally shaped our country even today,

01:10:00.920 --> 01:10:07.020
[Amit Varma]: which is the British conception of the sort of elections that they would have in India.

01:10:07.020 --> 01:10:12.120
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, the demographic anxiety that they lead to among Hindus here, can you elaborate

01:10:12.120 --> 01:10:13.120
[Amit Varma]: on that a bit?

01:10:13.120 --> 01:10:15.340
[Guest]: So, Amit, you've asked two questions, right?

01:10:15.340 --> 01:10:20.280
[Guest]: One is the debate on who is a Hindu, what is Hinduism, right?

01:10:20.280 --> 01:10:23.040
[Guest]: And why this is a very tough question to answer.

01:10:23.040 --> 01:10:26.480
[Guest]: The second question you asked is, what does elections do to that, right?

01:10:26.480 --> 01:10:30.240
[Guest]: How does elections put unique pressure on trying to answer this question?

01:10:30.240 --> 01:10:38.680
[Guest]: To come to the first one, Hinduism has 3,000 castes, as many sub-castes, so many different

01:10:38.680 --> 01:10:40.840
[Guest]: languages and dialects, right?

01:10:40.840 --> 01:10:45.480
[Guest]: So it has a lot of internal diversity, both theologically as well as in practice.

01:10:45.480 --> 01:10:49.960
[Guest]: To add to that, it doesn't have a Quran, it doesn't have an authoritative textbook, and

01:10:49.960 --> 01:10:52.120
[Guest]: this cannot be emphasized.

01:10:52.120 --> 01:10:57.320
[Guest]: Some people say it's the Vedas, but the Lingayat community of Karnataka is an anti-Vedic movement,

01:10:57.320 --> 01:10:58.320
[Guest]: right?

01:10:58.320 --> 01:10:59.320
[Guest]: They are Hindu, right?

01:10:59.320 --> 01:11:03.680
[Guest]: And it also doesn't have an authoritative institution, unlike the Vatican.

01:11:03.680 --> 01:11:08.840
[Guest]: So therefore, a clear answer, an authoritative answer to the question, what is Hinduism or

01:11:08.840 --> 01:11:11.160
[Guest]: who is a Hindu, is not available.

01:11:11.160 --> 01:11:12.160
[Guest]: That's not available.

01:11:12.160 --> 01:11:17.840
[Guest]: Nonetheless, I push back against, let's say, Marxist scholars who argue that therefore

01:11:17.840 --> 01:11:21.840
[Guest]: there was no such Hinduism until British rule.

01:11:21.840 --> 01:11:25.240
[Guest]: So they say that there is Christianity, there is Islam, but there is no such, that's not

01:11:25.240 --> 01:11:26.240
[Guest]: true.

01:11:26.240 --> 01:11:30.880
[Guest]: It's not true because A, a core part of Hinduism has been, as you mentioned, sacred geography,

01:11:30.880 --> 01:11:36.000
[Guest]: the idea of a theersthan, which is the snowy mountains on the top and the oceans below,

01:11:36.000 --> 01:11:40.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, and the Indus on one side, and that is there, it is recorded in the Vishnu Purana.

01:11:40.440 --> 01:11:46.040
[Guest]: But even earlier, when you had Greek and Roman visitors to India, they very clearly had a

01:11:46.040 --> 01:11:50.960
[Guest]: sense that on this side of the Indus lies a very particular civilization.

01:11:50.960 --> 01:11:55.000
[Guest]: So one of the things is that while Indians don't have a group consciousness that we are

01:11:55.000 --> 01:11:59.560
[Guest]: Hindu or we are Indian, any outsider was able to say that this is a distinctive civilization,

01:11:59.560 --> 01:12:00.560
[Guest]: right?

01:12:00.560 --> 01:12:04.240
[Guest]: And even the word India comes from the word Indus in that sense.

01:12:04.240 --> 01:12:07.920
[Guest]: So I push back against the idea that there is no such Hinduism.

01:12:07.920 --> 01:12:12.400
[Guest]: But nonetheless, because of these factors of Hinduism, the lack of an authoritative

01:12:12.400 --> 01:12:19.080
[Guest]: institution and the lack of a text, what is Hinduism or to put it differently, Hindu group

01:12:19.080 --> 01:12:22.080
[Guest]: consciousness has been harder to identify, right?

01:12:22.080 --> 01:12:25.600
[Guest]: That you are a Hindu, I am a Hindu, therefore, I should give you a job, right?

01:12:25.600 --> 01:12:29.240
[Unknown]: Because that means answering the question, what is Hinduism to which there are multiple

01:12:29.240 --> 01:12:35.240
[Guest]: answers, even though, you know, there is unity in diversity to articulate it by Hindus themselves

01:12:35.240 --> 01:12:36.640
[Unknown]: have been very hard.

01:12:36.640 --> 01:12:41.120
[Guest]: The first articulation of that happens by some scholars argue that it's the Vishnu

01:12:41.120 --> 01:12:42.120
[Guest]: Puranas, right?

01:12:42.120 --> 01:12:47.600
[Guest]: Around the 4th century AD where you have a recognized architecture of Hinduism with the

01:12:47.600 --> 01:12:53.920
[Guest]: sects of Vishnu, Shiva and Devi being the sacred feminine, you know, Jai Mata Di, etc,

01:12:53.920 --> 01:12:54.920
[Guest]: etc.

01:12:54.920 --> 01:12:59.480
[Guest]: Others say it's really the advent of Muslim group, which, you know, created a Hindu consciousness

01:12:59.480 --> 01:13:03.480
[Guest]: and a third group, the more Marxist group says it's British group, right?

01:13:03.480 --> 01:13:08.040
[Guest]: But whichever side you buy, I am much more inclined, by the way, to buy the idea that

01:13:08.040 --> 01:13:13.240
[Guest]: at least from the Vishnu Puranas, you have an architecture that resembles today's Hinduism,

01:13:13.240 --> 01:13:14.240
[Guest]: right?

01:13:14.240 --> 01:13:18.760
[Guest]: So whichever argument you buy, it's pretty clear that by the late 19th century, you have

01:13:18.760 --> 01:13:24.520
[Guest]: the quest for a Hindu identity thinkers like Vivekananda, Bhudev Mukhopadhyay, reform movements

01:13:24.520 --> 01:13:30.000
[Guest]: like the Brahmo Samaj, Arya Samaj are obsessed with the question, what is Hinduism, right?

01:13:30.000 --> 01:13:35.040
[Guest]: And I buy the argument that that is in some sense a response to British rule in India.

01:13:35.040 --> 01:13:42.320
[Guest]: But what this idea of who is a Hindu, what is a Hindu doesn't have is an idea of a state.

01:13:42.320 --> 01:13:48.480
[Guest]: So if you look at, you know, Bankim Chandra's famous book, which had Vande Mataram in it,

01:13:48.480 --> 01:13:50.680
[Unknown]: he doesn't think of an alternative to British rule.

01:13:50.680 --> 01:13:53.440
[Guest]: He is very happy with British rule at the end of it, right?

01:13:53.440 --> 01:13:57.560
[Guest]: So there's no articulation of what a Hindu state looks like.

01:13:57.560 --> 01:14:01.560
[Guest]: That begins to happen, as I argue, and that leads to the second question that you asked,

01:14:01.560 --> 01:14:05.440
[Guest]: only when the British introduced elections, because the moment the British introduced

01:14:05.440 --> 01:14:10.480
[Unknown]: elections in India, it's very limited, very halting, begins in the late 19th century,

01:14:10.480 --> 01:14:15.240
[Guest]: but really, you know, with the Minto-Modi reforms of 1909, and the Montague-Chancellor

01:14:15.240 --> 01:14:20.240
[Guest]: reforms of 1990, it's clear to all Indians that look, one day we will have universal

01:14:20.240 --> 01:14:22.800
[Guest]: adult franchise, and one day the British should leave.

01:14:22.800 --> 01:14:25.960
[Guest]: So that it's a slippery slope to parliamentary democracy.

01:14:25.960 --> 01:14:30.160
[Guest]: This creates amid, and this is a core argument, and is the core original argument of this

01:14:30.160 --> 01:14:33.440
[Guest]: book, panic among Indians, absolute panic, right?

01:14:33.440 --> 01:14:38.200
[Guest]: The Muslim League is created out of the sense of panic, it was largely created by the rich

01:14:38.200 --> 01:14:44.920
[Guest]: zamindars of United Provinces, what is today Uttar Pradesh, many of them were Muslim, right?

01:14:44.920 --> 01:14:49.200
[Guest]: And they had already seen that limited elections in the late 19th century had reduced their

01:14:49.200 --> 01:14:55.320
[Guest]: numbers to something closer to what their numerical strength was, which was 25% in pre-partition

01:14:55.320 --> 01:14:56.320
[Guest]: India.

01:14:56.320 --> 01:15:01.440
[Guest]: And they understood very clearly that once you get into this business of 1% 1 vote, you'll

01:15:01.440 --> 01:15:03.640
[Guest]: end up with the word majority and minority.

01:15:03.640 --> 01:15:08.400
[Guest]: Now, in India, the word majority and minority is every child knows the word, even if you

01:15:08.400 --> 01:15:09.400
[Guest]: don't know English.

01:15:09.400 --> 01:15:13.840
[Guest]: But we forget that that word exists only in the context of elections, otherwise, why does

01:15:13.840 --> 01:15:14.840
[Guest]: numbers matter?

01:15:14.840 --> 01:15:20.600
[Guest]: Elections and 1% 1 vote is the only principle where group size makes a difference in the

01:15:20.600 --> 01:15:23.640
[Unknown]: kind of power you use, and today we take it for granted.

01:15:23.640 --> 01:15:27.240
[Unknown]: In the early 20th century, it wasn't for granted, those were not the ways in which we thought

01:15:27.240 --> 01:15:28.240
[Guest]: about power.

01:15:28.240 --> 01:15:33.600
[Guest]: So the Muslim League is created with the specific intent of lobbying the British to reduce democracy

01:15:33.600 --> 01:15:36.400
[Guest]: defined as 1% 1 vote, right?

01:15:36.400 --> 01:15:42.120
[Guest]: They want parity between the 75% Hindus in India and the 20-25% Muslims, roughly.

01:15:42.120 --> 01:15:48.200
[Guest]: They want parity, which would mean, as Savarkar correctly understood, that 3 Hindu votes is

01:15:48.200 --> 01:15:54.560
[Guest]: equal to 1 Muslim vote, and they are successful because right in the beginning, when the British

01:15:54.560 --> 01:15:58.440
[Guest]: begin to introduce this sort of elections, they have separate electorates for Muslims,

01:15:58.440 --> 01:16:02.360
[Guest]: which is only Muslims vote for only Muslim leaders, right?

01:16:02.360 --> 01:16:06.760
[Guest]: So the Hindu Mahasabha is created as a response to this, the first national Hindu party.

01:16:06.760 --> 01:16:13.280
[Guest]: And their argument is, look, once you begin to do this, the voting power of a Hindu becomes

01:16:13.280 --> 01:16:18.000
[Guest]: much reduced as a Hindu as an individual, which is why, and this is a core argument

01:16:18.000 --> 01:16:23.120
[Guest]: of the book Amit, I argue that Hindu nationalism was very comfortable with elections.

01:16:23.120 --> 01:16:24.120
[Unknown]: Why wouldn't they be?

01:16:24.120 --> 01:16:26.640
[Unknown]: Because Hindus are a social majority in India, right?

01:16:26.640 --> 01:16:32.680
[Guest]: So when you read or hear about the BJP even today, one of the incongruencies you see is

01:16:32.680 --> 01:16:36.760
[Guest]: this is a party obsessed with creating a social majority, right?

01:16:36.760 --> 01:16:40.960
[Guest]: At the same time, it is politically liberal, at least if you hear their words, right?

01:16:40.960 --> 01:16:46.880
[Guest]: So for example, the idea that you should remove Article 370 and Kashmiris and the rest of

01:16:46.880 --> 01:16:51.120
[Unknown]: India must have exactly the same rights is a form of political liberalism that every

01:16:51.120 --> 01:16:52.800
[Guest]: Indian should have the same right.

01:16:52.800 --> 01:16:57.320
[Guest]: But underpinning that idea is an idea that Hindus are a social majority, right?

01:16:57.320 --> 01:17:04.360
[Guest]: That Indian Hindus have about 100 times as much voting power as the Muslim Kashmiri Indians,

01:17:04.360 --> 01:17:05.360
[Guest]: right?

01:17:05.360 --> 01:17:09.840
[Guest]: And therefore equalization will help empower a Hindu social majority.

01:17:09.840 --> 01:17:14.920
[Guest]: And the game, Amit, and I argue that that's also the game behind the creation of the RSS

01:17:14.920 --> 01:17:17.640
[Guest]: is to make sure enough Hindus vote as one.

01:17:17.640 --> 01:17:23.240
[Guest]: The 100-year project of the RSS, the Hindu Mahasabha, the Jansan, is to create a Hindu

01:17:23.240 --> 01:17:24.240
[Guest]: vote bank.

01:17:24.240 --> 01:17:30.000
[Guest]: And Narendra Modi is the apotheosis of that 100-year idea, which is created through elections.

01:17:30.000 --> 01:17:32.000
[Unknown]: Why does this idea matter even today?

01:17:32.000 --> 01:17:37.040
[Unknown]: The idea matters even today because too many critics of BJP, you know, say, oh, they're

01:17:37.040 --> 01:17:38.040
[Unknown]: fascists.

01:17:38.040 --> 01:17:40.400
[Guest]: And think about non-democratic means to get rid of them.

01:17:40.400 --> 01:17:43.360
[Guest]: The only way to defeat Narendra Modi is on election day.

01:17:43.360 --> 01:17:45.000
[Guest]: There's no other way to defeat him.

01:17:45.000 --> 01:17:46.000
[Guest]: They are not fascists.

01:17:46.000 --> 01:17:47.720
[Guest]: They are obsessed with elections.

01:17:47.720 --> 01:17:49.720
[Guest]: They are constituted with elections.

01:17:49.720 --> 01:17:54.040
[Guest]: In fact, a BJP leader offline, I'll tell you the person to add more credibility, unfortunately,

01:17:54.040 --> 01:17:58.280
[Guest]: I can't tell you online, but let me put it this way.

01:17:58.280 --> 01:18:02.160
[Guest]: Imagine the most important BJP leader who you think will say this is likely to be that

01:18:02.160 --> 01:18:03.160
[Guest]: person.

01:18:03.160 --> 01:18:07.880
[Guest]: Told me that, you know, I win elections in order to worship God, right?

01:18:07.880 --> 01:18:10.560
[Guest]: So you worship God through winning elections.

01:18:10.560 --> 01:18:14.440
[Guest]: And I, you know, the argument here is not that the BJP is a religious force in that

01:18:14.440 --> 01:18:15.440
[Guest]: sense.

01:18:15.440 --> 01:18:21.040
[Guest]: It's based on social identity, but that obsession with elections, like just now, Amit, while

01:18:21.040 --> 01:18:25.520
[Guest]: we are recording this, the Hyderabad municipal elections are going on, municipal elections.

01:18:25.520 --> 01:18:31.120
[Guest]: And you had Narendra Modi going there ostensibly to see some vaccine, but really to campaign

01:18:31.120 --> 01:18:32.120
[Unknown]: for it.

01:18:32.120 --> 01:18:33.120
[Guest]: Amit Shah has gone, Yogi Adityanath has gone.

01:18:33.120 --> 01:18:38.920
[Guest]: And at the very same time, Rahul Gandhi and his mother are holidaying in Goa.

01:18:38.920 --> 01:18:41.600
[Guest]: And I think his sister is holidaying in Himachal Pradesh.

01:18:41.600 --> 01:18:45.280
[Guest]: I may be wrong on the facts a little bit, but roughly.

01:18:45.280 --> 01:18:46.680
[Guest]: Why does the BJP do that?

01:18:46.680 --> 01:18:50.760
[Guest]: Because elections constitutes that, but that's, I'm not giving them a free pass by saying

01:18:50.760 --> 01:18:51.760
[Guest]: that.

01:18:51.760 --> 01:18:56.520
[Guest]: I'm just saying that, what do you think will happen if in a group based society where Indians,

01:18:56.520 --> 01:19:01.760
[Guest]: every part of an Indian life is based on groups, you suddenly introduce a principle of one

01:19:01.760 --> 01:19:03.040
[Guest]: person, one vote.

01:19:03.040 --> 01:19:06.640
[Guest]: It's not that overnight Indians are going to become like Swiss citizens who vote on

01:19:06.640 --> 01:19:07.640
[Guest]: the basis of interest.

01:19:07.640 --> 01:19:12.200
[Guest]: Instead, the game is who is a Hindu, how do we redefine that, right?

01:19:12.200 --> 01:19:16.680
[Guest]: And it's not just Hindu nationalists who are doing this, you have the creation of a Dravidian

01:19:16.680 --> 01:19:20.240
[Unknown]: identity in Tamil Nadu, which is a majority identity, right?

01:19:20.240 --> 01:19:24.760
[Unknown]: Kashi Ram understands that you can create an anti upper caste identity, which is the

01:19:24.760 --> 01:19:27.840
[Guest]: Bahujan identity, which is about 80% of India.

01:19:27.840 --> 01:19:35.840
[Guest]: So democracy in a group based society incentivizes politicians to constantly expand group size

01:19:35.840 --> 01:19:39.560
[Guest]: to conjure up majorities so that they can win elections, right?

01:19:39.560 --> 01:19:44.880
[Guest]: And in that sense, the BJP is a natural product of what you get when you introduce elections

01:19:44.880 --> 01:19:45.880
[Guest]: in India.

01:19:45.880 --> 01:19:46.880
[Amit Varma]: No, that's fascinating.

01:19:46.880 --> 01:19:49.600
[Amit Varma]: And I'm going to sort of try to unpack that layer by layer.

01:19:49.600 --> 01:19:54.000
[Amit Varma]: But first of all, you just gave us two examples of sentences that do two things that both

01:19:54.000 --> 01:19:58.560
[Amit Varma]: tell and show, you know, when Narendra Modi going to a municipal election or Rahul Gandhi

01:19:58.560 --> 01:20:04.440
[Amit Varma]: holidaying in Goa, both tell you a mundane fact, but also show you something, something

01:20:04.440 --> 01:20:05.440
[Amit Varma]: larger within that.

01:20:05.440 --> 01:20:10.000
[Guest]: But if I was writing this Amit, just to tell your listeners who are into writing, I would

01:20:10.000 --> 01:20:14.160
[Amit Varma]: edit the gyaan, I would just tell you these facts, you know, and put it in a way, and

01:20:14.160 --> 01:20:17.160
[Amit Varma]: the facts would speak for themselves, put it in a way in which the facts speak for them.

01:20:17.160 --> 01:20:21.920
[Amit Varma]: But that happens only in draft number nine or 10.

01:20:21.920 --> 01:20:25.320
[Amit Varma]: You know, you're intimidating everyone with all this talk of draft number nine or 10,

01:20:25.320 --> 01:20:30.680
[Amit Varma]: or I'll get it right in draft 18 and all of that, to sort of go back to this narrative.

01:20:30.680 --> 01:20:33.960
[Amit Varma]: And you know, another interesting thing that strikes me, and this is again, sort of how

01:20:33.960 --> 01:20:40.360
[Amit Varma]: circumstances can shape history that, you know, in 1906, you have this talk of elections,

01:20:40.360 --> 01:20:44.960
[Amit Varma]: and therefore, as a, you know, to protect their standing within the elites, a Muslim

01:20:44.960 --> 01:20:45.960
[Amit Varma]: League is formed.

01:20:45.960 --> 01:20:51.080
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, in 1909, you have the Minto-Modli reforms, and, you know, suddenly Hindus realized

01:20:51.080 --> 01:20:53.000
[Amit Varma]: three votes are going to be equal to one.

01:20:53.000 --> 01:20:57.160
[Amit Varma]: And then you have various other things happening as a response to that, including the Hindu

01:20:57.160 --> 01:21:01.960
[Amit Varma]: Massacre in 1915, with Lala Lajpatra and Mother Mohan Malviya, because, and they're a pressure

01:21:01.960 --> 01:21:04.160
[Amit Varma]: group within the Congress to begin with.

01:21:04.160 --> 01:21:07.640
[Amit Varma]: And then a number of interesting things happen, as you point out in the book, and you know,

01:21:07.640 --> 01:21:10.440
[Amit Varma]: I've spoken about on previous episodes and all of that.

01:21:10.440 --> 01:21:15.880
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, it's one is a whole Khilafat movement, which really makes no cohesive sense,

01:21:15.880 --> 01:21:21.720
[Amit Varma]: because, you know, one party to that, you know, the Ali brothers and all that are agitating

01:21:21.720 --> 01:21:26.920
[Amit Varma]: for this larger Muslim Ummah and the other party Mahatma Gandhi is talking about an Indian

01:21:26.920 --> 01:21:29.520
[Amit Varma]: state and the two don't sort of go together.

01:21:29.520 --> 01:21:33.880
[Amit Varma]: And many people view that as appeasement or selling out or, you know, what the hell is

01:21:33.880 --> 01:21:35.220
[Amit Varma]: the Congress doing?

01:21:35.220 --> 01:21:38.840
[Amit Varma]: And eventually that drives the Mahasabha away from the Congress as well.

01:21:38.840 --> 01:21:43.080
[Amit Varma]: And in the 20s, because of what is happening, because of this, what you call the demographic

01:21:43.080 --> 01:21:48.100
[Amit Varma]: anxiety, you also have the different strands of Hindutva come together.

01:21:48.100 --> 01:21:52.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, there is Savarkar and one could argue that, you know, if you look at Savarkar

01:21:52.440 --> 01:21:57.920
[Amit Varma]: pre-imprisonment, he's actually always, he's never saying anything anti-Muslim, but then

01:21:57.920 --> 01:22:03.400
[Amit Varma]: he's radicalized in his time in prison by the torture that he receives at the hands

01:22:03.400 --> 01:22:08.960
[Amit Varma]: of Muslims who are sort of, you know, the Pathans and so on, who are, you know, carrying

01:22:08.960 --> 01:22:13.000
[Amit Varma]: out the torture on the commands of the British and that kind of radicalizes him.

01:22:13.000 --> 01:22:15.120
[Amit Varma]: So that's another interesting circumstance.

01:22:15.120 --> 01:22:19.040
[Amit Varma]: But the two interesting things that happened in the 20s, obviously, is, you know, Savarkar

01:22:19.040 --> 01:22:23.560
[Amit Varma]: writing Hindutva and then the formation of the RSS.

01:22:23.560 --> 01:22:28.720
[Amit Varma]: And because both of them are sort of political and both of them, as you point out, are a

01:22:28.720 --> 01:22:33.920
[Amit Varma]: response in part to this demographic anxiety, you know, both of them, therefore, tend to

01:22:33.920 --> 01:22:34.920
[Amit Varma]: be inclusive.

01:22:34.920 --> 01:22:38.000
[Amit Varma]: How do you build the largest political movement that you can?

01:22:38.000 --> 01:22:42.200
[Amit Varma]: You bring everybody under one umbrella and you, you know, Savarkar, of course, besides

01:22:42.200 --> 01:22:49.360
[Amit Varma]: being an atheist and a lover of beef was also a sort of, you know, against caste.

01:22:49.360 --> 01:22:54.920
[Amit Varma]: And the RSS, you point out, was actually when you look at Hindu organizations, the RSS was

01:22:54.920 --> 01:22:58.200
[Amit Varma]: fairly radical because they didn't care about caste either.

01:22:58.200 --> 01:23:01.120
[Amit Varma]: They just wanted to bring everybody under the Hindu umbrella.

01:23:01.120 --> 01:23:03.040
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about this.

01:23:03.040 --> 01:23:10.160
[Amit Varma]: And why does this, you know, impression persist among the elites today that the BJP is a casteist

01:23:10.160 --> 01:23:14.400
[Amit Varma]: party when clearly, as you know, Prashant Jha wrote in How the BJP Wins, he quoted a

01:23:14.400 --> 01:23:17.480
[Amit Varma]: Dalit scholar as saying that they are the Dalit party of India.

01:23:17.480 --> 01:23:20.240
[Amit Varma]: They get more Dalit votes than everybody else.

01:23:20.240 --> 01:23:22.440
[Amit Varma]: So you know, why does that impression persist?

01:23:22.440 --> 01:23:27.800
[Amit Varma]: And tell me then a little bit about, you know, how the sort of the evolution of this sort

01:23:27.800 --> 01:23:28.800
[Guest]: of thinking.

01:23:28.800 --> 01:23:32.960
[Guest]: So, I mean, that's a good question, but that has a complex answer, right, which is the

01:23:32.960 --> 01:23:37.960
[Guest]: question you're asking is that the relationship between Hindu nationalism and caste, and that's

01:23:37.960 --> 01:23:40.000
[Guest]: a complex set of answers.

01:23:40.000 --> 01:23:44.160
[Guest]: I think that the headline news for me, you know, which is something you just said, which

01:23:44.160 --> 01:23:49.280
[Guest]: is that given that traditional Hinduism is so hierarchical, Hindu nationalism is the

01:23:49.280 --> 01:23:54.720
[Guest]: most progressive element of traditional Hinduism when it comes to caste, right?

01:23:54.720 --> 01:24:00.440
[Guest]: On the other hand, traditional Hinduism was very accommodating of multiple sects, multiple

01:24:00.440 --> 01:24:05.560
[Guest]: religious practices, you know, the apocryphal stories of when Arab Muslim traders landed

01:24:05.560 --> 01:24:10.080
[Guest]: in Kerala, local Muslims only helped build the mosque, right?

01:24:10.080 --> 01:24:14.200
[Guest]: On the other hand, Hindu nationalism is much more exclusive and regressive when it comes

01:24:14.200 --> 01:24:15.200
[Guest]: to religion.

01:24:15.200 --> 01:24:19.840
[Guest]: So this is the, many of the critics of the BJP just don't understand this, that if it

01:24:19.840 --> 01:24:24.120
[Guest]: was just in upper caste body, it would get 20% of the vote, you can't win.

01:24:24.120 --> 01:24:30.560
[Guest]: So it is this mix of being a progressive force for Hindus, or let's say the most progressive

01:24:30.560 --> 01:24:35.640
[Guest]: force for Hindus, let me qualify that, while being an out and out exclusive force for Muslims,

01:24:35.640 --> 01:24:39.720
[Guest]: specifically also Christians, also Muslims, that's what gives it this edge.

01:24:39.720 --> 01:24:43.560
[Guest]: And of course, the core argument of the book is that edge is defined by democracy.

01:24:43.560 --> 01:24:48.480
[Guest]: That once you introduce elections as an incentive to create majority, so as Hindus are post

01:24:48.480 --> 01:24:53.480
[Unknown]: independence about, you know, 80% of India, you just have to unite half of them and part

01:24:53.480 --> 01:24:58.280
[Unknown]: of uniting half of them is to pick on another, but half of them is also to organize meals

01:24:58.280 --> 01:25:00.560
[Guest]: between Brahmins and Dalits, right?

01:25:00.560 --> 01:25:07.120
[Guest]: So for example, the critics today are right in criticizing the BJP for these anti-love

01:25:07.120 --> 01:25:12.440
[Guest]: jihad laws, right? and because there's no empirical evidence that this is true at all.

01:25:12.440 --> 01:25:13.440
[Guest]: And I agree with that.

01:25:13.440 --> 01:25:18.800
[Guest]: But what they omit is that the VHP has spent a lot of time financially encouraging inter-caste

01:25:18.800 --> 01:25:19.800
[Guest]: marriages.

01:25:19.800 --> 01:25:25.320
[Guest]: So in a local village, you know, boy and girl of a different community try to marry, sometimes

01:25:25.320 --> 01:25:30.240
[Guest]: the local VHP person you have to go to, to protect yourself against the against the parents.

01:25:30.240 --> 01:25:33.160
[Guest]: And if you don't see this, then you're living in fool's paradise.

01:25:33.160 --> 01:25:37.240
[Unknown]: And I think many of the critics of the BJP, you know, they get very comfortable saying

01:25:37.240 --> 01:25:40.800
[Unknown]: over their fascist, which means you don't have to mobilize against them on the ground.

01:25:40.800 --> 01:25:44.600
[Unknown]: You don't have to actually convince your fellow citizens that look, vote for somebody else.

01:25:44.600 --> 01:25:50.480
[Guest]: Instead, you can write op-eds in like fancy newspapers and foreign, it may help your career,

01:25:50.480 --> 01:25:53.000
[Unknown]: but it doesn't change BJP at all.

01:25:53.000 --> 01:25:57.520
[Guest]: But you know, the deeper question you asked Amit, the relationship between caste and Hindu

01:25:57.520 --> 01:25:59.360
[Guest]: nationalism is complex.

01:25:59.360 --> 01:26:06.280
[Guest]: The RSS is created not just as an upper caste organization, but as an organization created

01:26:06.280 --> 01:26:12.480
[Guest]: by a few families from one specific or a couple of specific communities within Maharashtra

01:26:12.480 --> 01:26:15.480
[Guest]: Brahmins, the Karade and the Desha Brahmins communities.

01:26:15.480 --> 01:26:21.880
[Guest]: And I think that every single Sarsanchalak or head of the RSS, except one, has been a

01:26:21.880 --> 01:26:22.880
[Unknown]: Marathi speaking Brahmin.

01:26:22.880 --> 01:26:23.880
[Unknown]: Right.

01:26:23.880 --> 01:26:28.680
[Unknown]: So that tells you that the critics are not wrong in saying that the BJP originally is

01:26:28.680 --> 01:26:33.720
[Unknown]: and even today, if you look at the data, the heart of the BJP is still upper caste consolidation.

01:26:33.720 --> 01:26:35.720
[Guest]: So I don't want to go away from that.

01:26:35.720 --> 01:26:40.720
[Guest]: But if you wear a mask for a hundred years, Amit, that mask looks like your face and you

01:26:40.720 --> 01:26:45.640
[Guest]: know, that the outreach that they've been doing, even in the 1930s itself, back then

01:26:45.640 --> 01:26:51.360
[Unknown]: itself, Bhotse as an RSS member was part of the anti-caste or temple entry movement there.

01:26:51.360 --> 01:26:55.480
[Guest]: Now you can say that today's Dalits find that patronizing, right, saying that what do you

01:26:55.480 --> 01:26:56.480
[Unknown]: feel about reservations?

01:26:56.480 --> 01:27:01.040
[Unknown]: Well, when Mandal Commission is announced on August 1990, I have a whole chapter on

01:27:01.040 --> 01:27:02.040
[Guest]: that.

01:27:02.040 --> 01:27:06.680
[Guest]: Advani is under a lot of pressure from his upper caste base to oppose Mandal Commission

01:27:06.680 --> 01:27:07.680
[Guest]: recommendations.

01:27:07.680 --> 01:27:09.120
[Guest]: But actually he supports them.

01:27:09.120 --> 01:27:12.680
[Guest]: He asked for an extension of quota for the upper caste poor, which is what Narendra

01:27:12.680 --> 01:27:14.480
[Guest]: Modi has literally done now.

01:27:14.480 --> 01:27:19.400
[Unknown]: But otherwise he supports the Mandal Commission and had he not done that, had he opposed it,

01:27:19.400 --> 01:27:21.240
[Unknown]: the BJP would have remained an upper caste party.

01:27:21.240 --> 01:27:23.880
[Unknown]: He went against the core base, right?

01:27:23.880 --> 01:27:28.360
[Guest]: Today, as prime minister, Narendra Modi has done as much for reservations, right?

01:27:28.360 --> 01:27:32.760
[Guest]: As any prime minister that India has had, maybe Baahubali Singh, again, that's not a

01:27:32.760 --> 01:27:34.160
[Guest]: coincidence, right?

01:27:34.160 --> 01:27:38.360
[Guest]: So if you don't like the BJP, at least understand your enemy, right?

01:27:38.360 --> 01:27:44.520
[Guest]: And understand why is it that a tea seller's son from an oil pressing OBC caste in Gujarat,

01:27:44.520 --> 01:27:45.520
[Guest]: right?

01:27:45.520 --> 01:27:51.560
[Guest]: Who doesn't have a strong family background, joins the RSS, not just for social mobility,

01:27:51.560 --> 01:27:55.080
[Guest]: but for a sense of brotherhood and fellow feeling, I'm referring, of course, to Narendra

01:27:55.080 --> 01:27:56.080
[Guest]: Modi.

01:27:56.080 --> 01:28:01.120
[Guest]: If you don't understand this part, which goes along, what is an advertised rebuff to Muslims

01:28:01.120 --> 01:28:06.200
[Guest]: right from the beginning of the RSS, it's very hard to defeat it, you know?

01:28:06.200 --> 01:28:11.640
[Guest]: And this, you know, the idea, as you know, Amit, and as many of your listeners know,

01:28:11.640 --> 01:28:17.360
[Guest]: many Indian Muslim communities have practices that are on the ground are Hindu.

01:28:17.360 --> 01:28:24.240
[Guest]: And they operate on the many of these communities, Bhoras, Pujas, etc, etc, Jinnah's own community,

01:28:24.240 --> 01:28:29.360
[Guest]: you know, they live their lives on the border of, you know, Islam and Hinduism.

01:28:29.360 --> 01:28:34.600
[Guest]: The RSS doesn't like that, because just like they want to dilute the boundaries within

01:28:34.600 --> 01:28:39.000
[Guest]: Hinduism, they want to erect strong barriers between Hindu and outside, because if you

01:28:39.000 --> 01:28:42.600
[Guest]: don't do that, you can't answer the question, who is a Hindu or what is Hinduism?

01:28:42.600 --> 01:28:46.440
[Guest]: And if you don't have a clear answer to that question, how are you going to get all these

01:28:46.440 --> 01:28:48.320
[Guest]: people to vote as one?

01:28:48.320 --> 01:28:52.320
[Guest]: So right at the beginning, I have a story in the book that Hegdevar notices that there's

01:28:52.320 --> 01:28:57.040
[Guest]: a Muslim Sufi shrine near Nagpur, which are also attracting Hindu devotees.

01:28:57.040 --> 01:29:01.360
[Guest]: He doesn't like that, you know, he pushes, and my job, as you noticed in the book is

01:29:01.360 --> 01:29:03.480
[Guest]: not to support the BJP or to oppose it.

01:29:03.480 --> 01:29:05.160
[Guest]: And I hope I have succeeded in that.

01:29:05.160 --> 01:29:06.160
[Guest]: That's not my game here.

01:29:06.160 --> 01:29:08.160
[Guest]: But I have to say the truth, right?

01:29:08.160 --> 01:29:12.240
[Guest]: And the truth is that from the beginning, it has been suspicious of Muslims.

01:29:12.240 --> 01:29:15.560
[Guest]: And from the beginning, it has tried to reach out to lower caste Hindus.

01:29:15.560 --> 01:29:19.520
[Amit Varma]: No, and you know, the most fascinating phrase from this conversation so far is what you

01:29:19.520 --> 01:29:24.280
[Amit Varma]: just said about if you wear a mask for 100 years, it becomes a face, which leads me to

01:29:24.280 --> 01:29:29.240
[Amit Varma]: the sort of the meta musing that is there anything called a face or, you know, is it

01:29:29.240 --> 01:29:31.840
[Amit Varma]: all just a succession of masks?

01:29:31.840 --> 01:29:32.840
[Amit Varma]: But leave that aside.

01:29:32.840 --> 01:29:36.120
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you know, the other thing I'd also sort of like to point out to my listeners

01:29:36.120 --> 01:29:41.000
[Amit Varma]: as well reading this book, I had a sense that this is a very fascinating companion book

01:29:41.000 --> 01:29:44.800
[Amit Varma]: to Akshay Mukul's book on the Gita Press, because that is about the social and cultural

01:29:44.800 --> 01:29:51.440
[Amit Varma]: movement of Hindu nationalism, while yours focuses on the political side of it.

01:29:51.440 --> 01:29:54.480
[Amit Varma]: And for me, the two sort of come together very well.

01:29:54.480 --> 01:29:59.680
[Guest]: Can I give you just a little bit of a counter because, you know, I've read the book, I cite

01:29:59.680 --> 01:30:04.000
[Guest]: the book, I love Akshay Mukul and he's also been on your podcast, right?

01:30:04.000 --> 01:30:09.760
[Guest]: But just to push back just a little bit, see his evidence for is that, you know, the Gita

01:30:09.760 --> 01:30:14.840
[Unknown]: Press is I think he looks at Kalyan, which is the magazine of Gita Press, and definitely

01:30:14.840 --> 01:30:17.560
[Guest]: many of the views there are regressive, right?

01:30:17.560 --> 01:30:20.880
[Guest]: My only pushback is that's not Hindu nationalism, right?

01:30:20.880 --> 01:30:25.680
[Guest]: So really, if you want to look at where what political Hinduism is doing, look at the RSS

01:30:25.680 --> 01:30:27.680
[Guest]: mouthpiece organizer, right?

01:30:27.680 --> 01:30:30.000
[Guest]: Look at some of the BJP magazines, right?

01:30:30.000 --> 01:30:34.600
[Guest]: And that's the point that I'm pushing that when it comes to caste issues, especially

01:30:34.600 --> 01:30:40.360
[Guest]: your even gender, but mainly caste, the Hindu nationalism or the institutions of Hindu nationalism,

01:30:40.360 --> 01:30:46.760
[Guest]: like the RSS or the BJP or the Jansan are far more progressive than the Gita Press is.

01:30:46.760 --> 01:30:51.880
[Guest]: The Gita Press is really the organ of traditional Hinduism, right?

01:30:51.880 --> 01:30:56.840
[Guest]: And so that's one, you know, debate, I would say me and Akshay Mukul have that, look, he's

01:30:56.840 --> 01:30:57.840
[Unknown]: right, right?

01:30:57.840 --> 01:31:02.720
[Unknown]: But in many ways, the RSS and BJP want to go away from the stuff that is appearing in

01:31:02.720 --> 01:31:08.440
[Guest]: Kalyan, because if Hindu nationalism becomes the description that Akshay Mukul has from

01:31:08.440 --> 01:31:12.520
[Guest]: the Gita Press, how on earth is it going to get votes, you know?

01:31:12.520 --> 01:31:14.960
[Amit Varma]: No, no, that's absolutely a fair point.

01:31:14.960 --> 01:31:16.680
[Amit Varma]: And the picture is vast and complex.

01:31:16.680 --> 01:31:20.280
[Amit Varma]: So you know, the elephant will have a leg, the elephant will have a tail, the elephant

01:31:20.280 --> 01:31:21.600
[Amit Varma]: will have a trunk.

01:31:21.600 --> 01:31:26.760
[Amit Varma]: Tell me now a little bit about many people today speak of Hindu nationalism as if it

01:31:26.760 --> 01:31:27.760
[Amit Varma]: is one thing.

01:31:27.760 --> 01:31:32.320
[Amit Varma]: But of course, see, you know, the RSS is going in one direction, Savarkar is going in another

01:31:32.320 --> 01:31:33.320
[Amit Varma]: direction.

01:31:33.320 --> 01:31:37.880
[Amit Varma]: In fact, there are clashes between them, because Savarkar, of course, is political in 1942.

01:31:37.880 --> 01:31:42.680
[Amit Varma]: He wants the RSS foot soldiers to help him in the elections and the RSS just says no

01:31:42.680 --> 01:31:43.680
[Amit Varma]: and get lost.

01:31:43.680 --> 01:31:47.560
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, that is at the point where, you know, shortly after that, Nathuram Godse starts

01:31:47.560 --> 01:31:51.880
[Amit Varma]: his magazine, where he rails against two things, Mahatma Gandhi and the RSS.

01:31:51.880 --> 01:31:52.880
[Guest]: Agrani, Agrani.

01:31:52.880 --> 01:31:53.880
[Amit Varma]: Agrani.

01:31:53.880 --> 01:31:59.160
[Amit Varma]: So, so tell me a little bit about this sort of very interesting relationship between the

01:31:59.160 --> 01:32:02.160
[Amit Varma]: RSS and Savarkar and how they view each other.

01:32:02.160 --> 01:32:05.800
[Amit Varma]: And of course, the Hindu Mahasabha as well, which is very prominent then, but doesn't

01:32:05.800 --> 01:32:09.680
[Amit Varma]: seem so much now in hindsight, but because it's almost disappeared.

01:32:09.680 --> 01:32:13.880
[Amit Varma]: But at the time, that was like another prominent sort of force.

01:32:13.880 --> 01:32:16.720
[Guest]: Yeah, it was the first national Hindu party.

01:32:16.720 --> 01:32:17.720
[Guest]: Yeah, absolutely.

01:32:17.720 --> 01:32:23.440
[Guest]: I mean, the larger question that you're asking is that, you know, Hindu nationalism, as you

01:32:23.440 --> 01:32:25.440
[Guest]: said, you know, speaks in many voices, right?

01:32:25.440 --> 01:32:30.680
[Guest]: Then how is, but it's nonetheless, I mean, I can't emphasize this organizationally united,

01:32:30.680 --> 01:32:36.200
[Guest]: but the Hindu nationalism today is basically comes out of an organizational constellation

01:32:36.200 --> 01:32:38.280
[Unknown]: with the RSS as the sun.

01:32:38.280 --> 01:32:42.440
[Guest]: There's no two ways about it, you know, and you have plenty of quote-unquote Hindu organizations

01:32:42.440 --> 01:32:46.640
[Guest]: like the Karni Seva, which I would not call Hindu nationalist in that sense, because it

01:32:46.640 --> 01:32:48.400
[Unknown]: doesn't arise out of the RSS.

01:32:48.400 --> 01:32:52.200
[Guest]: You may have some similarities and thoughts, this, that, but they are not, right?

01:32:52.200 --> 01:32:56.960
[Guest]: Or no shortage of Akhadas, you know, who have like similar views to like the BJP, but they

01:32:56.960 --> 01:33:01.080
[Guest]: are, they don't report to Modi and there's no way Modi can reach out to them.

01:33:01.080 --> 01:33:06.760
[Guest]: So Hindu nationalism organizationally is actually quite clear, what is, if you tell me the organization,

01:33:06.760 --> 01:33:07.760
[Unknown]: I'll tell you.

01:33:07.760 --> 01:33:08.760
[Guest]: Is it Hindu?

01:33:08.760 --> 01:33:10.560
[Guest]: Like Hindu Mahasabha today is outside the paper.

01:33:10.560 --> 01:33:15.800
[Guest]: Hindu Mahasabha, for example, you know, they celebrate Godse's statues, the RSS is furious

01:33:15.800 --> 01:33:19.240
[Unknown]: with that, but you can't say anything because the Hindu Mahasabha today has nothing to do

01:33:19.240 --> 01:33:20.240
[Guest]: with the RSS.

01:33:20.240 --> 01:33:24.480
[Guest]: Yet, as you pointed out, they speak in different voices and look, this is really the heart

01:33:24.480 --> 01:33:28.560
[Unknown]: of the book, which is, that's why the title Jugalbandi, which is that the power of Hindu

01:33:28.560 --> 01:33:34.120
[Guest]: nationalism is that just like in a Jugalbandi, you have people playing different instruments,

01:33:34.120 --> 01:33:35.120
[Guest]: different music.

01:33:35.120 --> 01:33:39.600
[Guest]: Nonetheless, you're able to make music together and RSS celebrates that.

01:33:39.600 --> 01:33:44.040
[Amit Varma]: So for example, right now, just to give you one more example, before we go to the Savarkar

01:33:44.040 --> 01:33:49.160
[Guest]: Bolvalkar question then, but something to sort of link your listeners to today, many

01:33:49.160 --> 01:33:54.880
[Amit Varma]: of the labor reforms that the Narendra Modi government has made, right, is opposed by

01:33:54.880 --> 01:33:55.880
[Guest]: the RSS trade union.

01:33:55.880 --> 01:33:56.880
[Guest]: How do you make sense of it?

01:33:56.880 --> 01:33:57.880
[Guest]: Right?

01:33:57.880 --> 01:33:58.880
[Unknown]: They opposed it.

01:33:58.880 --> 01:33:59.880
[Unknown]: How do you make sense of it?

01:33:59.880 --> 01:34:00.880
[Guest]: Both are part of the RSS, right?

01:34:00.880 --> 01:34:06.880
[Guest]: Narendra Modi is an ex-pracharak, BJP is very much part of the RSS family, right?

01:34:06.880 --> 01:34:12.080
[Unknown]: But you have to, and the answer is that the RSS has always seen this like an Indian family.

01:34:12.080 --> 01:34:15.600
[Unknown]: In Indian family, the, you know, legendarily the mother-in-law and daughter-in-law don't

01:34:15.600 --> 01:34:16.600
[Unknown]: get along.

01:34:16.600 --> 01:34:17.600
[Unknown]: Brothers may be fighting, right?

01:34:17.600 --> 01:34:21.720
[Guest]: The father and the daughter may be having some issues, but nonetheless, at the end of

01:34:21.720 --> 01:34:22.720
[Guest]: the day, you stay united.

01:34:22.720 --> 01:34:27.800
[Guest]: And again, you know, we can discuss in detail, the heart of this book's argument is that

01:34:27.800 --> 01:34:31.720
[Unknown]: the reason the BJP wins, there are many reasons, but I would say the cutting edge reason is

01:34:31.720 --> 01:34:35.280
[Guest]: that even when they disagree, they don't split, right?

01:34:35.280 --> 01:34:39.200
[Guest]: And the reason they do that is from a very early age, they're taught a certain version

01:34:39.200 --> 01:34:44.440
[Guest]: of Hindu history, where you have these different battles where Hindus lose on the battlefield

01:34:44.440 --> 01:34:47.920
[Guest]: because at key moments, they stab each other in the back, right?

01:34:47.920 --> 01:34:48.920
[Guest]: This is the key.

01:34:48.920 --> 01:34:51.440
[Guest]: And so that becomes an organizational ethic for today.

01:34:51.440 --> 01:34:56.320
[Unknown]: Now coming back to the question that you asked on Savarkar and Golwalkar, you know, people

01:34:56.320 --> 01:34:59.400
[Guest]: whisper about it, but I think I'm one of the first people to point out that they didn't

01:34:59.400 --> 01:35:00.400
[Guest]: like each other.

01:35:00.400 --> 01:35:04.720
[Unknown]: They didn't like each other, one for the reason you mentioned, which is that Golwalkar wanted

01:35:04.720 --> 01:35:06.600
[Guest]: nothing to do with politics, right?

01:35:06.600 --> 01:35:11.160
[Guest]: Because he was more focused on the social aspect of Hindu nationalism, which is creating

01:35:11.160 --> 01:35:13.520
[Guest]: a common Hindu social identity.

01:35:13.520 --> 01:35:18.000
[Guest]: But as I pointed out, that itself is spurred by elections, otherwise, why do you care whether

01:35:18.000 --> 01:35:22.600
[Guest]: 40% of Hindus think alike, except you want to make them into a whole pack, right?

01:35:22.600 --> 01:35:26.160
[Unknown]: This is Savarkar who straight up wanted to contest elections.

01:35:26.160 --> 01:35:30.560
[Unknown]: He became the head of the Hindu Mahasabha, he wanted to win elections and he kept losing.

01:35:30.560 --> 01:35:35.440
[Guest]: And he kept losing because the Hindus of that period voted for the better Hindu leader,

01:35:35.440 --> 01:35:38.160
[Guest]: better I mean electorally, Mahatma Gandhi, right?

01:35:38.160 --> 01:35:42.800
[Unknown]: And that was Savarkar's huge anger, he hated Gandhi not because they were different, but

01:35:42.800 --> 01:35:46.280
[Guest]: actually they were pretty similar in that they were appealing to, right?

01:35:46.280 --> 01:35:51.160
[Guest]: It's just that Gandhi was able to get the Hindu vote by not being anti-Muslim.

01:35:51.160 --> 01:35:53.600
[Unknown]: So that was Savarkar's game, right?

01:35:53.600 --> 01:35:57.120
[Unknown]: And but what so that was definitely one reason for the difference.

01:35:57.120 --> 01:36:00.880
[Guest]: But another bigger reason is that they were very different personalities.

01:36:00.880 --> 01:36:07.400
[Guest]: Now this obsession with unity that the RSS has, with teamwork over all else means that

01:36:07.400 --> 01:36:11.720
[Guest]: these kind of brilliant geniuses, you know, who are prima donnas don't have a place in

01:36:11.720 --> 01:36:12.720
[Guest]: it.

01:36:12.720 --> 01:36:18.320
[Amit Varma]: And I hope that it is descriptively accurate to say that the RSS doesn't have too many

01:36:18.320 --> 01:36:19.320
[Guest]: smart people in it.

01:36:19.320 --> 01:36:23.720
[Guest]: And I mean it in a very descriptive sense, because you know, think about any organization

01:36:23.720 --> 01:36:29.080
[Guest]: Amit that you've worked in, you'd always have these brilliant jerks, I'm sure in Crick

01:36:29.080 --> 01:36:33.000
[Guest]: Info you also found these guys, they're very good, you know, they're very bright, but it's

01:36:33.000 --> 01:36:35.560
[Guest]: impossible to work with them in an organization.

01:36:35.560 --> 01:36:40.120
[Guest]: The RSS is obsessed about weeding these people out, you know, so people like Subramanian

01:36:40.120 --> 01:36:45.280
[Guest]: Swami, M.L.Sondhi, who was a Rhodes Scholar, Balraj Madhok, who I spent a lot of time with,

01:36:45.280 --> 01:36:50.160
[Unknown]: very bright, much brighter than the average RSS pacharak, you know, a genuine thinker,

01:36:50.160 --> 01:36:54.000
[Guest]: right, but just will not subordinate the self to the organization.

01:36:54.000 --> 01:36:59.680
[Guest]: In contrast, someone like Atal Bihari Vajpayee, also very bright, but not an intellectual,

01:36:59.680 --> 01:37:04.080
[Unknown]: knew that when what he wanted the RSS was unwilling to do, he would, as I say in the

01:37:04.080 --> 01:37:07.640
[Guest]: book, sulk on mute, but he wouldn't leave the party.

01:37:07.640 --> 01:37:11.440
[Unknown]: And I think Savarkar was a little different, he was a bit of a prima donna.

01:37:11.440 --> 01:37:16.800
[Guest]: So even today, when I talk to people in the RSS, I mean, Amit Shah has his photograph,

01:37:16.800 --> 01:37:20.360
[Guest]: you know, in his drawing room, Advani has his photograph in the drawing room.

01:37:20.360 --> 01:37:24.520
[Guest]: But they also see him as a little bit of a warning that, you know, if you want to succeed

01:37:24.520 --> 01:37:30.160
[Guest]: in India, you, you know, you may have Savarkar's grand ideas, but you can't behave like him,

01:37:30.160 --> 01:37:31.160
[Amit Varma]: you know.

01:37:31.160 --> 01:37:36.760
[Amit Varma]: No, and that's like one of the sort of fascinating stances, this whole RSS is organizational

01:37:36.760 --> 01:37:41.320
[Amit Varma]: ethic, where you never speak out against your own organization or against your colleagues

01:37:41.320 --> 01:37:42.320
[Guest]: in public.

01:37:42.320 --> 01:37:43.320
[Guest]: Externally.

01:37:43.320 --> 01:37:44.320
[Unknown]: Exactly.

01:37:44.320 --> 01:37:45.320
[Unknown]: In public, that's what I said.

01:37:45.320 --> 01:37:48.440
[Guest]: I'm able to show you plenty of situations where internally, there's a far more robust

01:37:48.440 --> 01:37:53.160
[Unknown]: debate happening, at least in the period that I'm writing about that happens in the Congress.

01:37:53.160 --> 01:37:57.080
[Unknown]: The Congress, they talk about democracy, democracy, there's zero internal democracy, right?

01:37:57.080 --> 01:38:01.360
[Guest]: Whereas, you know, I point out that when Vajpayee government was in power, there was no shortage

01:38:01.360 --> 01:38:06.720
[Guest]: of his own cabinet ministers like Murali Manohar Joshi, Ram Nayak from his own party, who opposed

01:38:06.720 --> 01:38:09.600
[Guest]: his policies and spoke up in cabinet, you know.

01:38:09.600 --> 01:38:13.800
[Amit Varma]: I ended my last sentence by saying in public, you did not wait for that.

01:38:13.800 --> 01:38:17.760
[Amit Varma]: But yeah, I completely agree with you that the Congress is the opposite ethos, it might

01:38:17.760 --> 01:38:21.560
[Amit Varma]: seem there is no dissent, but that is because it is not allowed, there is no internal dissent

01:38:21.560 --> 01:38:22.560
[Amit Varma]: either.

01:38:22.560 --> 01:38:24.960
[Amit Varma]: And that's a whole sort of different story.

01:38:24.960 --> 01:38:28.360
[Amit Varma]: And the examples you pointed out that the people who spoke out like Balraj Madhok and

01:38:28.360 --> 01:38:31.760
[Amit Varma]: Subramanian Swamy in the 70s, basically left the party.

01:38:31.760 --> 01:38:37.800
[Amit Varma]: So Vajpayee knew that even if he disagrees, he's got to hold his peace and sort of bide

01:38:37.800 --> 01:38:38.800
[Amit Varma]: his time.

01:38:38.800 --> 01:38:45.200
[Amit Varma]: Now, tell me a little bit about how this ethos comes from their reading of history, specifically

01:38:45.200 --> 01:38:51.680
[Amit Varma]: you point in your book to the Third Battle of Panipat in 1761, as having a profound lesson

01:38:51.680 --> 01:38:54.800
[Amit Varma]: for the whole Hindu nationalist movement.

01:38:54.800 --> 01:39:01.480
[Amit Varma]: And this sort of this particular organizational ethic that you stick together as a team, no

01:39:01.480 --> 01:39:04.600
[Amit Varma]: matter how much you disagree in private also comes directly from there.

01:39:04.600 --> 01:39:06.960
[Guest]: Tell me a little bit about the importance of that.

01:39:06.960 --> 01:39:10.840
[Guest]: Well, so let me tell you, let me tell you the research answer, which is how I got to

01:39:10.840 --> 01:39:11.840
[Guest]: the answer.

01:39:11.840 --> 01:39:12.840
[Guest]: Right?

01:39:12.840 --> 01:39:14.760
[Guest]: Because rather than just tell you the answer how I got there.

01:39:14.760 --> 01:39:18.040
[Guest]: So I've been, you know, I interviewed about 200 people for this book, many of them from

01:39:18.040 --> 01:39:19.040
[Guest]: the RSS, BJP.

01:39:19.040 --> 01:39:24.360
[Guest]: And I was, I mean, I was, I was struck by how they kept referring to history.

01:39:24.360 --> 01:39:26.840
[Guest]: Of course, it was their version of history.

01:39:26.840 --> 01:39:30.800
[Guest]: So, you know, at my university, if I asked a historian, you know, they will say, where's

01:39:30.800 --> 01:39:31.800
[Guest]: the footnote?

01:39:31.800 --> 01:39:32.800
[Guest]: That's not the point.

01:39:32.800 --> 01:39:38.080
[Guest]: In fact, many of them like, not just, they write historical fiction, for example, K.M.

01:39:38.080 --> 01:39:39.080
[Guest]: Munshi.

01:39:39.080 --> 01:39:44.600
[Guest]: Amit Shah's, you know, one of his favorite books is K.M. Munshi's trilogy on the last

01:39:44.600 --> 01:39:47.160
[Guest]: Hindu king of Gujarat, Sidhrath Jai Singh.

01:39:47.160 --> 01:39:48.160
[Guest]: It's not a historical book.

01:39:48.160 --> 01:39:53.320
[Guest]: It's like, you know, will you call Amish Tripathi, who I like a lot, his writing, he's not a

01:39:53.320 --> 01:39:54.320
[Guest]: historian, right?

01:39:54.320 --> 01:39:58.640
[Guest]: You can say at the most is historical fiction, but that forms the basis for, you know, what

01:39:58.640 --> 01:40:01.680
[Unknown]: the RSS reads and understands about India.

01:40:01.680 --> 01:40:05.720
[Guest]: And so I had, you know, this was, I was in Chandrapur, right, this is about a couple

01:40:05.720 --> 01:40:06.720
[Guest]: of years back.

01:40:06.720 --> 01:40:09.320
[Unknown]: That's about an hour, about a few hours away from Nagpur.

01:40:09.320 --> 01:40:14.240
[Unknown]: And I just visited the family home of Mohan Bhagwat, who is the head of the RSS.

01:40:14.240 --> 01:40:19.560
[Guest]: And I spoke to his brother, Ravindra, who is the only person in the family who has given

01:40:19.560 --> 01:40:20.560
[Unknown]: me permission to quote, right.

01:40:20.560 --> 01:40:25.360
[Guest]: And, you know, he spoke a lot about Shakha and, you know, he's a very low key lawyer.

01:40:25.360 --> 01:40:29.800
[Guest]: By the way, another sign that, you know, if you go and meet like the brother or a sister

01:40:29.800 --> 01:40:34.320
[Guest]: of a top congressman, they'd be living in style, you know, but the, you know, the brother

01:40:34.320 --> 01:40:38.640
[Guest]: of the, you know, the, what many people think is the man who really runs India is living

01:40:38.640 --> 01:40:41.920
[Guest]: in a low key style and low key house and going to a trial court.

01:40:41.920 --> 01:40:43.920
[Unknown]: It's a very different ethic.

01:40:43.920 --> 01:40:49.040
[Guest]: So the one thing is that I have to prevent myself, and this is an aside, I mean, of not

01:40:49.040 --> 01:40:54.480
[Guest]: becoming too admiring of the RSS, because many of the views which I disagree with, was

01:40:54.480 --> 01:40:59.400
[Unknown]: at odds with their personal austerity, you know, which I, it's very hard not to admire.

01:40:59.400 --> 01:41:04.080
[Unknown]: And then I meet people in the Congress who in many instances, I may even agree with,

01:41:04.080 --> 01:41:08.320
[Guest]: but then I see all of them that, you know, they may be wearing these like kurta pajamas,

01:41:08.320 --> 01:41:10.600
[Guest]: but they have like a 30,000 rupee pen, right.

01:41:10.600 --> 01:41:14.000
[Unknown]: And I'm like, you know, like, what kind of hypocrisy is this?

01:41:14.000 --> 01:41:17.840
[Unknown]: I think most Indians, you know, that's the flavor of the Congress that irritates them,

01:41:17.840 --> 01:41:18.840
[Guest]: right.

01:41:18.840 --> 01:41:24.800
[Unknown]: It's a massive hypocrisy between the frugal talk and the actual flashy lifestyle, right?

01:41:24.800 --> 01:41:25.800
[Unknown]: The RSS is the reverse.

01:41:25.800 --> 01:41:28.800
[Unknown]: So anyway, we have spoken a lot about the shakhas.

01:41:28.800 --> 01:41:33.320
[Guest]: Now, for those of you listeners who don't know it, the shakha is the principal unit

01:41:33.320 --> 01:41:34.320
[Guest]: of the RSS.

01:41:34.320 --> 01:41:39.920
[Guest]: You go for about an hour to an open ground and with about 20-30 people, you perform group

01:41:39.920 --> 01:41:44.160
[Guest]: exercises for half the time and for half the time, you have an intellectual conversation

01:41:44.160 --> 01:41:50.400
[Guest]: or somebody talks that kind of thing and he was talking about the shakha and then I did

01:41:50.400 --> 01:41:55.200
[Guest]: something that I think academics should do, which is that instead of actually going to

01:41:55.200 --> 01:42:00.360
[Guest]: a shakha at that time, I went on YouTube and saw a lot of shakha videos, you know, which

01:42:00.360 --> 01:42:03.200
[Guest]: I shouldn't, you know, I should have gone to shakha, you know, but I was like obsessed

01:42:03.200 --> 01:42:04.200
[Guest]: that, you know, why not?

01:42:04.200 --> 01:42:08.440
[Guest]: Easy, because all these amateur videos put up by RSS guys on shakha and, you know, my

01:42:08.440 --> 01:42:14.240
[Guest]: Western training, Amit had taught me to see these shakhas, you know, the marching as a

01:42:14.240 --> 01:42:18.360
[Guest]: sign of martial valor, because part of the Western theory of the RSS is that, you know,

01:42:18.360 --> 01:42:22.840
[Guest]: Hindus have a psychological feeling that they're puny compared to the more martial Muslim.

01:42:22.840 --> 01:42:25.320
[Guest]: So you know, this is a way to man up Hindus, right?

01:42:25.320 --> 01:42:30.480
[Guest]: There is some truth to it, but I saw it and I realized that it was more than just, you

01:42:30.480 --> 01:42:31.480
[Guest]: know, marching.

01:42:31.480 --> 01:42:32.480
[Guest]: It was actually synchronization.

01:42:32.480 --> 01:42:33.480
[Guest]: It was teamwork.

01:42:33.480 --> 01:42:38.200
[Guest]: And Amit, I'm sure that in the corporate organization that you have worked, you go for these corporate

01:42:38.200 --> 01:42:39.200
[Guest]: retreats sometimes, right?

01:42:39.200 --> 01:42:43.480
[Guest]: And you play, and I know it's a bit boring, but I think you play these games, right?

01:42:43.480 --> 01:42:44.480
[Guest]: To build team building.

01:42:44.480 --> 01:42:45.480
[Guest]: That's what an RSS shakha is.

01:42:45.480 --> 01:42:53.000
[Guest]: And in a flash, I understood, Amit, that the reading of history actually becomes an organizational

01:42:53.000 --> 01:42:58.160
[Guest]: form that the purpose of the shakha is to tell young Hindus, this is how you work in

01:42:58.160 --> 01:42:59.160
[Guest]: a team.

01:42:59.160 --> 01:43:00.160
[Guest]: This is how you coordinate.

01:43:00.160 --> 01:43:04.000
[Guest]: This is how you stand on each other's shoulder and break the dahi handi, right?

01:43:04.000 --> 01:43:08.040
[Guest]: So there is a martial element, but the core element is teamwork, right?

01:43:08.040 --> 01:43:12.400
[Guest]: And look, nothing I had read prepared me to understand this, but once I saw it, it was

01:43:12.400 --> 01:43:13.400
[Guest]: there all over the place.

01:43:13.400 --> 01:43:17.360
[Guest]: You know, it's one of those hidden in plain sight that the history lesson, and you know,

01:43:17.360 --> 01:43:19.280
[Guest]: frankly, the RSS is obsessed about it.

01:43:19.280 --> 01:43:24.680
[Guest]: So one history lesson that you mentioned was the third battle of Panipat, which was fought

01:43:24.680 --> 01:43:27.680
[Guest]: between Ahmed Shah Abdali from Afghanistan and the Marathas.

01:43:27.680 --> 01:43:32.600
[Guest]: Now this is particularly important because in the 18th century in India was the Maratha

01:43:32.600 --> 01:43:33.600
[Guest]: century.

01:43:33.600 --> 01:43:39.320
[Guest]: As many of your listeners will know, the Marathas controlled from Tanjore all the way to Delhi,

01:43:39.320 --> 01:43:40.320
[Guest]: right?

01:43:40.320 --> 01:43:46.360
[Guest]: They had it under the, this is the Peshwa, the Maratha empire that sort of succeeds Shivaji.

01:43:46.360 --> 01:43:50.600
[Guest]: And the British is a presence in India, but it's a minor presence.

01:43:50.600 --> 01:43:55.840
[Guest]: And the RSS believes that had the Marathas not lost in the third battle of Panipat, because

01:43:55.840 --> 01:43:56.840
[Unknown]: they got annihilated.

01:43:56.840 --> 01:44:02.120
[Unknown]: And that, and not just they got annihilated, even Ahmed Shah Abdali was so badly bruised,

01:44:02.120 --> 01:44:03.560
[Unknown]: he has to leave India.

01:44:03.560 --> 01:44:08.200
[Unknown]: And so the RSS version is that this created a power vacuum in India, that you neither

01:44:08.200 --> 01:44:12.360
[Guest]: had Ahmed Shah Abdali, nor did you have the Marathas, into this power vacuum crept the

01:44:12.360 --> 01:44:13.360
[Guest]: British.

01:44:13.360 --> 01:44:18.800
[Unknown]: Not just my view, in the 2019 elections, literally what Amit Shah said, and again, if anyone's

01:44:18.800 --> 01:44:22.920
[Guest]: paying attention, they should have said, why is this man, whose popular impression is that

01:44:22.920 --> 01:44:25.920
[Guest]: look, he doesn't leave, he's not a cultivated man in that sense.

01:44:25.920 --> 01:44:31.280
[Guest]: He's actually referring to very precise historical examples, when he's talking about defeating

01:44:31.280 --> 01:44:33.760
[Guest]: the Congress in 2019.

01:44:33.760 --> 01:44:38.600
[Guest]: And immediately those two things struck me, I would say it's the inside of the book, which

01:44:38.600 --> 01:44:44.840
[Guest]: is that the reading of history has created a ethos, where whatever they do, they don't

01:44:44.840 --> 01:44:47.560
[Guest]: split, because their view is that Indians always split.

01:44:47.560 --> 01:44:52.520
[Guest]: And they're not wrong in that, that anyone who works in India realizes that we are lousy

01:44:52.520 --> 01:44:54.720
[Guest]: team players, lousy.

01:44:54.720 --> 01:44:59.040
[Guest]: You have like, I'm sure in your time in Cricinfo or wherever else you work, there would have

01:44:59.040 --> 01:45:03.560
[Guest]: been five, six different factions, people who are like, have lunch together, other people

01:45:03.560 --> 01:45:04.560
[Guest]: have lunch.

01:45:04.560 --> 01:45:10.240
[Guest]: In meetings, they will say yes, yes, but then behind your back, they'll say no, no.

01:45:10.240 --> 01:45:14.040
[Guest]: Everyone who's listening to this podcast will sympathize with this problem, that you deal

01:45:14.040 --> 01:45:16.680
[Guest]: with Indian groups, you deal with factions.

01:45:16.680 --> 01:45:21.560
[Guest]: The RSS has understood it, and they spend all their time trying to solve this problem.

01:45:21.560 --> 01:45:23.040
[Guest]: That's why they really love it.

01:45:23.040 --> 01:45:26.720
[Guest]: That if you look in India, it's a massive competitive advantage, parties are splitting

01:45:26.720 --> 01:45:27.720
[Unknown]: all the time.

01:45:27.720 --> 01:45:31.240
[Unknown]: Today, the Congress is one, Congress versus Congress, Kapil Sibal is saying something,

01:45:31.240 --> 01:45:32.240
[Guest]: Chidambaram is saying something.

01:45:32.240 --> 01:45:38.600
[Guest]: It's not even as the RSS points out that having a single caste party, or, you know, will prevent

01:45:38.600 --> 01:45:39.600
[Guest]: this.

01:45:39.600 --> 01:45:44.080
[Guest]: Samadwadi party is a Yadav party, but the uncle and the nephew are at loggerheads, right?

01:45:44.080 --> 01:45:49.160
[Unknown]: Bahujan Samad party is a Jatav party, but Mayawati will never promote another Jatav.

01:45:49.160 --> 01:45:52.400
[Guest]: That's why Chandrashekhar Azad Rawan wants to set out his own party.

01:45:52.400 --> 01:45:54.960
[Guest]: Because if she does that, then her vote bank gets cut.

01:45:54.960 --> 01:45:59.560
[Guest]: This is the water that we drink, that we don't like behaving properly in a group when it

01:45:59.560 --> 01:46:01.240
[Guest]: comes to achieving a goal.

01:46:01.240 --> 01:46:07.280
[Guest]: The RSS's absolute genius has been to understand it, it is an exclusionary version, right?

01:46:07.280 --> 01:46:10.840
[Guest]: And the point is not whether the history lesson is accurate.

01:46:10.840 --> 01:46:16.200
[Guest]: The point is that that history lesson has become a very powerful tool for organizational

01:46:16.200 --> 01:46:17.200
[Guest]: renewal.

01:46:17.200 --> 01:46:21.600
[Guest]: Because when it comes to the third battle of Panipat, the RSS analysis is the Marathas

01:46:21.600 --> 01:46:25.320
[Guest]: were lost because they were fighting with each other, the Rajputs and the Jats did not

01:46:25.320 --> 01:46:26.320
[Guest]: help.

01:46:26.320 --> 01:46:30.640
[Guest]: The Maratha army was not a centralized command, unlike the RSS today, it was a confederacy

01:46:30.640 --> 01:46:35.440
[Guest]: where the Peshwas were normally in charge, but you had the Holkas, you had the Sindhias,

01:46:35.440 --> 01:46:37.520
[Guest]: you know, or you had the Bhosles.

01:46:37.520 --> 01:46:41.880
[Guest]: For them, this is the analysis of the weakness of the Hindu past.

01:46:41.880 --> 01:46:46.080
[Guest]: And I would say that the moment that just struck me, that after that conversation on

01:46:46.080 --> 01:46:52.440
[Guest]: Shaka, seeing this on YouTube, and then linking it to Israeli, that kind of thing takes three

01:46:52.440 --> 01:46:53.440
[Guest]: years to get.

01:46:53.440 --> 01:46:58.760
[Guest]: So, you know, to the researchers who are listening amongst you, that insight, right, is not a

01:46:58.760 --> 01:46:59.760
[Guest]: simple insight.

01:46:59.760 --> 01:47:05.600
[Guest]: You have to immerse yourself, you have to speak to people, and then one day in a flash,

01:47:05.600 --> 01:47:06.600
[Guest]: something strikes you.

01:47:06.600 --> 01:47:09.520
[Guest]: And now when I say it to RSS people, they are saying, yeah, it's true.

01:47:09.520 --> 01:47:15.240
[Guest]: In fact, I got one of the few reviews that have already come, the book is very early,

01:47:15.240 --> 01:47:18.800
[Unknown]: has been from an RSS gentleman who says that, look, he's the first English speaking guy

01:47:18.800 --> 01:47:21.720
[Guest]: to understand us, even though I am critical, right?

01:47:21.720 --> 01:47:22.720
[Guest]: Because this is their self-image.

01:47:22.720 --> 01:47:28.280
[Guest]: And I sometimes, and look, once a book like this comes out, people will say that, oh,

01:47:28.280 --> 01:47:32.080
[Guest]: this is obvious, this, that, or we should have found this earlier, but sometimes insights

01:47:32.080 --> 01:47:33.080
[Guest]: don't happen that way, right?

01:47:33.080 --> 01:47:37.560
[Guest]: Like first time someone comes up with an idea, you always say, oh, we should have known this

01:47:37.560 --> 01:47:40.960
[Guest]: 50 years earlier, but that never happens like that.

01:47:40.960 --> 01:47:46.280
[Amit Varma]: No, and it was fascinating to me, not just, you know, the third battle of Panipat in 1761,

01:47:46.280 --> 01:47:52.040
[Amit Varma]: but even, you know, that whole sense of how so many contemporary grievances can be in

01:47:52.040 --> 01:47:58.480
[Amit Varma]: some way, you know, given an origin story or given that huge story in history, for example,

01:47:58.480 --> 01:48:02.240
[Amit Varma]: you point out about how Amit Shah, of course, grew up in a household where he was surrounded

01:48:02.240 --> 01:48:05.880
[Amit Varma]: by books and was well read and one of the other books by K M Munshi, which was a big

01:48:05.880 --> 01:48:11.040
[Amit Varma]: influence on him and pretty much, you know, generations of Hindu nationalist leaders was

01:48:11.040 --> 01:48:18.480
[Amit Varma]: the one about the sacking of Somnath by Mahmud of Ghazni, which is, you know, which is an

01:48:18.480 --> 01:48:25.200
[Amit Varma]: interesting example of how, you know, history can be weaponized and history can shape the

01:48:25.200 --> 01:48:27.840
[Amit Varma]: psychology of people and just how they look at the world.

01:48:27.840 --> 01:48:31.000
[Amit Varma]: And it also kind of strikes me and, you know, we'll take an aside and I'll ask you this

01:48:31.000 --> 01:48:35.880
[Amit Varma]: now instead of at the end, that, you know, does it also work the other way that does

01:48:35.880 --> 01:48:39.800
[Amit Varma]: the politics that you have, then affect the history that you do?

01:48:39.800 --> 01:48:44.600
[Amit Varma]: And you've managed to keep it out of this book to the extent that I have absolutely

01:48:44.600 --> 01:48:47.840
[Amit Varma]: no idea what your political leanings are like.

01:48:47.840 --> 01:48:53.000
[Amit Varma]: So is that something that you consciously, you know, warn yourself about in terms of

01:48:53.000 --> 01:48:55.680
[Amit Varma]: even the facts that you choose to gather and so on?

01:48:55.680 --> 01:49:01.080
[Amit Varma]: And then do you sort of, you know, between the first and the 18th draft, as it were,

01:49:01.080 --> 01:49:07.000
[Amit Varma]: do you take, you know, not just yourself, but even your prism in a sense out of it?

01:49:07.000 --> 01:49:08.360
[Amit Varma]: Is that something that you thought about?

01:49:08.360 --> 01:49:09.360
[Guest]: I try my best.

01:49:09.360 --> 01:49:10.560
[Guest]: I mean, that's exactly right.

01:49:10.560 --> 01:49:13.000
[Guest]: I try my best to do that.

01:49:13.000 --> 01:49:18.560
[Guest]: Because look, the book I'm writing on the BJP before Modi is the most polarizing question

01:49:18.560 --> 01:49:20.360
[Unknown]: in India right now, right?

01:49:20.360 --> 01:49:22.320
[Guest]: I don't want to add fuel to that fire.

01:49:22.320 --> 01:49:27.600
[Guest]: Otherwise, every morning, there are like a million people on Twitter who are doing this.

01:49:27.600 --> 01:49:32.200
[Guest]: I don't want the book to fall prey to, is it a pro-BJP book, is it an anti-Modi book?

01:49:32.200 --> 01:49:35.760
[Guest]: You know, that's very, very hard to do, very hard to do.

01:49:35.760 --> 01:49:40.920
[Guest]: And especially when the book is not an oblique intervention, it's a central question, which

01:49:40.920 --> 01:49:43.840
[Guest]: is what is Hindu nationalism and why do they win?

01:49:43.840 --> 01:49:50.160
[Guest]: So the challenge before me was how do I make such a political, polarized topic, non-political

01:49:50.160 --> 01:49:54.480
[Unknown]: and non-polarized in a way in which you can read the book, whether you hate the BJP or

01:49:54.480 --> 01:49:57.600
[Unknown]: like the BJP, and this will help you understand it.

01:49:57.600 --> 01:50:02.280
[Guest]: And I just did a video interview with Barkha Dutt and she told me, look, this book didn't

01:50:02.280 --> 01:50:03.280
[Guest]: make me angry.

01:50:03.280 --> 01:50:04.280
[Guest]: She told me offline.

01:50:04.280 --> 01:50:09.200
[Guest]: And she said, I like that about the book and I hope that's how other people read it.

01:50:09.200 --> 01:50:13.880
[Guest]: This book is not going to get your BP up and let's take on Modi or let me become an internet

01:50:13.880 --> 01:50:14.880
[Unknown]: bug.

01:50:14.880 --> 01:50:18.720
[Guest]: This is not, it has a lot of masala, so you enjoy yourself, right?

01:50:18.720 --> 01:50:24.640
[Guest]: But I wanted it not to be an intervention that becomes a political football.

01:50:24.640 --> 01:50:29.880
[Guest]: And at least in the very early days, but so far I've been able to do it, but yes, I obsessed

01:50:29.880 --> 01:50:30.880
[Guest]: about this.

01:50:30.880 --> 01:50:36.400
[Guest]: I spent a lot of time thinking about how I should move, how I should move my views on

01:50:36.400 --> 01:50:37.400
[Unknown]: the way.

01:50:37.400 --> 01:50:41.280
[Unknown]: On the other hand, while I didn't want to be controversial, I had a fidelity to the

01:50:41.280 --> 01:50:42.280
[Guest]: truth.

01:50:42.280 --> 01:50:43.840
[Unknown]: And sometimes the truth is confidential.

01:50:43.840 --> 01:50:48.880
[Guest]: So for example, on the Gujarat riots, I don't hold back at all, as you've read, right?

01:50:48.880 --> 01:50:54.240
[Guest]: I know I detail precise, you know, exactly what happened, you know, what, and too often

01:50:54.240 --> 01:50:56.400
[Guest]: we ask, is Modi guilty, Modi not guilty?

01:50:56.400 --> 01:51:00.400
[Guest]: That's not the real question on the Gujarat riot, it was a massive connivance and state

01:51:00.400 --> 01:51:04.440
[Guest]: failure that you have to understand in that sense, right?

01:51:04.440 --> 01:51:10.760
[Guest]: So while I wanted to be quote unquote neutral, neutrality doesn't mean on the one hand, on

01:51:10.760 --> 01:51:11.760
[Unknown]: the other hand, right?

01:51:11.760 --> 01:51:15.560
[Unknown]: Because then when you have violence happening, when you have murder happening, neutrality

01:51:15.560 --> 01:51:19.440
[Unknown]: is not that, Oh, somebody said it's a murder, other person said it was deserved.

01:51:19.440 --> 01:51:21.200
[Unknown]: That's a very wrong way to do it, right?

01:51:21.200 --> 01:51:22.760
[Guest]: But it's a tightrope walk, Amit.

01:51:22.760 --> 01:51:25.920
[Guest]: So there's no like template for how to achieve this.

01:51:25.920 --> 01:51:29.080
[Unknown]: But I exactly what you said, I thought about it a lot.

01:51:29.080 --> 01:51:33.160
[Guest]: And I also, you know, over time, Amit, I've learned to respect the leader that the leader

01:51:33.160 --> 01:51:38.200
[Guest]: basically, you know, once the leader realizes there's a relationship between the evidence

01:51:38.200 --> 01:51:43.200
[Guest]: you give, and the arguments you give, then the leader is able to forgive a lot, you know,

01:51:43.200 --> 01:51:48.000
[Guest]: even if the leader disagrees with you completely, whereas very quickly a leader figures out

01:51:48.000 --> 01:51:52.640
[Guest]: if you have an agenda or an angle, and that's what I tried my best to prevent happening.

01:51:52.640 --> 01:51:56.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, in fact, speaking of neutrality, there's this famous thing, there's this famous

01:51:56.960 --> 01:52:02.080
[Amit Varma]: cliche about journalists, in fact, a cliched story about how if you are, if one person

01:52:02.080 --> 01:52:06.360
[Amit Varma]: says it is raining, and the other person says it is not raining, your job is not to report

01:52:06.360 --> 01:52:10.960
[Amit Varma]: them both, it is to go to the window and tell the reader whether it is raining or not.

01:52:10.960 --> 01:52:14.180
[Amit Varma]: Except in certain cases, you don't know whether it's a window or a TV screen.

01:52:14.180 --> 01:52:15.360
[Amit Varma]: So what do you do?

01:52:15.360 --> 01:52:19.520
[Amit Varma]: So to get back to the narrative of the book, you know, we've spoken about the difference

01:52:19.520 --> 01:52:24.040
[Amit Varma]: between Savarkar and the RSS and how the RSS is totally uninterested in politics.

01:52:24.040 --> 01:52:29.240
[Amit Varma]: At one point, there's this juicy quote, where Savarkar, you know, says to the RSS in 1942,

01:52:29.240 --> 01:52:31.880
[Amit Varma]: quote, what will you organize all these people for?

01:52:31.880 --> 01:52:34.360
[Amit Varma]: Will you make achar with them?

01:52:34.360 --> 01:52:39.960
[Amit Varma]: End quote, and, and then you point out how the assassination of Mahatma Gandhi and the

01:52:39.960 --> 01:52:45.080
[Amit Varma]: aftermath of that, when you know, the RSS is sort of ostracized and banned for a few

01:52:45.080 --> 01:52:49.320
[Amit Varma]: months, while the Hindu Mahasabha is not, because they have a minister in the cabinet

01:52:49.320 --> 01:52:54.480
[Amit Varma]: and all of that makes the RSS realize that no, they do need some kind of political presence

01:52:54.480 --> 01:52:55.480
[Amit Varma]: as well.

01:52:55.480 --> 01:53:00.240
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about sort of this shift in the thinking and how it came about.

01:53:00.240 --> 01:53:05.400
[Guest]: Firstly, I mean, I think in this, in the debate between Savarkar and RSS, I think the RSS

01:53:05.400 --> 01:53:08.240
[Guest]: has turned out to be right and Savarkar wrong.

01:53:08.240 --> 01:53:13.840
[Guest]: In that, this, you know, let's just take Assam, right, where a few years ago, BJP came to

01:53:13.840 --> 01:53:14.840
[Guest]: power in Assam.

01:53:14.840 --> 01:53:19.480
[Guest]: Now, the BJP came to power in Assam because for the last 20 years, the RSS has been going

01:53:19.480 --> 01:53:20.480
[Guest]: there and marching, right?

01:53:20.480 --> 01:53:25.160
[Guest]: They have these shakhas, they've been putting money, you know, and they don't put money,

01:53:25.160 --> 01:53:28.520
[Guest]: the shakha people pay the money themselves, but they've been putting like organizational

01:53:28.520 --> 01:53:33.560
[Guest]: energy into it and basically, you know, tilling the land, creating, you know, social unity

01:53:33.560 --> 01:53:39.360
[Guest]: among Hindus while demonizing Muslims, it's a both ways, that is also a jugal bandhi.

01:53:39.360 --> 01:53:44.480
[Guest]: That takes, you know, that social transformation then becomes the underpinning for the BJP's

01:53:44.480 --> 01:53:45.480
[Unknown]: rise in Assam.

01:53:45.480 --> 01:53:50.760
[Guest]: Savarkar didn't see that, like Savarkar just thought that it would be politics that would

01:53:50.760 --> 01:53:54.960
[Guest]: unite Hindus together, right, without that, there has to be an underlying social basis

01:53:54.960 --> 01:53:55.960
[Guest]: that also pushes it.

01:53:55.960 --> 01:54:01.360
[Guest]: And we didn't discuss earlier that part of that social basis is bottom up, which is organization,

01:54:01.360 --> 01:54:02.360
[Guest]: etc, etc.

01:54:02.360 --> 01:54:05.720
[Guest]: And I told you, I'm not quite sure about the data on that.

01:54:05.720 --> 01:54:09.040
[Unknown]: But the other is top down, which is what the RSS does, right?

01:54:09.040 --> 01:54:13.560
[Guest]: And that people tend to underestimate that, like even today, for example, Amit, and this

01:54:13.560 --> 01:54:18.520
[Guest]: is a good sign of the RSS that if you go to any district in India, and I go and sometimes

01:54:18.520 --> 01:54:22.360
[Guest]: I interview district collectors, district magistrates, who are the raja and ranis of

01:54:22.360 --> 01:54:26.320
[Guest]: the district, right, the collector, and the collector will, you know, even states which

01:54:26.320 --> 01:54:30.880
[Guest]: are under BJP, they will say, we don't know who the local pracharak is, because you know,

01:54:30.880 --> 01:54:35.120
[Guest]: it's not, you know, whereas, every time you have a new collector who comes to a district,

01:54:35.120 --> 01:54:39.160
[Guest]: all the local doctor, the local head of a this, that, the local head of a granite mill

01:54:39.160 --> 01:54:42.360
[Guest]: will all form a queue to do salaam, right?

01:54:42.360 --> 01:54:44.320
[Unknown]: The RSS person never does it.

01:54:44.320 --> 01:54:49.200
[Guest]: And that's because the RSS doesn't need the state, it's the BJP state that needs the RSS.

01:54:49.200 --> 01:54:50.200
[Guest]: That is remarkable, right?

01:54:50.200 --> 01:54:55.880
[Guest]: I mean, I show you here in this book, the kind of personal sacrifices RSS people make

01:54:55.880 --> 01:54:57.880
[Unknown]: without accepting anything in return.

01:54:57.880 --> 01:55:01.560
[Guest]: And again, these are all things that other parties should take from it.

01:55:01.560 --> 01:55:06.560
[Guest]: The BSP had this Bahujan Volunteer Force, which was like the RSS, they don't have this,

01:55:06.560 --> 01:55:07.800
[Guest]: I met people there.

01:55:07.800 --> 01:55:11.960
[Unknown]: The Congress has a Seva Dal, which is absolutely pathetic, how many of your listeners even

01:55:11.960 --> 01:55:13.520
[Guest]: know they exist, right?

01:55:13.520 --> 01:55:18.200
[Guest]: So on the first part that you asked that, you know, this debate between Savarkar on

01:55:18.200 --> 01:55:23.600
[Guest]: a pure political project versus the RSS view, which is a pure social project, which is the

01:55:23.600 --> 01:55:28.120
[Guest]: view that it had at that time, right, it's turned out that the social project actually

01:55:28.120 --> 01:55:32.080
[Unknown]: benefits the political project in a way in which Savarkar doesn't understand.

01:55:32.080 --> 01:55:34.280
[Unknown]: That's the enormous power of the RSS.

01:55:34.280 --> 01:55:38.160
[Guest]: The second part of the question you ask is that how does the RSS change its mind?

01:55:38.160 --> 01:55:40.160
[Guest]: And the answer is the murder of the Mahatma.

01:55:40.160 --> 01:55:44.360
[Guest]: I point out in the book that the RSS had no institutional role in it.

01:55:44.360 --> 01:55:48.280
[Guest]: In fact, the Godse Act actually set back Hindu nationalism.

01:55:48.280 --> 01:55:52.840
[Guest]: I mean, one of the counterfactuals that I see is that the partition, the Hindu Mahasabha

01:55:52.840 --> 01:55:58.120
[Guest]: and Savarkar's criticism of Gandhi turns out to be right, that when you begin to appease

01:55:58.120 --> 01:56:01.520
[Guest]: the Muslim League, what you don't, you don't get Hindu-Muslim unity, you get different

01:56:01.520 --> 01:56:02.520
[Guest]: countries.

01:56:02.520 --> 01:56:07.920
[Guest]: Objectively, the Savarkar's view on Congress politics vis-a-vis Muslim League turned out

01:56:07.920 --> 01:56:09.560
[Guest]: to be true, right?

01:56:09.560 --> 01:56:17.040
[Guest]: And with Hindu and Sikh refugees pouring into India after 1947, we see a jump in RSS membership

01:56:17.040 --> 01:56:18.040
[Guest]: and Hindu Mahasabha membership.

01:56:18.040 --> 01:56:22.320
[Guest]: They could have come to power, I mean, far earlier in India compared to 1996, they could

01:56:22.320 --> 01:56:24.560
[Guest]: have come to power far earlier, right?

01:56:24.560 --> 01:56:25.960
[Guest]: Why does that not happen?

01:56:25.960 --> 01:56:31.040
[Guest]: Because the murder of Mahatma, who is a Hindu leader, is linked to the RSS and Hindu Mahasabha,

01:56:31.040 --> 01:56:34.040
[Guest]: at least ideologically, if not institutionally, right?

01:56:34.040 --> 01:56:39.480
[Guest]: And the RSS is banned, Golwalkar in jail, all the pracharaks are put in jail.

01:56:39.480 --> 01:56:43.040
[Unknown]: On the other hand, they are able to notice that the Hindu Mahasabha, which is Savarkar's

01:56:43.040 --> 01:56:46.360
[Guest]: political party, is not banned, right?

01:56:46.360 --> 01:56:52.120
[Guest]: Even though the groups that were the Madanlal, Pahua, Apte, Bodse were all Hindu Mahasabha

01:56:52.120 --> 01:56:53.120
[Unknown]: members, right?

01:56:53.120 --> 01:56:57.840
[Unknown]: And they also realized why, which is that the Hindu Mahasabha is a coalition, is an

01:56:57.840 --> 01:56:59.520
[Unknown]: ally in parliament, right?

01:56:59.520 --> 01:57:03.000
[Guest]: It's the industry minister, Shyam Prasad Mukherjee, who's from the Hindu Mahasabha.

01:57:03.000 --> 01:57:07.760
[Unknown]: And so Nehru and Patel realized that, look, it's a splinter group, not the actual Hindu

01:57:07.760 --> 01:57:08.760
[Guest]: Mahasabha that's doing it.

01:57:08.760 --> 01:57:13.360
[Guest]: And the RSS realized and noticed that the ban that they were put through, which frankly

01:57:13.360 --> 01:57:14.360
[Guest]: is undemocratic.

01:57:14.360 --> 01:57:20.360
[Guest]: Because if there's no evidence to ban someone, to jail someone for this long, while I'm very

01:57:20.360 --> 01:57:24.760
[Unknown]: vocal when it's the BJP that violates civil liberty, what the Congress did to the RSS

01:57:24.760 --> 01:57:31.600
[Guest]: at that time, while had popular support, is to me at least a violation of civil liberties.

01:57:31.600 --> 01:57:36.560
[Unknown]: But the lesson the RSS learned is not a single MP spoke up in parliament in their favor.

01:57:36.560 --> 01:57:40.240
[Unknown]: And even though they wanted nothing to do with the state and government, the government

01:57:40.240 --> 01:57:46.040
[Unknown]: wanted something to do with it, which is why Golwalkar reluctantly in 1951, agrees to the

01:57:46.040 --> 01:57:51.680
[Guest]: setting up of a separate political party, the Jansa, with a lot of RSS members and the

01:57:51.680 --> 01:57:55.840
[Guest]: face would be Shyam Prasad Mukherjee, who has since left the Hindu Mahasabha, to contest

01:57:55.840 --> 01:57:57.720
[Unknown]: in India's first elections.

01:57:57.720 --> 01:58:05.360
[Guest]: So the RSS comes to politics because of Gandhi's murder and its quote-unquote oppression that

01:58:05.360 --> 01:58:09.520
[Guest]: it faces immediately after that, and very quickly, the RSS realizes that its social

01:58:09.520 --> 01:58:13.600
[Guest]: aim and the political aim of the party are actually quite united.

01:58:13.600 --> 01:58:19.120
[Amit Varma]: No, what you said about, you know, the RSS's vision, winning out over Savarkar's is also

01:58:19.120 --> 01:58:23.120
[Amit Varma]: echoed in, you know, one of my favorite quotes about politics, which, you know, all my listeners

01:58:23.120 --> 01:58:25.080
[Amit Varma]: will groan now because they know what's coming.

01:58:25.080 --> 01:58:28.720
[Amit Varma]: But Andrew Breitbart once said, politics is downstream of culture.

01:58:28.720 --> 01:58:35.320
[Amit Varma]: And I think the great triumph of Hindu nationalism comes from the RSS recognizing the truth of

01:58:35.320 --> 01:58:36.320
[Amit Varma]: this, in a sense.

01:58:36.320 --> 01:58:41.880
[Guest]: And sorry to interrupt you again, that's also the failure of the Nehruvian idea of India,

01:58:41.880 --> 01:58:46.200
[Guest]: because they didn't understand the sentence that you just said, that Nehruvian politics

01:58:46.200 --> 01:58:49.240
[Guest]: was seen as unmoved from culture.

01:58:49.240 --> 01:58:52.840
[Amit Varma]: A point that I repeatedly keep making, you know, it's become another trope of my show

01:58:52.840 --> 01:58:56.440
[Amit Varma]: that I ask my guests something I won't ask you because it's too much of a cliche now

01:58:56.440 --> 01:59:01.440
[Amit Varma]: and we have so much else to talk about, but was our relatively liberal constitution imposed

01:59:01.440 --> 01:59:06.160
[Amit Varma]: on an illiberal society and therefore was always that top-down imposition was always

01:59:06.160 --> 01:59:08.440
[Amit Varma]: sort of bound to fail in some way.

01:59:08.440 --> 01:59:12.000
[Amit Varma]: But you know, having said that, I can sort of contradict that immediately by pointing

01:59:12.000 --> 01:59:17.560
[Amit Varma]: out that the first leader of the Jansang, Shama Prasad Mukherjee, in many tellings comes

01:59:17.560 --> 01:59:19.920
[Amit Varma]: across as a remarkably liberal man.

01:59:19.920 --> 01:59:24.360
[Amit Varma]: For example, he left the Hindu Mahasabha because he was upset that they would not admit members

01:59:24.360 --> 01:59:28.360
[Amit Varma]: of other religions, which he thought was completely pointless.

01:59:28.360 --> 01:59:32.600
[Amit Varma]: And I did an episode recently with Rupur Dhaman Singh on the making of the first amendment.

01:59:32.600 --> 01:59:36.640
[Amit Varma]: And there, if you just look at all the arguments and what people are doing across sides, it

01:59:36.640 --> 01:59:41.480
[Amit Varma]: appears to be Shama Prasad Mukherjee, who is a great liberal and Nehru, who is the enemy

01:59:41.480 --> 01:59:42.480
[Amit Varma]: of liberalism.

01:59:42.480 --> 01:59:46.840
[Amit Varma]: And again, all those arguments and all those quotes are in the public domain.

01:59:46.840 --> 01:59:51.320
[Amit Varma]: You know, I was struck by this very intriguing thing that you said about the Bharatiya Jansang

01:59:51.320 --> 01:59:52.920
[Amit Varma]: when it was formed.

01:59:52.920 --> 01:59:57.000
[Amit Varma]: And this is possibly partly because even though, you know, Shama Prasad wants to form it, he

01:59:57.000 --> 02:00:01.760
[Amit Varma]: asked Golwalkar, he says no, but then eventually, you know, enough of Golwalkar's colleagues

02:00:01.760 --> 02:00:02.760
[Amit Varma]: want it.

02:00:02.760 --> 02:00:05.200
[Amit Varma]: So he agrees and a lot of RSS people come in.

02:00:05.200 --> 02:00:11.600
[Amit Varma]: And you speak about how this represents a movement away from primadonnas and ideologues

02:00:11.600 --> 02:00:13.840
[Amit Varma]: towards orators and organizers.

02:00:13.840 --> 02:00:17.760
[Amit Varma]: And primadonnas you've spoken about before, but you speak about how temperamentally they

02:00:17.760 --> 02:00:22.240
[Amit Varma]: are dangerous for an organization, ideologues, you know, you use the word theorems for them

02:00:22.240 --> 02:00:24.480
[Amit Varma]: just as you do temperament for primadonnas.

02:00:24.480 --> 02:00:30.840
[Amit Varma]: But the orators and organizers are interesting because this almost, in a sense, then besieges

02:00:30.840 --> 02:00:36.440
[Amit Varma]: the future of the BJP, of course, today with Modi and Shah, but even earlier than with

02:00:36.440 --> 02:00:41.040
[Amit Varma]: sort of Vajpayee and Advani, which is, you know, the meat of your remarkable book.

02:00:41.040 --> 02:00:46.400
[Amit Varma]: So let's talk about the two of them now and the very different circumstances in which

02:00:46.400 --> 02:00:48.040
[Amit Varma]: they kind of, you know, came to being.

02:00:48.040 --> 02:00:53.120
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about the early Vajpayee because, you know, he's born in Gwalior on Christmas

02:00:53.120 --> 02:00:55.080
[Amit Varma]: Day in 1924.

02:00:55.080 --> 02:01:01.040
[Amit Varma]: And you speak about how Gwalior is a hub for resurgent Hindu identity, in your words.

02:01:01.040 --> 02:01:04.040
[Amit Varma]: And you also say that, you know, Vajpayee's future and therefore India's future could

02:01:04.040 --> 02:01:07.000
[Amit Varma]: have been different had he been born in, say, United Provinces.

02:01:07.000 --> 02:01:13.480
[Amit Varma]: So explain to me a bit of Vajpayee's background and how that sort of shaped him and eventually,

02:01:13.480 --> 02:01:15.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, led him to becoming part of the RSS.

02:01:15.240 --> 02:01:20.520
[Guest]: Well, I mean, coming to the first part of your question, from the very beginning, Hindu

02:01:20.520 --> 02:01:24.680
[Guest]: nationalism has realized that they need an orator and an organizer.

02:01:24.680 --> 02:01:29.680
[Guest]: So the first Jugalbandi in that respect was Shamprasad Mukherjee, who was, you know, the

02:01:29.680 --> 02:01:34.200
[Guest]: youngest vice chancellor of Calcutta University, erudite man, etc, etc.

02:01:34.200 --> 02:01:36.800
[Amit Varma]: He was vice chancellor at the age of 33.

02:01:36.800 --> 02:01:40.680
[Amit Varma]: And no doubt, many people will point out that people at the age of 33 are still doing their

02:01:40.680 --> 02:01:41.680
[Amit Varma]: PhDs in JNU.

02:01:41.680 --> 02:01:42.680
[Amit Varma]: They will snark.

02:01:42.680 --> 02:01:43.680
[Guest]: There you go.

02:01:43.680 --> 02:01:44.680
[Guest]: Right.

02:01:44.680 --> 02:01:50.440
[Unknown]: But Jugalbandi was very, so he was very consciously made the face of the movement because he wanted

02:01:50.440 --> 02:01:52.440
[Guest]: somebody who would speak in Parliament.

02:01:52.440 --> 02:01:57.040
[Guest]: At the same time, you had Dindayal Upadhyay, who was seconded by Guru Golwalkar, who was

02:01:57.040 --> 02:02:02.760
[Guest]: the head of the RSS at that time, to be the Advani for Shamprasad Mukherjee and then, of

02:02:02.760 --> 02:02:03.760
[Guest]: course, you have Vajpayee Advani.

02:02:03.760 --> 02:02:06.680
[Guest]: And now you have Modi and Amit Shah.

02:02:06.680 --> 02:02:13.000
[Guest]: Point being that there's a bit of social engineering that there was a space for someone like Vajpayee.

02:02:13.000 --> 02:02:18.400
[Guest]: And because Shamprasad Mukherjee dies young, right, or dies early, there was a need to

02:02:18.400 --> 02:02:23.200
[Guest]: replace so that to understand Vajpayee's rise, you have to understand Vajpayee's personality,

02:02:23.200 --> 02:02:24.200
[Guest]: etc, etc.

02:02:24.200 --> 02:02:29.720
[Guest]: But the fact that luck, and this is something you referred to beginning, luckily for Vajpayee,

02:02:29.720 --> 02:02:34.360
[Guest]: the very traits he exhibited was something that Hindu nationalism required hugely after

02:02:34.360 --> 02:02:36.840
[Unknown]: the death of Shamprasad Mukherjee.

02:02:36.840 --> 02:02:40.200
[Guest]: But the sort of corollary to that is if it wasn't Vajpayee, it may have been somebody

02:02:40.200 --> 02:02:41.200
[Guest]: else.

02:02:41.200 --> 02:02:45.040
[Guest]: That person may not have had the talent to take the BJP to victory, you know, so many

02:02:45.040 --> 02:02:46.040
[Guest]: decades later.

02:02:46.040 --> 02:02:51.880
[Guest]: So Vajpayee, his family, he's a Kanyakumari Brahmin, they are poor, they are originally

02:02:51.880 --> 02:02:54.280
[Guest]: from Bateshwar in what is today Uttar Pradesh.

02:02:54.280 --> 02:02:59.640
[Guest]: But I think his grandfather moves to Gwalior, which is a princely state, is a princely state

02:02:59.640 --> 02:03:05.720
[Guest]: run by a Hindu king, which is the Maharaja of Gwalior, he's a Maratha, he's a Sindhiya,

02:03:05.720 --> 02:03:06.720
[Guest]: right?

02:03:06.720 --> 02:03:11.480
[Guest]: Again, a progeny of, you know, according to the RSS, you know, the person who made one

02:03:11.480 --> 02:03:14.680
[Guest]: of the mistakes in the third battle of Panipat, right?

02:03:14.680 --> 02:03:19.720
[Guest]: And harsh critics would argue that even today, so many hundred years later, you see a Sindhiya

02:03:19.720 --> 02:03:20.720
[Guest]: splitting the party.

02:03:20.720 --> 02:03:25.360
[Guest]: It's a bit mean, but you know, I am sorry for that.

02:03:25.360 --> 02:03:30.280
[Guest]: So Vajpayee comes, you know, it's a very traditional Gangetic Brahmin family, he wears a sacred

02:03:30.280 --> 02:03:31.280
[Guest]: thread.

02:03:31.280 --> 02:03:36.640
[Guest]: His brother also wears a sacred thread and the RSS happens to come to Gwalior because

02:03:36.640 --> 02:03:37.640
[Guest]: it is Marathi speaking, right?

02:03:37.640 --> 02:03:40.640
[Guest]: Otherwise, it wouldn't have come there that quickly.

02:03:40.640 --> 02:03:46.080
[Guest]: So very soon after the creation of the RSS, you know, it's been able to percolate into

02:03:46.080 --> 02:03:51.040
[Unknown]: Gwalior because the king of the Raja of Gwalior is a Maratha, Marathi speaking, was part of

02:03:51.040 --> 02:03:53.160
[Guest]: the old Maratha Empire, right?

02:03:53.160 --> 02:03:57.960
[Guest]: And that's also why Vajpayee Marathi is very good because if you go to Gwalior even today,

02:03:57.960 --> 02:04:01.240
[Guest]: you have Marathi speakers and you have Hindi speakers, right?

02:04:01.240 --> 02:04:05.760
[Unknown]: And the RSS comes there and he joins the Shaka and he joins the Shaka because of his caste,

02:04:05.760 --> 02:04:09.480
[Guest]: because you know, he was a, you know, a Brahmin and he joins and that was the social base

02:04:09.480 --> 02:04:11.360
[Guest]: of the RSS at that point.

02:04:11.360 --> 02:04:15.080
[Guest]: And I also mentioned there that on the first day, he's wearing a sacred thread, but very

02:04:15.080 --> 02:04:20.120
[Guest]: quickly he realizes that he doesn't want markers that distinguish himself from other Hindus

02:04:20.120 --> 02:04:23.160
[Guest]: and he removes the sacred thread and his own brother, I don't think I mentioned it in the

02:04:23.160 --> 02:04:27.600
[Guest]: book on, you know, in the first days in the Shaka, he cooks his own meals because he doesn't

02:04:27.600 --> 02:04:31.480
[Unknown]: want somebody who's not a Brahmin to cook his meals and within three, four days he ends

02:04:31.480 --> 02:04:32.480
[Guest]: that.

02:04:32.480 --> 02:04:39.440
[Guest]: To me, that's a wonderful story because it tells you that compared to traditional Hinduism,

02:04:39.440 --> 02:04:48.040
[Guest]: the RSS, again, for electoral logic, initially pushes you to be much more progressive, right?

02:04:48.040 --> 02:04:53.480
[Guest]: And that is Vajpayee's trajectory and his father then becomes a teacher in the Gwalior

02:04:53.480 --> 02:04:56.560
[Guest]: education system and employee of the Maharaja of Gwalior.

02:04:56.560 --> 02:05:00.680
[Guest]: He's a fantastic orator, that is Vajpayee's great skill.

02:05:00.680 --> 02:05:01.680
[Guest]: He's a middle-rung poet.

02:05:01.680 --> 02:05:06.480
[Guest]: So people who say Vajpayee is a great poet haven't read his poetry like I have, but what

02:05:06.480 --> 02:05:10.800
[Guest]: it gives him is a rhythm of sentences, right?

02:05:10.800 --> 02:05:17.440
[Guest]: That mixed with Vajpayee's extraordinary political antennae and the fact that his father was

02:05:17.440 --> 02:05:22.760
[Guest]: also a very good speaker gives Vajpayee's legendary quality, which is that he says a

02:05:22.760 --> 02:05:27.560
[Guest]: sentence that the left says is in their favor and the right says is in their favor.

02:05:27.560 --> 02:05:29.960
[Guest]: This is Vajpayee's like eternal quality, right?

02:05:29.960 --> 02:05:33.920
[Guest]: Like he'll say something in parliament and parliament will say, wow, this man is one

02:05:33.920 --> 02:05:38.480
[Guest]: of us without irritating the RSS, Arvani just can't do that, right?

02:05:38.480 --> 02:05:43.160
[Guest]: So that's Vajpayee's kind of background and as I argue, it's a background that is far

02:05:43.160 --> 02:05:49.400
[Guest]: apart from the moderate personality eventually gets and what changes Vajpayee from a provincial

02:05:49.400 --> 02:05:54.920
[Guest]: gangetic Brahmin into this kind of liberal avtaar that most liberal Indians kind of said

02:05:54.920 --> 02:05:57.920
[Guest]: right man in the wrong party are two things, Amit.

02:05:57.920 --> 02:06:00.280
[Guest]: One is it's the influence of parliament.

02:06:00.280 --> 02:06:06.560
[Guest]: At the age of 34, Vajpayee becomes an MP again, social engineering because Dindyal Upadhyay

02:06:06.560 --> 02:06:12.360
[Guest]: who runs the party at that time wants a good articulate replacement for Shyama Prashad

02:06:12.360 --> 02:06:13.360
[Unknown]: Mukherjee.

02:06:13.360 --> 02:06:19.080
[Guest]: And he's in parliament from the age from 1957, basically unbroken to 2007, 2008, that's enormous,

02:06:19.080 --> 02:06:20.080
[Guest]: right?

02:06:20.080 --> 02:06:25.840
[Guest]: Whether in the Lok Sabha or the Rajya Sabha and Vajpayee does not care who represents

02:06:25.840 --> 02:06:26.840
[Guest]: the party.

02:06:26.840 --> 02:06:30.560
[Guest]: He wants to make sure that he has the best seat to speak in parliament.

02:06:30.560 --> 02:06:32.560
[Guest]: That's his self-image, right?

02:06:32.560 --> 02:06:36.160
[Guest]: And parliament in that period, right, is an Aruvian consensus.

02:06:36.160 --> 02:06:40.000
[Guest]: Even if you're not part of the Congress, you broadly believe in an Aruvian consensus to

02:06:40.000 --> 02:06:44.400
[Guest]: be respectable in parliament, you have to accommodate the Aruvian consensus and Vajpayee

02:06:44.400 --> 02:06:45.400
[Unknown]: does that.

02:06:45.400 --> 02:06:50.640
[Guest]: And he does that not because he's a half a congressman as his right wing critics allege,

02:06:50.640 --> 02:06:55.360
[Guest]: but that is what you have to behave to get respectability in Congress of that period.

02:06:55.360 --> 02:07:00.760
[Guest]: So that is the first liberalizing influence of Vajpayee, given his social background.

02:07:00.760 --> 02:07:06.160
[Guest]: The other, which has led to some controversy in the book is his longtime companion Rajkumari

02:07:06.160 --> 02:07:07.160
[Guest]: Kaul.

02:07:07.160 --> 02:07:11.960
[Guest]: They are in love when Vajpayee is 17, she's 16 in Gwalior, they study in the same college

02:07:11.960 --> 02:07:16.160
[Guest]: together, but it doesn't happen, I think, because the families oppose, but they meet

02:07:16.160 --> 02:07:21.840
[Guest]: a couple of decades later and at that time, Rajkumari Kaul is married and Vajpayee then

02:07:21.840 --> 02:07:28.880
[Guest]: has a long standing relationship with her, her husband, Mr. Kaul, Rajkumari Kaul and

02:07:28.880 --> 02:07:31.640
[Guest]: Vajpayee live together, right?

02:07:31.640 --> 02:07:35.080
[Guest]: And she is Indira Gandhi's second cousin.

02:07:35.080 --> 02:07:40.640
[Guest]: She's a remarkable woman, I think one of the most under studied political women of the

02:07:40.640 --> 02:07:47.360
[Guest]: 20th century in that she plays a role in liberalizing one of the greatest politicians of 20th century

02:07:47.360 --> 02:07:49.200
[Guest]: India, namely Vajpayee.

02:07:49.200 --> 02:07:53.320
[Guest]: She has long discussions on him, say on the Ayodhya movement, she's opposed to the demolition

02:07:53.320 --> 02:07:59.200
[Guest]: of Babri Masjid, and she's a key part of the puzzle in trying to understand why someone

02:07:59.200 --> 02:08:03.520
[Guest]: like Vajpayee with Vajpayee's background began to be seen as a moderate.

02:08:03.520 --> 02:08:04.520
[Amit Varma]: No, no.

02:08:04.520 --> 02:08:09.040
[Amit Varma]: And, and, you know, I found it fascinating how you've quoted Vajpayee at one point as

02:08:09.040 --> 02:08:14.120
[Amit Varma]: saying quote, I am unmarried, but not, yeah.

02:08:14.120 --> 02:08:15.240
[Amit Varma]: So that was fascinating.

02:08:15.240 --> 02:08:20.200
[Amit Varma]: I wanted to explore a sort of a couple of interesting facets of Vajpayee's personality

02:08:20.200 --> 02:08:21.200
[Amit Varma]: here.

02:08:21.200 --> 02:08:25.720
[Amit Varma]: And one is even though Advani, who we'll speak about later, had an actual cosmopolitan background

02:08:25.720 --> 02:08:32.480
[Amit Varma]: and all of that, Vajpayee in many ways is also fairly cosmopolitan in the sense that,

02:08:32.480 --> 02:08:36.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, in that 95 meeting that you write about where Advani says that he'll be the

02:08:36.720 --> 02:08:41.600
[Amit Varma]: prime ministerial face of the BJP, Vajpayee cautions him by quoting Hazrat Nizamuddin

02:08:41.600 --> 02:08:47.320
[Amit Varma]: and he says, Delhi toh bahut door hai, and you know, he's a man who likes Bhang Pakoras,

02:08:47.320 --> 02:08:53.880
[Amit Varma]: he makes prawn curry, you know, he likes his whiskey, you describe him as an epicurean.

02:08:53.880 --> 02:08:57.680
[Amit Varma]: So it seems very interesting that, and this is something that is also say common with

02:08:57.680 --> 02:09:02.400
[Amit Varma]: Advani, whose background would make you expect this much more, but he's also, you know, Advani

02:09:02.400 --> 02:09:04.520
[Amit Varma]: is also into English literature and all that.

02:09:04.520 --> 02:09:09.360
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting thing is that where their political vision or perhaps a political vision

02:09:09.360 --> 02:09:14.880
[Amit Varma]: that they are sort of driven to by circumstances can be exclusionary and can have a narrow

02:09:14.880 --> 02:09:19.240
[Amit Varma]: vision of what a person in India is or what a Hindu is.

02:09:19.240 --> 02:09:23.840
[Amit Varma]: In their lived reality, in the concrete, outside the abstract, in the world of the concrete,

02:09:23.840 --> 02:09:28.960
[Amit Varma]: they are actually quite cosmopolitan and syncretic and absorbing all of these different cultures

02:09:28.960 --> 02:09:30.240
[Amit Varma]: and all of that.

02:09:30.240 --> 02:09:34.380
[Amit Varma]: And this about Vajpayee seemed very interesting to me.

02:09:34.380 --> 02:09:38.400
[Amit Varma]: What was also fascinating though, which is sort of a counterpoint to that, is you quote

02:09:38.400 --> 02:09:43.920
[Amit Varma]: a family friend of his saying, quote, from an early age, Vajpayee resented English speaking

02:09:43.920 --> 02:09:47.160
[Amit Varma]: Indians, but he was also fascinated by them.

02:09:47.160 --> 02:09:48.840
[Amit Varma]: That's the story of his life.

02:09:48.840 --> 02:09:49.840
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

02:09:49.840 --> 02:09:52.120
[Amit Varma]: And this has multiple resonances.

02:09:52.120 --> 02:09:56.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, first of all, to what extent do you feel that this was true and not just something

02:09:56.440 --> 02:09:58.160
[Amit Varma]: that this person was saying?

02:09:58.160 --> 02:10:02.520
[Amit Varma]: Did it change with Rajkumari Kaul, who was earlier Rajkumari Haksar, and as you pointed

02:10:02.520 --> 02:10:06.960
[Amit Varma]: out, second cousin of Indira Gandhi, to what extent did she change that because, you know,

02:10:06.960 --> 02:10:11.420
[Amit Varma]: he was fluent in English and obviously brought a lot more of these influences?

02:10:11.420 --> 02:10:17.360
[Amit Varma]: And to what extent does that sort of resentment towards English speaking elites linger on

02:10:17.360 --> 02:10:19.840
[Amit Varma]: and shape the politics today?

02:10:19.840 --> 02:10:24.640
[Amit Varma]: Because it is true that a lot of Indian politics has been shaped in a top down way from English

02:10:24.640 --> 02:10:27.720
[Amit Varma]: speaking elites who are disconnected with the rest of the country.

02:10:27.720 --> 02:10:33.280
[Amit Varma]: And it is natural and rational, you know, to imagine resentment towards that.

02:10:33.280 --> 02:10:39.960
[Guest]: Yeah, I think that that's a key way to understand the RSS, this insecurity and this anger at

02:10:39.960 --> 02:10:44.480
[Amit Varma]: English speaking elites, like me, Amit, like, and this made my life very hard when I started

02:10:44.480 --> 02:10:49.520
[Guest]: doing interviews, you know, and the thing is, I didn't pretend to be otherwise, right?

02:10:49.520 --> 02:10:53.520
[Guest]: I didn't pretend that, you know, I was pretty clear, look, I grew up in Bandra, that I've

02:10:53.520 --> 02:10:59.400
[Guest]: gone to, you know, Harvard and Princeton, like, but at the same time, they want you

02:10:59.400 --> 02:11:00.400
[Guest]: to know their story.

02:11:00.400 --> 02:11:04.200
[Unknown]: So it's a complicated, you know, it's a complicated relationship.

02:11:04.200 --> 02:11:07.480
[Guest]: You talk about Vajpayee, but you know, Advani is even more syncretic.

02:11:07.480 --> 02:11:12.320
[Guest]: Yes, he came from an English speaking background, he knew, which is defined as, you know, English

02:11:12.320 --> 02:11:14.320
[Unknown]: before you know any other Indian language, right?

02:11:14.320 --> 02:11:15.320
[Guest]: He did.

02:11:15.320 --> 02:11:17.640
[Guest]: I mean, he knew English before he knew Hindi.

02:11:17.640 --> 02:11:23.040
[Guest]: But at the same time, he, the kind of Hinduism that is practiced amongst Sindhis of that

02:11:23.040 --> 02:11:25.960
[Guest]: period in Karachi, is a very syncretic one.

02:11:25.960 --> 02:11:31.000
[Guest]: His, in his house, you have Sikh rituals, you know, that are practiced.

02:11:31.000 --> 02:11:36.360
[Guest]: His mother used to go to a Sufi shrine, precisely the kind of shrine that the RSS, the Higdewar

02:11:36.360 --> 02:11:38.480
[Guest]: opposed, which we discussed earlier.

02:11:38.480 --> 02:11:42.800
[Guest]: So it's a syncretic background, and he's English speaking, he's playing tennis, as I mentioned,

02:11:42.800 --> 02:11:47.240
[Guest]: you have to understand Advani is to understand him through the catastrophe of partition,

02:11:47.240 --> 02:11:51.720
[Guest]: and his desire to make his family and India whole again, that sense he comes across as

02:11:51.720 --> 02:11:56.360
[Guest]: a much more sympathetic character in this book, than the cartoonish versions of him,

02:11:56.360 --> 02:12:01.560
[Guest]: you know, wearing that hat in the Rath Yatra, right, saying that here's a man who is really

02:12:01.560 --> 02:12:07.200
[Guest]: shaped by these grand forces of history that he's trying to, you know, come to terms with

02:12:07.200 --> 02:12:09.760
[Guest]: after so many years.

02:12:09.760 --> 02:12:16.920
[Guest]: And ironically, Amit, the quality that pole vaults Advani into the heart of Hindu nationalism

02:12:16.920 --> 02:12:19.040
[Guest]: is the fact that he speaks English.

02:12:19.040 --> 02:12:25.520
[Guest]: So Atal Bihari Vajpayee becomes an MP in 1957, and also leader of the party, the Jan Sangh

02:12:25.520 --> 02:12:30.800
[Guest]: in Parliament, even though they had, I think, only three MPs, and Dindya Lupadia himself,

02:12:30.800 --> 02:12:35.760
[Guest]: a dhoti wearing Hindi speaking type, realizes very quickly that Luckhians Delhi is English

02:12:35.760 --> 02:12:36.760
[Guest]: speaking.

02:12:36.760 --> 02:12:40.360
[Guest]: So if you want to speak to journalists, you want to speak to diplomats, I mean, you know,

02:12:40.360 --> 02:12:45.240
[Guest]: he has the same insight that Arnab Goswami has had like 50 years later.

02:12:45.240 --> 02:12:50.240
[Guest]: But the difference is that Dindya Lupadia says, look, I need somebody to help Vajpayee

02:12:50.240 --> 02:12:52.480
[Guest]: navigate this English speaking world.

02:12:52.480 --> 02:12:55.920
[Guest]: And who's the English speaking person we have in our midst?

02:12:55.920 --> 02:12:58.920
[Guest]: It's Lal Krishna Advani, who happens to be in Rajasthan.

02:12:58.920 --> 02:13:03.200
[Guest]: That's the immediate reason that he is moved as secretary to Vajpayee in 1957.

02:13:03.200 --> 02:13:09.240
[Guest]: So it's this very complicated relationship between the English speaking world and Hindu

02:13:09.240 --> 02:13:14.080
[Guest]: nationalism, given that that was a reason for the rise of Advani himself, right.

02:13:14.080 --> 02:13:19.680
[Guest]: And of course, once Vajpayee gets much bigger, his political constituency becomes the English

02:13:19.680 --> 02:13:24.440
[Guest]: speaking liberals compared to Advani, right, even though the English speaking types who

02:13:24.440 --> 02:13:30.040
[Guest]: get into the BJP, Chandan Mitra, Swapan Das Gupta, Vajpayee can't relate to any of them.

02:13:30.040 --> 02:13:31.840
[Unknown]: They are all Advani's men.

02:13:31.840 --> 02:13:37.600
[Unknown]: So you know, this is a, it's a fascinating thread that runs through this book, without

02:13:37.600 --> 02:13:42.600
[Unknown]: a, and I like it also because it's a contradictory thread, there's no clear, you know, it's like

02:13:42.600 --> 02:13:46.760
[Amit Varma]: a river that is kind of meandering up and down there, the relationship between English

02:13:46.760 --> 02:13:48.760
[Amit Varma]: speaking resentment and Hindu nationalism.

02:13:48.760 --> 02:13:53.880
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, there's a very telling quote in your book about the time where, you know,

02:13:53.880 --> 02:13:56.120
[Amit Varma]: Advani was sent to Delhi to help out Vajpayee.

02:13:56.120 --> 02:14:00.760
[Amit Varma]: And you quote an RSS man active during that period, as saying, quote, there are two types

02:14:00.760 --> 02:14:05.800
[Amit Varma]: of Indians, those who use Western toilets, and those who use Indian toilets, we use Indian

02:14:05.800 --> 02:14:11.080
[Amit Varma]: toilets, but we need some people who use Western toilets, stop it, which is why, you know,

02:14:11.080 --> 02:14:12.920
[Amit Varma]: Advani is sort of sent there.

02:14:12.920 --> 02:14:17.880
[Amit Varma]: Another sort of very interesting thing about Advani is that this sort of impression of

02:14:17.880 --> 02:14:21.360
[Amit Varma]: Advani as a hardliner and Vajpayee as a moderate.

02:14:21.360 --> 02:14:24.720
[Amit Varma]: And I think there is perhaps much more truth to Vajpayee's moderation.

02:14:24.720 --> 02:14:29.880
[Amit Varma]: But Advani was sort of, you know, circumstances almost forced him to take this hardline stand

02:14:29.880 --> 02:14:34.400
[Amit Varma]: because first of all, in 1985, he's kind of, you know, pitchforked into the leadership

02:14:34.400 --> 02:14:39.000
[Amit Varma]: of the party when Vajpayee has to go because, you know, all the Hindu vote has gone to Rajiv

02:14:39.000 --> 02:14:43.240
[Amit Varma]: Gandhi and all of that, and then over a period of time, he, you know, becomes hardline out

02:14:43.240 --> 02:14:44.240
[Amit Varma]: of circumstance.

02:14:44.240 --> 02:14:47.240
[Amit Varma]: Now, I'm struck by a bunch of quotes about him.

02:14:47.240 --> 02:14:52.360
[Amit Varma]: In fact, and one is, of course, from Balraj Madhok, who was opposed to both Advani and

02:14:52.360 --> 02:14:58.000
[Amit Varma]: Vajpayee and Balraj Madhok called Advani, a quote, boneless wonder, who does not have

02:14:58.000 --> 02:15:02.120
[Amit Varma]: his own character or opinion, stop quote.

02:15:02.120 --> 02:15:06.880
[Amit Varma]: And much later, you know, you quote Arun Shourie as saying of the time in the cabinet together

02:15:06.880 --> 02:15:11.360
[Amit Varma]: in the Vajpayee government, that Advani was the second most powerful man in the country.

02:15:11.360 --> 02:15:17.640
[Amit Varma]: The most powerful was the man who last met him, you know, indicating that he is so impressionable

02:15:17.640 --> 02:15:18.640
[Amit Varma]: as it were.

02:15:18.640 --> 02:15:23.680
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about Advani's beliefs, like we've already sort of spoken about, you know,

02:15:23.680 --> 02:15:28.440
[Amit Varma]: Vajpayee the orator and, you know, Advani, the organizer coming together and that's how

02:15:28.440 --> 02:15:29.440
[Amit Varma]: they start.

02:15:29.440 --> 02:15:33.160
[Amit Varma]: But Advani also becomes not bad at orating at a later period in time.

02:15:33.160 --> 02:15:34.840
[Amit Varma]: But so he's an organizer.

02:15:34.840 --> 02:15:35.840
[Amit Varma]: He's looking after the party.

02:15:35.840 --> 02:15:36.960
[Amit Varma]: The party has an ethic.

02:15:36.960 --> 02:15:38.120
[Amit Varma]: It is a team ethic.

02:15:38.120 --> 02:15:40.080
[Amit Varma]: He has a cosmopolitan background.

02:15:40.080 --> 02:15:44.280
[Amit Varma]: You know, he went to St. Patrick's and, you know, you describe an incident about I think

02:15:44.280 --> 02:15:48.840
[Amit Varma]: in the early 2000s, he goes to Pakistan and he goes to that school and they sing for he's

02:15:48.840 --> 02:15:53.340
[Amit Varma]: a jolly good fellow for him and, you know, his eyes missed over, as you point out.

02:15:53.340 --> 02:15:54.600
[Amit Varma]: So he is that kind of man.

02:15:54.600 --> 02:16:00.880
[Amit Varma]: He's also what is the sense that you get about, you know, what his views are like?

02:16:00.880 --> 02:16:01.880
[Amit Varma]: What does he really believe?

02:16:01.880 --> 02:16:02.880
[Amit Varma]: What is he driven by?

02:16:02.880 --> 02:16:06.960
[Amit Varma]: Like Swapan Dasgupta at one point said, as you've quoted in your book, that Advani was

02:16:06.960 --> 02:16:11.760
[Amit Varma]: a different man before and after the Rath Yatra, which is interesting.

02:16:11.760 --> 02:16:16.600
[Amit Varma]: But I think that is, you know, he would have reached a bit of an age there where your basic

02:16:16.600 --> 02:16:18.260
[Amit Varma]: character doesn't change.

02:16:18.260 --> 02:16:23.160
[Amit Varma]: So are these people political animals who are responding to incentives in the political

02:16:23.160 --> 02:16:28.880
[Amit Varma]: marketplace, which later determines the way that they are looked at or at their core,

02:16:28.880 --> 02:16:31.240
[Amit Varma]: is there something else which you can point to?

02:16:31.240 --> 02:16:36.000
[Amit Varma]: Like with Vajpayee, certainly you can say that he had things that he stood up for and

02:16:36.000 --> 02:16:37.000
[Amit Varma]: strong beliefs.

02:16:37.000 --> 02:16:41.040
[Amit Varma]: For example, when, you know, the Golwalkar asked him to break up his relationship with

02:16:41.040 --> 02:16:44.280
[Amit Varma]: the Rajkumari, he just flat out refused.

02:16:44.280 --> 02:16:48.240
[Amit Varma]: And you know what, give me a sense of Advani in that sense.

02:16:48.240 --> 02:16:52.560
[Guest]: You know, the narrative spine of this book, Amit, is Vajpayee and Advani.

02:16:52.560 --> 02:16:57.680
[Guest]: So it was very important for me to get their personalities right, very important, right.

02:16:57.680 --> 02:17:01.440
[Guest]: And to have that, look, people change, as you said, people change over 80 years, but

02:17:01.440 --> 02:17:05.680
[Guest]: they also have to have some part of their personalities that are constant.

02:17:05.680 --> 02:17:11.080
[Guest]: And after thinking about this for three years, I realized that the two core personality traits

02:17:11.080 --> 02:17:17.120
[Guest]: of Advani, right, one is loyalty, you know, he's defined by loyalty, you know, and it's

02:17:17.120 --> 02:17:20.560
[Guest]: a trait that, you know, is very welcome in the RSS.

02:17:20.560 --> 02:17:25.860
[Guest]: And the second trait is underconfidence, he's constantly unsure, he has this Hamlet-like

02:17:25.860 --> 02:17:31.080
[Guest]: quality, where, you know, he's constantly unsure to do or not to do, to be or not to

02:17:31.080 --> 02:17:34.240
[Guest]: be, you know, in a sense, Vajpayee doesn't have that at all.

02:17:34.240 --> 02:17:38.640
[Guest]: So right from the beginning, when he meets Vajpayee, he's in awe of Vajpayee's speaking

02:17:38.640 --> 02:17:39.640
[Guest]: talent.

02:17:39.640 --> 02:17:43.440
[Guest]: And Advani himself is very underconfident about his speaking talent, right.

02:17:43.440 --> 02:17:45.600
[Guest]: He's an unnatural politician in that sense.

02:17:45.600 --> 02:17:50.160
[Guest]: But you know, he's loyal, he spends a lot of time with the party carder, the party carder

02:17:50.160 --> 02:17:54.200
[Guest]: like that, Vajpayee has no time for them, Vajpayee only has time for Parliament.

02:17:54.200 --> 02:17:58.800
[Guest]: So over time, he develops this hardline image amidst for three reasons.

02:17:58.800 --> 02:18:04.960
[Guest]: One is that he listens to the party, he listens to the RSS, he spends morning to evening like

02:18:04.960 --> 02:18:09.480
[Guest]: going to party headquarters, listening to what people are saying, Vajpayee doesn't do

02:18:09.480 --> 02:18:10.480
[Guest]: that at all.

02:18:10.480 --> 02:18:12.680
[Guest]: And the party is far more hardline than Parliament.

02:18:12.680 --> 02:18:15.520
[Guest]: So Advani becomes the face of the party.

02:18:15.520 --> 02:18:18.080
[Guest]: That's the first reason why he gets a hardline image.

02:18:18.080 --> 02:18:22.720
[Guest]: The second reason he gets a hardline image is that Vajpayee liked that, because Vajpayee

02:18:22.720 --> 02:18:26.960
[Guest]: understood the fact that you need an orator and an organiser and at the times in which

02:18:26.960 --> 02:18:32.000
[Guest]: the RSS was tiring of him, he would say, look, if you're tiring of me, I'll put a different

02:18:32.000 --> 02:18:35.520
[Guest]: party president that you like, who will also be loyal to me.

02:18:35.520 --> 02:18:36.520
[Guest]: And that was Advani.

02:18:36.520 --> 02:18:41.000
[Unknown]: So they needed the jugalbandhi, Vajpayee understood it, Advani understood it also.

02:18:41.000 --> 02:18:44.960
[Guest]: The third reason he's given the impression of being hardline today is the Rath Yatra,

02:18:44.960 --> 02:18:47.240
[Guest]: right, and the Babri Majid demolition.

02:18:47.240 --> 02:18:50.400
[Guest]: No question, that's the defining feature of Advani.

02:18:50.400 --> 02:18:55.720
[Guest]: I point out in the book though that Rath Yatra, of which I'm critical, if you've read that,

02:18:55.720 --> 02:18:58.280
[Guest]: was not because he was a religious zealot at all.

02:18:58.280 --> 02:19:01.680
[Guest]: It was sheer naked political opportunism.

02:19:01.680 --> 02:19:07.240
[Guest]: That in August 1990, the VP Singh government announces the Mandal Commission report, where

02:19:07.240 --> 02:19:11.680
[Guest]: you have reservations in central government jobs for OBCs or backward castes.

02:19:11.680 --> 02:19:15.920
[Guest]: This immediately sets off panic among the upper caste base of the BJP.

02:19:15.920 --> 02:19:20.760
[Guest]: And Advani is able to see that if this continues like this, there will be a split between the

02:19:20.760 --> 02:19:25.480
[Unknown]: upper caste and the backward caste, you know, and if it's just upper caste, the BJP cannot

02:19:25.480 --> 02:19:26.600
[Unknown]: come to power.

02:19:26.600 --> 02:19:30.880
[Guest]: So literally a month later, he announces the Rath Yatra, where he travels from Somnath

02:19:30.880 --> 02:19:33.200
[Guest]: to Ayodhya, or he plans to travel to Ayodhya.

02:19:33.200 --> 02:19:37.280
[Guest]: The Ayodhya movement is by that time already seven years old.

02:19:37.280 --> 02:19:42.680
[Guest]: So nothing explains the timing of the Rath Yatra, except that literally a month earlier,

02:19:42.680 --> 02:19:47.720
[Guest]: you had the VP Singh government, right, and I would say that that is the sheer political

02:19:47.720 --> 02:19:53.200
[Guest]: opportunism, right, rather than, you know, deeply held Islamophobia and a sign of that

02:19:53.200 --> 02:19:58.040
[Guest]: is that in all his speeches that you see there, right, I don't want to defend him, he's very

02:19:58.040 --> 02:20:03.000
[Guest]: careful not to criticize Muslims directly, which is something you hear every day in this

02:20:03.000 --> 02:20:04.000
[Unknown]: government.

02:20:04.000 --> 02:20:07.840
[Guest]: You know, he's very, very careful and even when the crowd starts saying something against

02:20:07.840 --> 02:20:13.000
[Guest]: Prophet Mohammed or something, Advani is the first to shush them up, you know, saying that's

02:20:13.000 --> 02:20:14.000
[Unknown]: not what this is about.

02:20:14.000 --> 02:20:19.960
[Guest]: That's what gives him this Hamlet-like quality that his own social instincts and the political

02:20:19.960 --> 02:20:24.600
[Guest]: persona that frankly is good for him, like, you know, it's good to be called a hardliner

02:20:24.600 --> 02:20:28.880
[Amit Varma]: because the parliament and English-speaking liberals will hate you, but the RSS and the

02:20:28.880 --> 02:20:31.920
[Unknown]: cadre will say, okay, he's one of us, right?

02:20:31.920 --> 02:20:36.120
[Guest]: But that's what gives Advani this complexity and I don't want to defend him or anything

02:20:36.120 --> 02:20:41.000
[Guest]: like that, but certainly as the beginning of the book shows Amit, he could have become

02:20:41.000 --> 02:20:46.120
[Guest]: prime minister in 96, but he is understands, or you can say underconfident, or he understands

02:20:46.120 --> 02:20:50.960
[Guest]: his own limitations that if he is prime minister, the BJP will never get allies and so you need

02:20:50.960 --> 02:20:52.440
[Guest]: someone like Vajpayee.

02:20:52.440 --> 02:20:56.080
[Guest]: So he gets Vajpayee out of cold storage and Vajpayee is then the PM candidate and then

02:20:56.080 --> 02:21:02.360
[Guest]: Vajpayee becomes PM again, 96, 98 and 99 and Advani serves under him and I just think that's

02:21:02.360 --> 02:21:07.480
[Unknown]: remarkable because how many politicians, you know, are aware of their own limitations.

02:21:07.480 --> 02:21:11.440
[Guest]: Certainly, you know, today's Congress and Rahul Gandhi are not aware of their limitations,

02:21:11.440 --> 02:21:12.440
[Guest]: right?

02:21:12.440 --> 02:21:18.880
[Guest]: And in that sense, certainly when you read this book, the hundred percent negative image

02:21:18.880 --> 02:21:24.320
[Unknown]: of Advani, some of you may have, will be diluted just a little bit and the hundred percent

02:21:24.320 --> 02:21:28.840
[Guest]: positive image of Vajpayee that some of you have will be diluted just a little bit.

02:21:28.840 --> 02:21:32.120
[Guest]: They were a jugal bandhi, they were at some level play acting.

02:21:32.120 --> 02:21:35.320
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, responding to incentives, before I get to my next question, a couple

02:21:35.320 --> 02:21:38.200
[Amit Varma]: of asides and the first is an aside to an aside.

02:21:38.200 --> 02:21:41.600
[Amit Varma]: So it may seem completely irrelevant, but I remember, you know, there used to be this

02:21:41.600 --> 02:21:46.160
[Amit Varma]: news magazine in the early 90s called NewsTrack, which would go around in videotapes.

02:21:46.160 --> 02:21:50.400
[Amit Varma]: And I remember, you know, watching an episode of NewsTrack where there was an interview

02:21:50.400 --> 02:21:55.480
[Amit Varma]: of Devi Lal and it was fabulous if someone can find the clip, I don't know if it exists,

02:21:55.480 --> 02:22:00.400
[Amit Varma]: where he is basically sitting in, I think a banyan and a dhoti in the garden on a chair

02:22:00.400 --> 02:22:03.880
[Amit Varma]: with his feet up and the camera angle is, you know, at his shoes.

02:22:03.880 --> 02:22:07.640
[Amit Varma]: So his shoes are really big and he is kind of in the background.

02:22:07.640 --> 02:22:13.040
[Amit Varma]: And the interviewer asks him, ki Devi Lal ji, apne apne bete ko chief minister kyu banaya?

02:22:13.040 --> 02:22:18.000
[Amit Varma]: And Devi Lal says, toh kya Bhajan Lal ke chhore ko banaya?

02:22:18.000 --> 02:22:19.280
[Amit Varma]: Which is a masterful answer.

02:22:19.280 --> 02:22:24.480
[Amit Varma]: But the reason this aside came to me was because of the next aside, which is again about how

02:22:24.480 --> 02:22:30.120
[Amit Varma]: circumstance seems to shape politics in the sense that VP Singh went in for all the Mandal

02:22:30.120 --> 02:22:35.000
[Amit Varma]: stuff he did partly because Devi Lal was agitating and he felt politically insecure.

02:22:35.000 --> 02:22:39.360
[Amit Varma]: And then Advani responds to that with, you know, the Rath Yatra and then whatever happens

02:22:39.360 --> 02:22:43.640
[Amit Varma]: happens and it, you know, it's like a domino effect of one thing after another and you

02:22:43.640 --> 02:22:45.760
[Amit Varma]: wonder what would have happened if the chain was broken.

02:22:45.760 --> 02:22:53.600
[Amit Varma]: Now, tell me a little bit about sort of the relationship between Advani and Vajpayee like

02:22:53.600 --> 02:22:57.000
[Amit Varma]: at one level, their backgrounds are pretty different.

02:22:57.000 --> 02:23:01.600
[Amit Varma]: You know, you point out how Vajpayee is from Gwalior, the orthodox strand of colonial era

02:23:01.600 --> 02:23:05.840
[Amit Varma]: Hinduism as it were, Advani is from the reformist strand.

02:23:05.840 --> 02:23:12.080
[Amit Varma]: He is, you know, in Karachi where he's going to St. Patrick's and he's playing tennis and

02:23:12.080 --> 02:23:16.680
[Amit Varma]: the Guru Granth Sahib is at home in one sense, he's almost like his family is partly Nanak

02:23:16.680 --> 02:23:19.080
[Amit Varma]: Panthi, it would seem.

02:23:19.080 --> 02:23:23.840
[Amit Varma]: And then they both joined the RSS and they come together and you describe their first

02:23:23.840 --> 02:23:30.600
[Amit Varma]: meeting where, you know, Shyamaprasad Mukherjee goes to Kota to campaign before the 5152 elections

02:23:30.600 --> 02:23:35.200
[Amit Varma]: and because he's not great at Hindi, the RSS sends Vajpayee who was earlier the editor

02:23:35.200 --> 02:23:39.680
[Amit Varma]: of their magazine to help him out and Advani is just smitten.

02:23:39.680 --> 02:23:44.920
[Amit Varma]: And he says about Vajpayee, he describes him later as quote, a poet who had drifted into

02:23:44.920 --> 02:23:49.520
[Amit Varma]: politics, something was smoldering within him and the fire in his belly produced an

02:23:49.520 --> 02:23:52.840
[Amit Varma]: unmistakable glow on his face, stop quote.

02:23:52.840 --> 02:23:58.880
[Amit Varma]: And at a sense, it almost, you know, it seems like and they're both deeply emotional people,

02:23:58.880 --> 02:24:02.800
[Amit Varma]: as Vasundhara Rajesh India tells you, I think at another point of the story, and it seems

02:24:02.800 --> 02:24:07.240
[Amit Varma]: to me like a beautiful sort of bromance that is developing through the book that these

02:24:07.240 --> 02:24:12.760
[Amit Varma]: are such different people, Vajpayee much more flamboyant, given to expression, slightly

02:24:12.760 --> 02:24:17.720
[Amit Varma]: more colourful life, while Advani, despite the cosmopolitan background is a very stable

02:24:17.720 --> 02:24:23.480
[Amit Varma]: personality, very Uxorious, if I might use that word, I shouldn't use jargon, but Uxorious,

02:24:23.480 --> 02:24:28.680
[Amit Varma]: however you pronounce it means someone absolutely devoted to his wife, which is, of course,

02:24:28.680 --> 02:24:33.400
[Amit Varma]: a very formidable Kamla Jagdiani, who also kind of stays in the background, just like

02:24:33.400 --> 02:24:35.520
[Amit Varma]: Rajkumari Kaul.

02:24:35.520 --> 02:24:40.240
[Amit Varma]: What was the relation like, you've also spoken about how, you know, in later in the 60s and

02:24:40.240 --> 02:24:45.320
[Amit Varma]: the 70s, they'd go and watch movies together, and they just loved each other's company.

02:24:45.320 --> 02:24:49.760
[Amit Varma]: And yet there is a sort of drift when, you know, the first Vajpayee government actually

02:24:49.760 --> 02:24:54.280
[Amit Varma]: spends his time because Vajpayee realizes that there isn't enough talent in the RSS.

02:24:54.280 --> 02:24:59.080
[Amit Varma]: And so he brings in all these other people and centralizes a lot of things in the PMO.

02:24:59.080 --> 02:25:01.000
[Amit Varma]: And Advani is a bit resentful.

02:25:01.000 --> 02:25:05.320
[Amit Varma]: What's the personal relationship been growing through the years like Advani makes in a sense

02:25:05.320 --> 02:25:10.640
[Amit Varma]: a supreme sacrifice in 95, where he says that, you know, Vajpayee should be the PM candidate,

02:25:10.640 --> 02:25:15.440
[Amit Varma]: and the whole party is just aghast at that, and, you know, he is the obvious choice.

02:25:15.440 --> 02:25:18.560
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about that relationship and your sense of it.

02:25:18.560 --> 02:25:23.320
[Amit Varma]: And was it moving in parts to sort of, you know, look at how that unfolds through the

02:25:23.320 --> 02:25:24.320
[Amit Varma]: years?

02:25:24.320 --> 02:25:30.360
[Guest]: So, I mean, I look at this relationship, this Jugalbandi as having three different strands.

02:25:30.360 --> 02:25:34.600
[Guest]: The first strand, which is, I think, the, you know, the one that is essential is that

02:25:34.600 --> 02:25:37.040
[Guest]: they like each other, they like hanging out.

02:25:37.040 --> 02:25:41.000
[Guest]: So think about your listeners to think about friends you like to hang out with, there's

02:25:41.000 --> 02:25:42.000
[Guest]: no formula for it.

02:25:42.000 --> 02:25:45.000
[Guest]: Like, you know, you, you may like somebody else, but you may not like like shooting the

02:25:45.000 --> 02:25:49.080
[Guest]: breeze for an evening with somebody, you know, somebody else you may disagree and argue with,

02:25:49.080 --> 02:25:50.920
[Guest]: but it's fun to hang out with.

02:25:50.920 --> 02:25:51.920
[Guest]: They were like that.

02:25:51.920 --> 02:25:56.760
[Guest]: So they, you know, they, and it's hard to reduce that chemistry into three or four equations.

02:25:56.760 --> 02:25:59.120
[Guest]: So they like Bollywood films, right?

02:25:59.120 --> 02:26:01.000
[Guest]: That was an aspect of the personal relationship.

02:26:01.000 --> 02:26:02.000
[Guest]: They like to eat, right?

02:26:02.000 --> 02:26:07.240
[Guest]: They used to go out, Advani was a vegetarian, Vajpayee was anything but, you know, they

02:26:07.240 --> 02:26:09.240
[Guest]: would discuss, you know, each other's family.

02:26:09.240 --> 02:26:10.800
[Guest]: So they would do that kind of thing.

02:26:10.800 --> 02:26:14.080
[Guest]: They had a similar emotional quotient that they could, you know, cry and laugh at the

02:26:14.080 --> 02:26:15.080
[Guest]: same time.

02:26:15.080 --> 02:26:20.080
[Guest]: There was definitely a fanboy element, Advani when he met as the quote that you read out,

02:26:20.080 --> 02:26:25.160
[Guest]: now Advani was, you know, startled by Vajpayee and look, I think one of the big strengths

02:26:25.160 --> 02:26:30.240
[Guest]: of the book is I never met Vajpayee and I mean this because anyone I know who met Vajpayee

02:26:30.240 --> 02:26:35.800
[Guest]: was bedazzled by him, you know, any journalist, anyone who sees it in parliament, he could

02:26:35.800 --> 02:26:40.600
[Guest]: make time stop and I would encourage your listeners to go at least on YouTube and see

02:26:40.600 --> 02:26:45.360
[Guest]: some of his speeches, you know, even when, you know, he's being calculated this, that

02:26:45.360 --> 02:26:50.160
[Guest]: he, you know, unlike many politicians who try to convince you, Vajpayee could make you

02:26:50.160 --> 02:26:51.160
[Guest]: laugh.

02:26:51.160 --> 02:26:52.160
[Guest]: He could make you smile.

02:26:52.160 --> 02:26:55.120
[Guest]: You know, his sentences had an angularity to it.

02:26:55.120 --> 02:26:57.960
[Guest]: He in his best sense, he had the ability to uplift you.

02:26:57.960 --> 02:27:01.080
[Guest]: Now the problem with that is that may not be the person he is.

02:27:01.080 --> 02:27:06.160
[Guest]: Many cases, many times it is, sometimes it's not, but you can get totally, you know, emotional

02:27:06.160 --> 02:27:08.440
[Guest]: and irrational if you met him.

02:27:08.440 --> 02:27:12.760
[Guest]: So many of the people who are a little critical of my book for being, you know, because of

02:27:12.760 --> 02:27:17.880
[Guest]: sort of puncturing this grand Vajpayee image, which I do, while at the same time saying

02:27:17.880 --> 02:27:21.600
[Guest]: he was one of India's greatest prime ministers, but look, he was a human being and he was

02:27:21.600 --> 02:27:22.600
[Guest]: a politician.

02:27:22.600 --> 02:27:26.640
[Guest]: Are people who met him and people who've been blinded by that, right?

02:27:26.640 --> 02:27:32.080
[Guest]: I have not, and I'm thankful for that because had I met Vajpayee, this book would definitely

02:27:32.080 --> 02:27:34.200
[Guest]: have come across as a fanboy book, right?

02:27:34.200 --> 02:27:37.120
[Guest]: I don't think India has had a greater political orator.

02:27:37.120 --> 02:27:41.840
[Guest]: And I think part of the personal equation between Vajpayee and Advani was Advani was

02:27:41.840 --> 02:27:42.840
[Guest]: a fanboy.

02:27:42.840 --> 02:27:45.200
[Guest]: He was a fanboy of Vajpayee.

02:27:45.200 --> 02:27:48.680
[Guest]: The second strand of that relationship was professional.

02:27:48.680 --> 02:27:53.280
[Guest]: Something that we discussed earlier that Hindu nationalism needs a moderate, needs a hardliner,

02:27:53.280 --> 02:27:57.320
[Guest]: needs an orator, needs an organizer, and both of them fitted that part.

02:27:57.320 --> 02:28:00.680
[Guest]: And you know, when the mood of the nation was for moderation, Vajpayee was in front.

02:28:00.680 --> 02:28:04.880
[Guest]: When the mood of the nation was for radicalism, Advani was propped in front.

02:28:04.880 --> 02:28:10.600
[Guest]: And by the way, as an aside, Amit, I think that is the most remarkable part of the relationship

02:28:10.600 --> 02:28:15.080
[Guest]: that in a country as hierarchical as India, you have a relationship that is able to switch

02:28:15.080 --> 02:28:17.520
[Guest]: spots not once, but twice.

02:28:17.520 --> 02:28:22.480
[Guest]: So it's like, you know, Obama now serving under Biden, Biden had served under Obama,

02:28:22.480 --> 02:28:26.240
[Guest]: Obama now serving under Biden, and then a few years later, Biden once again serving

02:28:26.240 --> 02:28:27.240
[Guest]: under Obama.

02:28:27.240 --> 02:28:28.240
[Guest]: It's unthinkable.

02:28:28.240 --> 02:28:30.080
[Guest]: But that's literally what Vajpayee and Advani did.

02:28:30.080 --> 02:28:34.160
[Guest]: And that was also because they were professionally compatible, right?

02:28:34.160 --> 02:28:38.200
[Guest]: In a way in which Advani and Murali Manohar Joshi were competing with the same spot, there

02:28:38.200 --> 02:28:39.200
[Guest]: was no jugalbandi there.

02:28:39.200 --> 02:28:41.040
[Guest]: That's why they didn't like each other.

02:28:41.040 --> 02:28:46.280
[Guest]: Or Subramanian Swamy and Madhok were competing with the same spot as the face and voice of

02:28:46.280 --> 02:28:52.080
[Guest]: Hindu nationalism as Vajpayee did, whereas Vajpayee and Advani were perfectly compatible

02:28:52.080 --> 02:28:57.040
[Guest]: in a jugalbandi that is at least in part a requirement of Hindu nationalism, which is

02:28:57.040 --> 02:29:01.720
[Guest]: both a party seeking political power as well as a social movement seeking to transform

02:29:01.720 --> 02:29:02.720
[Guest]: society.

02:29:02.720 --> 02:29:04.800
[Guest]: So it's like the communists in that respect.

02:29:04.800 --> 02:29:08.040
[Guest]: And that's the second strand, professional compatibility.

02:29:08.040 --> 02:29:12.280
[Guest]: The third strand, however, and that's like, literally, that's the taste that I want to

02:29:12.280 --> 02:29:17.340
[Guest]: leave you with in the book is ideology, that it's a, it's a, it's an ideology that focuses

02:29:17.340 --> 02:29:18.340
[Guest]: on teamwork.

02:29:18.340 --> 02:29:23.560
[Guest]: And even when the things went so bad between Vajpayee and Advani, for Advani, it was, you

02:29:23.560 --> 02:29:26.760
[Guest]: know, between 98 and 2004, when they were in power.

02:29:26.760 --> 02:29:31.840
[Guest]: And for Vajpayee, it was between 1986 and 1993 or 1994, they never divorced.

02:29:31.840 --> 02:29:36.400
[Guest]: So it was like one of these odd couples squabbling in the, in the park that you see, and you're

02:29:36.400 --> 02:29:39.480
[Guest]: like, they're going to call the police, but they go home and cook for each other.

02:29:39.480 --> 02:29:41.000
[Guest]: It's like that.

02:29:41.000 --> 02:29:46.800
[Guest]: And what keeps that couple united is a deep ideological belief in the sanctity of marriage.

02:29:46.800 --> 02:29:48.400
[Guest]: That's what these people had.

02:29:48.400 --> 02:29:53.240
[Guest]: And a good sign of that is the end of the book, which, you know, I'm sorry, please read

02:29:53.240 --> 02:29:54.240
[Guest]: the book.

02:29:54.240 --> 02:29:55.240
[Guest]: Don't just see, hear the podcast.

02:29:55.240 --> 02:30:00.440
[Guest]: But at the end, at Vajpayee's, you know, just after his funeral, Advani has to speak and

02:30:00.440 --> 02:30:05.000
[Guest]: Advani could have deferred to Vajpayee, his 60 year relationship with Vajpayee in terms

02:30:05.000 --> 02:30:10.260
[Guest]: of personality or in terms of personal chemistry or in terms of professional compatibility.

02:30:10.260 --> 02:30:11.680
[Guest]: But he focuses on ideology.

02:30:11.680 --> 02:30:17.240
[Guest]: He says that thinking about Vajpayee will help us live according to the ideology and

02:30:17.240 --> 02:30:21.120
[Guest]: principles that the RSS has laid for us or words to that effect.

02:30:21.120 --> 02:30:22.440
[Guest]: That's very telling.

02:30:22.440 --> 02:30:26.960
[Guest]: Because even after all these decades, even after all the love, the warmth, the professional

02:30:26.960 --> 02:30:30.520
[Guest]: compatibility, the marriage was kept together by an ideology.

02:30:30.520 --> 02:30:32.040
[Amit Varma]: No, that's fascinating.

02:30:32.040 --> 02:30:37.480
[Amit Varma]: And I'll go off on another sort of brief digression by something that you said, and something

02:30:37.480 --> 02:30:39.000
[Amit Varma]: that you wrote.

02:30:39.000 --> 02:30:42.720
[Amit Varma]: What you said was that you're glad you didn't meet Vajpayee because then you might have

02:30:42.720 --> 02:30:43.720
[Amit Varma]: been biased by it.

02:30:43.720 --> 02:30:46.080
[Amit Varma]: And this could have been a fanboy story.

02:30:46.080 --> 02:30:50.280
[Amit Varma]: In your book, at one point, you also write about how Advani realizing consciously that

02:30:50.280 --> 02:30:53.280
[Amit Varma]: he needs to woo English speaking journalists.

02:30:53.280 --> 02:30:58.280
[Amit Varma]: And so he gets Swapandas Gupta and Chandan Mitra and so on into the fold.

02:30:58.280 --> 02:31:01.720
[Amit Varma]: And since then, they've been complete fanboys.

02:31:01.720 --> 02:31:07.480
[Amit Varma]: And equally, I know, sort of, quote unquote, liberal acquaintances of mine, who have been

02:31:07.480 --> 02:31:11.400
[Amit Varma]: granted a meeting with Rahul Gandhi and suddenly their view just flipped and they are just

02:31:11.400 --> 02:31:16.800
[Amit Varma]: in complete awe of the guy and no, no, he's not as dumb as you think he is and blah, blah,

02:31:16.800 --> 02:31:17.800
[Amit Varma]: blah.

02:31:17.800 --> 02:31:22.280
[Amit Varma]: So what happens like, you know, and I'm referring to sort of, if you have any observations about

02:31:22.280 --> 02:31:27.240
[Amit Varma]: this human trait, that you meet this person in power, who's a public figure who is nice

02:31:27.240 --> 02:31:28.240
[Amit Varma]: to you.

02:31:28.240 --> 02:31:31.320
[Amit Varma]: And suddenly you just flip your independent thinking vanishes.

02:31:31.320 --> 02:31:32.560
[Amit Varma]: I have seen this so often.

02:31:32.560 --> 02:31:33.560
[Guest]: And it's just so bizarre.

02:31:33.560 --> 02:31:34.560
[Guest]: It's the power of raw charisma.

02:31:34.560 --> 02:31:41.160
[Guest]: This is what Max Weber said is a very key component of why politics works and boy did

02:31:41.160 --> 02:31:42.160
[Guest]: Vajpayee have it.

02:31:42.160 --> 02:31:46.600
[Guest]: You know, like Advani, I don't think you meet Advani, you say sincere man, you know, if

02:31:46.600 --> 02:31:51.200
[Guest]: you like him, you know, like whatever educated man, but you know, you won't like with Vajpayee,

02:31:51.200 --> 02:31:53.800
[Guest]: like, you know, journalists will go to talk to him.

02:31:53.800 --> 02:31:57.320
[Guest]: Journalists have told me to talk to him about some political story, and he kind of turned

02:31:57.320 --> 02:32:01.160
[Guest]: to the window and see, you know, barish suno and they go and for five minutes, listen to

02:32:01.160 --> 02:32:04.160
[Guest]: the sound of the rain, you know, I mean, it's mesmerizing.

02:32:04.160 --> 02:32:09.960
[Guest]: Absolutely mesmerizing, which is, and that, of course, at a personal level, at a political

02:32:09.960 --> 02:32:15.520
[Guest]: level, Vajpayee's command over what to say, what not to say was an enormous political

02:32:15.520 --> 02:32:16.520
[Guest]: tool.

02:32:16.520 --> 02:32:21.400
[Guest]: Like to give you one example again, this charisma, he goes to Pakistan in the late nineties on

02:32:21.400 --> 02:32:27.960
[Guest]: the bus, Lahore bus yatra, and he gives a speech in Pakistan to all the elites of Pakistan.

02:32:27.960 --> 02:32:33.440
[Guest]: And he just totally floors them, both in the way he quotes Urdu and the way he speaks,

02:32:33.440 --> 02:32:35.840
[Guest]: but also in like the sentences he uses.

02:32:35.840 --> 02:32:39.600
[Guest]: So he gives the sentence and I quoted in the book, I'm saying it in English, which is,

02:32:39.600 --> 02:32:45.480
[Guest]: he says that, you know, some people feel that by coming to Pakistan, I have put a mohar

02:32:45.480 --> 02:32:48.480
[Guest]: or I put a stamp on their existence, right?

02:32:48.480 --> 02:32:53.760
[Guest]: So that's the beautiful sentence, because what he's saying is, and the Pakistan audience

02:32:53.760 --> 02:32:58.520
[Guest]: understands is that people in the RSS who believe in Akhand Bharat, who believe that

02:32:58.520 --> 02:33:02.920
[Guest]: Pakistan should not exist in the first place, feel that by Vajpayee going there, that he

02:33:02.920 --> 02:33:04.840
[Guest]: has put a seal on Pakistan, right?

02:33:04.840 --> 02:33:07.000
[Guest]: But he never has to say it in that complicated way.

02:33:07.000 --> 02:33:10.880
[Guest]: He actually George Orwell, you know, should use Vajpayee as an example, because he, you

02:33:10.880 --> 02:33:14.640
[Guest]: know, he shows without telling, and then the next sentence is remarkable.

02:33:14.640 --> 02:33:20.560
[Guest]: He says, I'm here to tell you that Pakistan's existence doesn't need a stamp from anybody.

02:33:20.560 --> 02:33:24.880
[Guest]: And the crowd there goes bananas, because they get exactly what he's trying to say.

02:33:24.880 --> 02:33:29.800
[Unknown]: At the same time, nobody in India makes a complaint, the RSS doesn't say anything, because

02:33:29.800 --> 02:33:33.240
[Unknown]: at least formally the sentence seems okay, you know.

02:33:33.240 --> 02:33:37.860
[Guest]: So this charisma that you're talking about is able to float people, charm parliament,

02:33:37.860 --> 02:33:43.880
[Guest]: but it's also able to say things and not say things that is able to pay for the very different

02:33:43.880 --> 02:33:48.640
[Guest]: and sometimes conflicting constituencies of Hindu nationalism.

02:33:48.640 --> 02:33:51.280
[Amit Varma]: And how much of Vajpayee is Mukhota?

02:33:51.280 --> 02:33:56.020
[Amit Varma]: Like how much of this is, do you think is your field is performative?

02:33:56.020 --> 02:34:00.280
[Amit Varma]: And how much is sort of the real Vajpayee, because it seems to me at different points

02:34:00.280 --> 02:34:04.120
[Amit Varma]: in your narrative, you get a sense of a man who does believe in certain things and is

02:34:04.120 --> 02:34:08.520
[Amit Varma]: willing to stand up, like, for example, his relationship with Rajkumari when Golwalkar

02:34:08.520 --> 02:34:12.920
[Amit Varma]: asked him to break that down, or even his sort of stubbornness towards like when he

02:34:12.920 --> 02:34:18.120
[Amit Varma]: forms the BJP in 1980, and he's saying Gandhian socialism, and we won't talk about the other

02:34:18.120 --> 02:34:23.280
[Amit Varma]: and he kind of abandons the Hindu vote, so to say what you would imagine, all of which,

02:34:23.280 --> 02:34:27.360
[Amit Varma]: you know, then goes to the Congress and the RSS stops working for them, but he kind of

02:34:27.360 --> 02:34:32.240
[Amit Varma]: sticks to his gun till the, you know, the election of 84, which is so disastrous.

02:34:32.240 --> 02:34:37.240
[Amit Varma]: So I did get the sense through the book that there are certain core beliefs that he will

02:34:37.240 --> 02:34:40.040
[Amit Varma]: not compromise on no matter what the politics.

02:34:40.040 --> 02:34:45.560
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit more about your sense of the man in those terms that between Mukhota

02:34:45.560 --> 02:34:48.200
[Amit Varma]: and man, you know, what's happening there?

02:34:48.200 --> 02:34:49.520
[Amit Varma]: Are there lines he will not cross?

02:34:49.520 --> 02:34:53.440
[Guest]: So good question, I mean, then, you know, despite having spent three years and reading

02:34:53.440 --> 02:34:56.040
[Guest]: everything he's written, I don't have an answer.

02:34:56.040 --> 02:35:00.000
[Guest]: And that's something I learned, even when I worked with Narsimha Rao, that you think

02:35:00.000 --> 02:35:04.280
[Guest]: you know, Narsimha Rao, I was focusing only on Narsimha Rao, and it was only a biography.

02:35:04.280 --> 02:35:09.040
[Guest]: And even so, there were parts of him I didn't understand, you know, and I then began to

02:35:09.040 --> 02:35:12.480
[Guest]: realize that, you know, if I think about my parents, or if I think about my wife, or I

02:35:12.480 --> 02:35:16.840
[Guest]: think about my daughter, you know, I know them so well, sometimes they surprise you.

02:35:16.840 --> 02:35:21.000
[Guest]: And I'm sure that your listeners and you also Amit, you think you know somebody very well.

02:35:21.000 --> 02:35:24.400
[Guest]: And then sometimes you realize you don't know, there's parts to them that you can never quite

02:35:24.400 --> 02:35:25.400
[Guest]: make out.

02:35:25.400 --> 02:35:29.160
[Guest]: And even while writing it, I wanted to leave that, like human beings are not mathematical

02:35:29.160 --> 02:35:32.280
[Guest]: equations where you figure them out, because they sometimes surprise you.

02:35:32.280 --> 02:35:36.920
[Guest]: And at least I hope that with Advani and Vajpayee, I make them living and breathing, and you

02:35:36.920 --> 02:35:41.120
[Unknown]: come away knowing something about them, but they also seem to have this ability to sometimes

02:35:41.120 --> 02:35:42.480
[Guest]: surprise you, right.

02:35:42.480 --> 02:35:47.800
[Guest]: So that's how I sort of told the story of Vajpayee, especially this sort of core conflict

02:35:47.800 --> 02:35:51.600
[Guest]: that you talked about saying that, you know, is he really a moderate or is he putting on

02:35:51.600 --> 02:35:52.600
[Guest]: a mask, right?

02:35:52.600 --> 02:35:56.760
[Guest]: And at times, it seemed he was wearing a mask, at times, he seemed that, you know, his instincts

02:35:56.760 --> 02:35:57.760
[Guest]: were liberal.

02:35:57.760 --> 02:36:03.600
[Guest]: And I didn't fight that, I didn't try to paper that over, and I didn't try to kind of explain

02:36:03.600 --> 02:36:04.600
[Guest]: it at the end.

02:36:04.600 --> 02:36:11.960
[Guest]: Except to say that, you know, large and great personalities are complex figures.

02:36:11.960 --> 02:36:16.000
[Unknown]: So they are like, Narsimha Rao, for example, had this deep vision for India, but was also

02:36:16.000 --> 02:36:17.000
[Guest]: a corrupt man.

02:36:17.000 --> 02:36:18.000
[Guest]: Right?

02:36:18.000 --> 02:36:21.520
[Guest]: Corrupt man in the sense, he definitely bribed the GMM MPs, I provide evidence for that.

02:36:21.520 --> 02:36:24.400
[Guest]: At the same time, he was a frugal man, the money wasn't for himself.

02:36:24.400 --> 02:36:29.200
[Guest]: So you know, it's a complex, could be very petty to his family, Narsimha Rao, Gandhi,

02:36:29.200 --> 02:36:32.240
[Unknown]: you know, he's not a good family man, didn't treat his sons very well.

02:36:32.240 --> 02:36:36.920
[Guest]: At the same time, you know, this remarkable human being, you know, outside of his family.

02:36:36.920 --> 02:36:42.720
[Guest]: And I think this desire to have just one answer I push against, and I push against because

02:36:42.720 --> 02:36:48.160
[Guest]: I don't know, you know, and maybe if I spent even five years, more years on this book,

02:36:48.160 --> 02:36:53.560
[Guest]: and only focused on Bajpayee, I may not have been able to get to the core of your answer.

02:36:53.560 --> 02:36:59.160
[Guest]: Except to say that, I think in a lot of cases, Bajpayee's first instinct was, quote unquote,

02:36:59.160 --> 02:37:00.160
[Guest]: liberal.

02:37:00.160 --> 02:37:04.760
[Guest]: But that was accompanied by this worry or this anxiety, that he was always a guest artist

02:37:04.760 --> 02:37:05.760
[Guest]: to the party.

02:37:05.760 --> 02:37:06.760
[Unknown]: Right?

02:37:06.760 --> 02:37:07.760
[Unknown]: So there is an element to that.

02:37:07.760 --> 02:37:15.800
[Guest]: But there is a magic to human beings and there is a magical inconsistency to human beings

02:37:15.800 --> 02:37:19.520
[Amit Varma]: that sometimes precludes me from answering a question like the one you asked.

02:37:19.520 --> 02:37:23.280
[Amit Varma]: No, and in fact, it's quite possible that Bajpayee himself wouldn't be able to answer

02:37:23.280 --> 02:37:26.240
[Amit Varma]: it because sometimes we are a mystery even to ourselves.

02:37:26.240 --> 02:37:29.960
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one of the other tropes of my show, which keeps coming up is about how everyone

02:37:29.960 --> 02:37:31.560
[Amit Varma]: contains multitudes.

02:37:31.560 --> 02:37:37.040
[Amit Varma]: And the sort of the three Indian figures I always cite when I'm talking about, you know,

02:37:37.040 --> 02:37:41.480
[Amit Varma]: how true that statement is, is Mahatma Gandhi, Nehru and Vajpayee.

02:37:41.480 --> 02:37:47.120
[Amit Varma]: You know, it was very sad when Vajpayee died recently that the response on social media,

02:37:47.120 --> 02:37:51.580
[Amit Varma]: especially was so polarized that either he was, you know, the best Prime Minister we

02:37:51.580 --> 02:37:52.580
[Amit Varma]: ever had.

02:37:52.580 --> 02:37:53.960
[Amit Varma]: And there is some truth to that.

02:37:53.960 --> 02:37:58.440
[Amit Varma]: Or he was, you know, a Hindu nationalist demagogue who was just othering Muslims.

02:37:58.440 --> 02:38:01.120
[Amit Varma]: And there is a little bit of truth to that as well.

02:38:01.120 --> 02:38:05.560
[Amit Varma]: But you know, before we move on to talking about the Bharatiya Jansangh, you know, that

02:38:05.560 --> 02:38:10.440
[Amit Varma]: first leg of the political movement where Vajpayee and Advani are really together.

02:38:10.440 --> 02:38:15.520
[Amit Varma]: One final question on Advani per se, because one of the interesting bits of trivia that

02:38:15.520 --> 02:38:20.960
[Amit Varma]: struck me from your book is that he was also a sort of a part-time film critic.

02:38:20.960 --> 02:38:23.960
[Amit Varma]: And that he wrote film reviews for the magazine, The Organizer.

02:38:23.960 --> 02:38:28.400
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, at one point when, you know, he criticized Richard Attenberg's Gandhi,

02:38:28.400 --> 02:38:33.280
[Amit Varma]: because he said that why are foreigners making a film on Gandhi, aren't Indians good enough

02:38:33.280 --> 02:38:34.280
[Amit Varma]: to do it?

02:38:34.280 --> 02:38:38.480
[Amit Varma]: And that led to a tangential question, which is neither about Advani nor about cinema,

02:38:38.480 --> 02:38:45.080
[Amit Varma]: but more about sort of protectionism and the Swadeshi Jagran Manch kind of sentiment that

02:38:45.080 --> 02:38:47.600
[Amit Varma]: foreign things are bad, Indian things are good.

02:38:47.600 --> 02:38:51.440
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, the economic logic behind that is complete rubbish.

02:38:51.440 --> 02:38:57.280
[Amit Varma]: But I've come to realize that the point of that sentiment is that insular protectionist

02:38:57.280 --> 02:39:03.240
[Amit Varma]: sentiment is not even so much sort of economic, though there is, of course, a political logic

02:39:03.240 --> 02:39:07.480
[Amit Varma]: of it that your base of small traders will want to be protected from imports and all

02:39:07.480 --> 02:39:12.960
[Amit Varma]: that, but is also in a sense, psychological, and it's this distrust and resentment and

02:39:12.960 --> 02:39:19.060
[Amit Varma]: hatred of the other who comes from outside because of, you know, these centuries of colonization

02:39:19.060 --> 02:39:20.880
[Amit Varma]: and invasion and all of that.

02:39:20.880 --> 02:39:26.200
[Amit Varma]: To what extent do you think that what is otherwise a sort of an economic position in the modern

02:39:26.200 --> 02:39:30.920
[Amit Varma]: world comes from this deep rooted psychological insecurity?

02:39:30.920 --> 02:39:33.880
[Guest]: Just two points on that.

02:39:33.880 --> 02:39:39.920
[Guest]: Before we talk about Janasang and BJP and the economic question, you know, you mentioned

02:39:39.920 --> 02:39:44.040
[Guest]: that Advani was a film critic, he was a full time film critic.

02:39:44.040 --> 02:39:47.680
[Guest]: And just as an interesting anecdote, for those of you who want to do research after this,

02:39:47.680 --> 02:39:53.760
[Unknown]: that in Advani's own memoir, I think I read, if my memory serves right, that, you know,

02:39:53.760 --> 02:39:58.560
[Guest]: he had spent some time with the organizer and he had a pen named Netraj, N-E-T-R-A.

02:39:58.560 --> 02:40:02.400
[Unknown]: So then, of course, my researcher mindset, let me go and find these articles, which was

02:40:02.400 --> 02:40:06.240
[Guest]: a huge pain because we're looking at articles written in the 1960s.

02:40:06.240 --> 02:40:10.280
[Unknown]: So I went to this archive, that archive, and in the 1960s and all is not digitized, it's

02:40:10.280 --> 02:40:14.560
[Unknown]: you know, it's a physical thing and you have to kind of open it, some of it is a microfilm.

02:40:14.560 --> 02:40:15.560
[Unknown]: So it's a lot of effort.

02:40:15.560 --> 02:40:20.040
[Guest]: But then I was able to pick out that some of, you know, Netraj's criticisms, including

02:40:20.040 --> 02:40:23.840
[Unknown]: like saying that, you know, when you want to make a film on Gandhi, why are we going

02:40:23.840 --> 02:40:24.840
[Unknown]: to Richard Attenborough, right?

02:40:24.840 --> 02:40:28.240
[Unknown]: It would eventually, a decade later come out as a film, but even then he was criticizing

02:40:28.240 --> 02:40:29.240
[Guest]: this.

02:40:29.240 --> 02:40:33.280
[Guest]: So, you know, this, this is a part about this process that I quite like, you get a clue

02:40:33.280 --> 02:40:35.920
[Guest]: somewhere, you know, I used to read Shalakum as a kid.

02:40:35.920 --> 02:40:39.560
[Guest]: So maybe I just, you know, if I can't do the real thing, I do like the fake thing, which

02:40:39.560 --> 02:40:43.280
[Guest]: is a researcher's Shalakum, which is, you get a tip like this, then you go to one library,

02:40:43.280 --> 02:40:48.480
[Guest]: you go to another library, you go to a microfilm and, you know, this, just doing that one sentence,

02:40:48.480 --> 02:40:52.960
[Guest]: finding out a couple of his reviews took me a lot of time, but it was worth it, you know,

02:40:52.960 --> 02:40:55.760
[Guest]: because it's someone like you will, you will read it and you'll immediately notice it and

02:40:55.760 --> 02:41:00.880
[Guest]: use, and it's a show don't tell, like, don't tell me that Advani was a reviewer, you know,

02:41:00.880 --> 02:41:05.240
[Guest]: write some of the, you know, quote him giving some of those reviews that itself gives you

02:41:05.240 --> 02:41:06.640
[Guest]: something about the man, right?

02:41:06.640 --> 02:41:11.520
[Guest]: So the, thank you for noticing that because otherwise a week could have been wasted, right?

02:41:11.520 --> 02:41:16.360
[Guest]: But the larger question you ask is about this instinct of protectionism that Hindu nationalism

02:41:16.360 --> 02:41:22.560
[Guest]: has, let me push back a little bit against that Amit, because I spent a lot of time in

02:41:22.560 --> 02:41:28.160
[Guest]: the book arguing that Hindu nationalism doesn't really have a theory of what to do once you

02:41:28.160 --> 02:41:29.600
[Guest]: have state power.

02:41:29.600 --> 02:41:34.000
[Guest]: So it has this theory on how you get state power in a democracy by uniting Hindus, othering

02:41:34.000 --> 02:41:36.280
[Guest]: Muslims, etc, etc, etc.

02:41:36.280 --> 02:41:41.080
[Guest]: But if you say, what is the Hindu nationalist view on foreign policy, on economics, on welfare

02:41:41.080 --> 02:41:42.640
[Guest]: scheme, it doesn't have it.

02:41:42.640 --> 02:41:47.040
[Guest]: You have Hindu nationalists over time, who have expressed views on it.

02:41:47.040 --> 02:41:51.280
[Guest]: So just like you have Arun Shourie, who is a strong pro marketer, who I would call a

02:41:51.280 --> 02:41:55.280
[Guest]: Hindu nationalist, you know, broadly, even though he's currently fighting with the institution,

02:41:55.280 --> 02:42:00.720
[Guest]: his cultural critiques, etc, etc, on Marxism, or against reservation, all of that have Hindu

02:42:00.720 --> 02:42:01.720
[Guest]: nationalist elements to it.

02:42:01.720 --> 02:42:06.720
[Guest]: At the same time, you have his former close friend, Gurumurthy, who was, you know, with

02:42:06.720 --> 02:42:07.720
[Guest]: the Swadeshi Jagran Manch.

02:42:07.720 --> 02:42:13.560
[Guest]: Much earlier, as I point out in the book itself, you have Subramanian Swamy and Balraj Madho,

02:42:13.560 --> 02:42:17.320
[Guest]: who wanted a frontal assault on Indira Gandhi's socialism.

02:42:17.320 --> 02:42:21.120
[Guest]: But you have Deep Dayal Upadhyaya and Vajpayee who push against it, and they push against

02:42:21.120 --> 02:42:26.160
[Guest]: it not for ideological reasons, but they feel that the Indian voter was actually not free

02:42:26.160 --> 02:42:27.560
[Guest]: market at that time.

02:42:27.560 --> 02:42:32.560
[Guest]: So even if they were rejecting Indira Gandhi, they were not rejecting the Nehruvian consensus.

02:42:32.560 --> 02:42:37.800
[Guest]: And that tells you, in the book itself, that on this, there's plenty of diversity within

02:42:37.800 --> 02:42:38.800
[Guest]: Hindu nationalism.

02:42:38.800 --> 02:42:43.640
[Guest]: So even this protectionist instinct that you talk about, is not in evidence when they come

02:42:43.640 --> 02:42:44.640
[Guest]: to power.

02:42:44.640 --> 02:42:48.920
[Guest]: I mean, I would argue and the book does argue that Yashwant Sinha and Jaiswant Singh, who

02:42:48.920 --> 02:42:54.280
[Guest]: were the finance ministers of the Vajpayee government between 98 and 2004, were the most

02:42:54.280 --> 02:43:00.720
[Guest]: kind of anti-statist, pro market finance ministers India has had, and I would say that, you know,

02:43:00.720 --> 02:43:05.040
[Guest]: and maybe this is betraying my own ideological impulses, so feel free to disagree with you,

02:43:05.040 --> 02:43:08.840
[Guest]: that did India a lot of good in those years, you know, between 98 and 2000.

02:43:08.840 --> 02:43:14.400
[Guest]: Once again, you know, I even when I teach, I say, the few times I show you my cards,

02:43:14.400 --> 02:43:18.200
[Guest]: I wanted to be clear to the listener that there are other cards that one can play, you

02:43:18.200 --> 02:43:19.200
[Guest]: know.

02:43:19.200 --> 02:43:25.400
[Guest]: So that's a complex answer to this question that the protectionist instinct is not embedded

02:43:25.400 --> 02:43:26.400
[Guest]: in Hindu nationalism.

02:43:26.400 --> 02:43:27.400
[Guest]: It's just not.

02:43:27.400 --> 02:43:33.000
[Guest]: If you look at the thinkers, if you look at the actions, and therefore to answer the question,

02:43:33.000 --> 02:43:38.680
[Guest]: why is Narendra Modi's economic policy the way it is, don't look at Hindu nationalism.

02:43:38.680 --> 02:43:39.680
[Guest]: Don't look at Savarkar.

02:43:39.680 --> 02:43:40.680
[Guest]: Look at Narendra Modi.

02:43:40.680 --> 02:43:41.680
[Guest]: Look at the circumstances.

02:43:41.680 --> 02:43:46.440
[Guest]: If you want to understand demonetization, don't read like Dindayal Upadhyay, right?

02:43:46.440 --> 02:43:48.760
[Guest]: So the ideology does some things for you.

02:43:48.760 --> 02:43:49.760
[Guest]: And that's very important.

02:43:49.760 --> 02:43:55.800
[Guest]: For example, you can't understand what Narendra Modi and Amit Shah have done on Article 370

02:43:55.800 --> 02:44:00.080
[Guest]: without knowing that the Jan Sangh right from the fifties itself has said in the constitution,

02:44:00.080 --> 02:44:03.680
[Guest]: in their manifesto, if we come to power, this is what we'll do.

02:44:03.680 --> 02:44:08.600
[Guest]: The Citizenship Amendment Act and the NRC again, is based on this ideological obsession

02:44:08.600 --> 02:44:09.600
[Guest]: with demographics.

02:44:09.600 --> 02:44:14.080
[Guest]: So to understand those actions of the Modi government or the Vajpayee government, definitely

02:44:14.080 --> 02:44:15.560
[Guest]: look to ideology.

02:44:15.560 --> 02:44:21.960
[Guest]: But the Hindu nationalist ideology is silent on 90% of things we, you and me would call

02:44:21.960 --> 02:44:22.960
[Guest]: governance, right?

02:44:22.960 --> 02:44:29.360
[Guest]: So there may be individual RSS heads who have a view on it, like Sudarshan did, who was

02:44:29.360 --> 02:44:35.680
[Guest]: kind of left-wing on economics and Dattopan Thegdi, again, RSS man who founded India's

02:44:35.680 --> 02:44:37.320
[Guest]: largest trade union.

02:44:37.320 --> 02:44:41.880
[Guest]: But there are plenty of others within Hindu nationalism who don't agree with that.

02:44:41.880 --> 02:44:46.960
[Guest]: That's what makes it remarkable to Amit that on a lot of intellectual areas, it's actually

02:44:46.960 --> 02:44:52.720
[Guest]: a broad tent that as long as you don't defeat the party, split the party, you're actually

02:44:52.720 --> 02:44:55.760
[Guest]: allowed to have various kinds of views within it.

02:44:55.760 --> 02:44:57.320
[Amit Varma]: No, that's a fair point.

02:44:57.320 --> 02:44:58.780
[Amit Varma]: And you've revealed your cards.

02:44:58.780 --> 02:45:03.800
[Amit Varma]: But I'll also at this point, reveal my cards and point out that the two central figures

02:45:03.800 --> 02:45:07.840
[Amit Varma]: of your two biographies, Narasimha Rao and Vajpayee are in my mind, the best prime ministers

02:45:07.840 --> 02:45:09.240
[Amit Varma]: we've had by far.

02:45:09.240 --> 02:45:14.320
[Amit Varma]: But here I would again, sort of not exactly push back, but just state a thought that comes

02:45:14.320 --> 02:45:19.200
[Amit Varma]: to my mind that if you, you know, Jaswant and Yashwant were good finance ministers,

02:45:19.200 --> 02:45:20.200
[Amit Varma]: but they were not from the RSS.

02:45:20.200 --> 02:45:21.200
[Amit Varma]: They were sort of outsiders.

02:45:21.200 --> 02:45:26.040
[Amit Varma]: Jaswant really, you know, came from the Swatantra party and Yashwant Sinha was an earlier finance

02:45:26.040 --> 02:45:28.120
[Amit Varma]: minister for another government.

02:45:28.120 --> 02:45:33.280
[Amit Varma]: And the RSS, like you pointed out about how in the 80s, because the RSS felt that the

02:45:33.280 --> 02:45:37.440
[Amit Varma]: BJP was ignoring the Hindu vote, you know, they reset up the Vishwa Hindu Parishad in

02:45:37.440 --> 02:45:38.440
[Amit Varma]: a sense.

02:45:38.440 --> 02:45:44.600
[Amit Varma]: And similarly, in 91, when liberalization happened, because they felt that the BJP wasn't

02:45:44.600 --> 02:45:50.920
[Amit Varma]: strong enough in voicing their opposition to it, they set up the Swadeshi Jagran Manch.

02:45:50.920 --> 02:45:56.600
[Amit Varma]: So at least from the RSS point of view, you know, there seems to be some continuity.

02:45:56.600 --> 02:46:01.280
[Amit Varma]: And it struck me that this might come not from economic ideology, being pro free markets

02:46:01.280 --> 02:46:07.000
[Amit Varma]: or against them or whatever, but just a distrust of foreigners in general.

02:46:07.000 --> 02:46:11.040
[Amit Varma]: But yeah, but I mean, that's just kind of me thinking aloud.

02:46:11.040 --> 02:46:14.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's, do you want to respond to that?

02:46:14.000 --> 02:46:19.160
[Guest]: I mean, I don't know, because, you know, look, there's definitely a nativist instinct in

02:46:19.160 --> 02:46:20.160
[Guest]: the RSS.

02:46:20.160 --> 02:46:24.120
[Guest]: The question is, to what extent does it, is it articulated in policy?

02:46:24.120 --> 02:46:25.120
[Guest]: That's what we really care about.

02:46:25.120 --> 02:46:26.120
[Guest]: Right?

02:46:26.120 --> 02:46:27.120
[Guest]: And I'm like, don't look there.

02:46:27.120 --> 02:46:30.640
[Unknown]: But look, during the Vajpayee government, Amit, there are many other areas where you

02:46:30.640 --> 02:46:34.600
[Guest]: can see the imprint on the RSS, for example, on teaching of history, right?

02:46:34.600 --> 02:46:38.920
[Guest]: Actually, RSS didn't care really about that the foreign minister wasn't from the RSS,

02:46:38.920 --> 02:46:42.560
[Guest]: but they wanted Rudlimanav Joshi to be the education or HRD minister.

02:46:42.560 --> 02:46:43.560
[Unknown]: They care about it, right?

02:46:43.560 --> 02:46:48.440
[Guest]: Equally, when it came to telecom and roads, I point out, the RSS supported it, because

02:46:48.440 --> 02:46:54.360
[Unknown]: just like the RSS support for GST, it supports the vision of a united India, unity, remember,

02:46:54.360 --> 02:46:57.440
[Unknown]: that's the core idea, territorial and cultural unity.

02:46:57.440 --> 02:46:59.920
[Guest]: So you have to think of it in those terms, right?

02:46:59.920 --> 02:47:05.560
[Guest]: Because when you spend a lot of time thinking about the RSS as these anti-Dalvian protectionists,

02:47:05.560 --> 02:47:09.880
[Guest]: and then you end up with two prime ministers who whatever else you say, that's not the

02:47:09.880 --> 02:47:11.720
[Unknown]: frame in which you think about them.

02:47:11.720 --> 02:47:16.000
[Guest]: So when they have come to power, that's not the frame in which they have operated, right?

02:47:16.000 --> 02:47:22.120
[Guest]: And even today, you know, on the disputes that the RSS, the Swadeshi Jagrand Manch or

02:47:22.120 --> 02:47:27.440
[Guest]: the RSS trade unions are having with the Modi government, you know, on let's say on some

02:47:27.440 --> 02:47:30.440
[Guest]: of the economic reforms that they're trying to do.

02:47:30.440 --> 02:47:33.680
[Guest]: It's not that Mohan Bhagwat is taking the side of the Swadeshi Jagrand Manch against

02:47:33.680 --> 02:47:34.680
[Guest]: Modi.

02:47:34.680 --> 02:47:39.240
[Amit Varma]: He's like, look, this is a family, figure it out, you know, which is a healthy attitude,

02:47:39.240 --> 02:47:40.240
[Amit Varma]: frankly.

02:47:40.240 --> 02:47:41.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, absolutely.

02:47:41.240 --> 02:47:45.520
[Amit Varma]: And to sort of buttress your point about Modi, there's clearly no ideology there like I did

02:47:45.520 --> 02:47:49.640
[Amit Varma]: this episode with Pooja Mehra, who's written the book called The Lost Decade, which, you

02:47:49.640 --> 02:47:53.280
[Amit Varma]: know, describes in very fine detail how everything that Modi did in government was shaped by

02:47:53.280 --> 02:47:57.800
[Amit Varma]: political imperatives when, you know, he was with a jibe of a suit boot, the government

02:47:57.800 --> 02:47:59.800
[Amit Varma]: was thrown at him and all of that.

02:47:59.800 --> 02:48:04.280
[Amit Varma]: And he figured that economic reforms would not sell with the public.

02:48:04.280 --> 02:48:10.240
[Amit Varma]: He instantly kind of moved away from it and went into status populist directions as it

02:48:10.240 --> 02:48:11.240
[Amit Varma]: were.

