02:49:43.600 --> 02:49:44.880
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen.

02:49:44.880 --> 02:49:49.760
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Vinay Sitapati on his marvelous book Jugalbandi, the BJP before Modi.

02:49:49.760 --> 02:49:54.760
[Amit Varma]: And now, you know, we've spoken about sort of the background of Hindu nationalism and,

02:49:54.760 --> 02:49:58.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, all the different conditions which lead to it sort of coming to being.

02:49:58.800 --> 02:50:03.200
[Amit Varma]: We spoken about the different personalities of Advani and Vajpayee and the relationship

02:50:03.200 --> 02:50:04.200
[Amit Varma]: between them.

02:50:04.200 --> 02:50:08.480
[Amit Varma]: I want to speak now a little bit about the Bhartiya Jansangh.

02:50:08.480 --> 02:50:12.600
[Amit Varma]: You know, we spoke about how it originated because after the assassination of Mahatma

02:50:12.600 --> 02:50:17.280
[Amit Varma]: Gandhi, when the RSS was sort of thrust into the wilderness and demonized and banned for

02:50:17.280 --> 02:50:21.040
[Amit Varma]: a few months, they realized that we need to have a political voice.

02:50:21.040 --> 02:50:25.680
[Amit Varma]: And you know, Golwalkar, despite being initially hesitant, said, okay, let's go for it and

02:50:25.680 --> 02:50:32.920
[Amit Varma]: supplied his RSS pracharaks and his RSS people to this new party led by Shyama Prasad Mukherjee.

02:50:32.920 --> 02:50:38.720
[Amit Varma]: And then, you know, who dies young, so at 51, so, and there's an interesting counterfactual

02:50:38.720 --> 02:50:39.720
[Amit Varma]: there.

02:50:39.720 --> 02:50:40.800
[Amit Varma]: And if we have time, I'll ask you about those.

02:50:40.800 --> 02:50:42.880
[Amit Varma]: But then Vajpayee and Advani take over the party.

02:50:42.880 --> 02:50:47.400
[Amit Varma]: Now this, the next phase that happens is very interesting to me, because what you point

02:50:47.400 --> 02:50:52.680
[Amit Varma]: out is that for about 15 to 18 years, they have to function within what you call the

02:50:52.680 --> 02:50:54.740
[Amit Varma]: Nehruvian consensus.

02:50:54.740 --> 02:50:57.020
[Amit Varma]: So what do you mean by that?

02:50:57.020 --> 02:51:01.560
[Amit Varma]: And tell me a little bit about what it implies and which are the areas where Vajpayee and

02:51:01.560 --> 02:51:07.320
[Amit Varma]: Advani feel that they can compromise, because they have to go with the temper of the times

02:51:07.320 --> 02:51:12.080
[Amit Varma]: and which are the areas that are so core to them, that they never compromise on those?

02:51:12.080 --> 02:51:18.920
[Guest]: Amit, I think the Nehruvian consensus, the way I use it in the book, has three pillars.

02:51:18.920 --> 02:51:22.960
[Guest]: Pillar one, which is the most controversial pillar is the relationship between the state

02:51:22.960 --> 02:51:23.960
[Guest]: and Hinduism.

02:51:23.960 --> 02:51:28.840
[Guest]: Now, I don't want to say the sentence Nehru was anti-Hindu, I mean, the BJP says that

02:51:28.840 --> 02:51:29.840
[Guest]: all the time.

02:51:29.840 --> 02:51:31.080
[Guest]: I don't think that's right.

02:51:31.080 --> 02:51:36.400
[Guest]: But Nehru certainly was worried that a Hindu majority country, where the majority of Hindus

02:51:36.400 --> 02:51:41.720
[Guest]: were religious Hindus, it wasn't just they were Hindus by name only, there was a threat

02:51:41.720 --> 02:51:44.200
[Guest]: that the religion would enter the state.

02:51:44.200 --> 02:51:51.840
[Guest]: So just speaking descriptively, objectively, without any value judgment, Nehru definitely

02:51:51.840 --> 02:51:56.320
[Guest]: intervened in Hinduism, much more than he intervened in other religions.

02:51:56.320 --> 02:52:01.800
[Guest]: This is the codification of Hindu law, for example.

02:52:01.800 --> 02:52:06.800
[Guest]: The other thing that the BJP talks about all the time, which is that, why is Tirupati temple

02:52:06.800 --> 02:52:09.760
[Guest]: run by three IAS officers?

02:52:09.760 --> 02:52:14.640
[Guest]: This of course is long standing, but it is a grouse that they have that, why has nationalization

02:52:14.640 --> 02:52:17.560
[Guest]: of temples taken place and not other religions?

02:52:17.560 --> 02:52:22.200
[Guest]: I think part of the reason was that Nehru felt that this force had to be controlled.

02:52:22.200 --> 02:52:27.880
[Guest]: Otherwise, it would go against his modernizing experiment and part of it was that he felt

02:52:27.880 --> 02:52:29.600
[Guest]: that he was a Hindu.

02:52:29.600 --> 02:52:35.760
[Guest]: So as a Hindu, he had the right and the legitimacy to intervene in Hindu affairs, especially

02:52:35.760 --> 02:52:40.000
[Guest]: because Hinduism doesn't have an authoritative church or an authoritative text.

02:52:40.000 --> 02:52:45.920
[Guest]: So the modern Nehruvian state became the vehicle for speaking and reforming Hinduism, right,

02:52:45.920 --> 02:52:50.600
[Guest]: which is the BJP and the Jansans counter to that has always been, but Nehru is not really

02:52:50.600 --> 02:52:51.840
[Guest]: a Hindu.

02:52:51.840 --> 02:52:53.000
[Guest]: But Nehru believed that.

02:52:53.000 --> 02:52:57.880
[Guest]: On the other hand, he did not think, especially when it came to dealing with post-partition

02:52:57.880 --> 02:53:03.120
[Guest]: Muslims that he had the same legitimacy or the Congress party had the same legitimacy

02:53:03.120 --> 02:53:05.000
[Guest]: to deal with Muslim affairs.

02:53:05.000 --> 02:53:09.440
[Guest]: On hindsight, you can say that he was being a little short-sighted because even though

02:53:09.440 --> 02:53:15.240
[Guest]: he had a, you know, I wouldn't say noble, but he had a pretty idealistic aim here.

02:53:15.240 --> 02:53:19.560
[Guest]: It has been, you know, it does expose that the state has not been even handed when it

02:53:19.560 --> 02:53:24.640
[Guest]: comes to religion and it has definitely given the BJP an issue from an issue where there

02:53:24.640 --> 02:53:25.640
[Guest]: was none.

02:53:25.640 --> 02:53:29.200
[Guest]: And I think those of your listeners who don't like the BJP, I think the first thing you

02:53:29.200 --> 02:53:34.000
[Guest]: should do is to admit this and then to say, but so what, you know, and this was his particular

02:53:34.000 --> 02:53:35.000
[Guest]: logic.

02:53:35.000 --> 02:53:39.680
[Guest]: So I think that's the first pillar of the Nehruvian consensus, which is that a particular

02:53:39.680 --> 02:53:43.520
[Guest]: worry that Hinduism and traditional Hinduism should stay out of the state.

02:53:43.520 --> 02:53:47.440
[Guest]: Nehru, of course, didn't have a worry that Islam would enter the Indian state because

02:53:47.440 --> 02:53:52.600
[Guest]: Muslims were a minority, but he did have this special worry when it came to Hinduism.

02:53:52.600 --> 02:53:56.360
[Guest]: Second Amit, and you know, I'm, I'm a fan of your podcast enough to know that the second

02:53:56.360 --> 02:54:01.240
[Guest]: pillar is something you don't like, which is the role of the state in the economy, in

02:54:01.240 --> 02:54:06.240
[Guest]: society, the, you know, big brother, you know, can see all, knows all.

02:54:06.240 --> 02:54:11.760
[Guest]: That was a modernizing impulse that, you know, the Madhav Khosla, who's been on your podcast

02:54:11.760 --> 02:54:17.440
[Guest]: before, you know, made it quite clear to your listeners that Nehru's and Ambedkar's idea

02:54:17.440 --> 02:54:22.280
[Guest]: of the constitution was premised on the fact that they thought traditional Indian society

02:54:22.280 --> 02:54:24.680
[Guest]: was incapable of liberal democracy.

02:54:24.680 --> 02:54:29.640
[Guest]: And so the constitution would be this transformative, you know, and a teaching tool to teach Indians

02:54:29.640 --> 02:54:32.080
[Guest]: to understand liberal secular democracy.

02:54:32.080 --> 02:54:33.120
[Guest]: Right.

02:54:33.120 --> 02:54:37.600
[Guest]: So that I think was the second pillar of the Nehruvian state, which is that a belief that

02:54:37.600 --> 02:54:43.240
[Guest]: the modern state will be the vehicle for transformation of the Indian economy and, and society.

02:54:43.240 --> 02:54:49.160
[Guest]: A third pillar, which had to do more with temperament than policy was this belief that

02:54:49.160 --> 02:54:52.960
[Guest]: you must respect the protocols of democracy.

02:54:52.960 --> 02:54:56.200
[Guest]: You must mean, you know, respect constitutional functionaries.

02:54:56.200 --> 02:55:01.080
[Guest]: You must respect those, you know, who you actually have power over to give you just

02:55:01.080 --> 02:55:06.400
[Guest]: one example, Nehru was remarkably courteous to his chief ministers, the chief ministers

02:55:06.400 --> 02:55:11.800
[Guest]: during that time, even though, especially after 1950, Nehru completely controlled the

02:55:11.800 --> 02:55:16.720
[Guest]: Congress party and the chief ministers were totally beholden to him yet, as you can see

02:55:16.720 --> 02:55:20.320
[Guest]: from his letters to chief ministers, he was very respectful of that.

02:55:20.320 --> 02:55:25.800
[Guest]: So these were the three pillars of the Nehruvian consensus, a particular worry that Hinduism

02:55:25.800 --> 02:55:26.800
[Guest]: would take over the state.

02:55:26.800 --> 02:55:31.520
[Guest]: Let me put that in the most neutral way possible, a belief that the state, the heavy handed

02:55:31.520 --> 02:55:36.520
[Guest]: state would, from the commanding heights, not just transform the economy, but transform

02:55:36.520 --> 02:55:37.520
[Guest]: Indian society.

02:55:37.520 --> 02:55:44.120
[Guest]: And third is a temperament in which you respected constitutional functionaries, you know, even

02:55:44.120 --> 02:55:49.760
[Guest]: when Nehru disagreed with the Supreme Court, as I think Tripu Dhaman Singh was already

02:55:49.760 --> 02:55:51.440
[Guest]: come on your podcast.

02:55:51.440 --> 02:55:56.040
[Guest]: I just feel that when I answer your questions, I also answer, you know, half your podcast

02:55:56.040 --> 02:55:57.960
[Guest]: listeners come through.

02:55:57.960 --> 02:56:02.920
[Guest]: But I think that was the third aspect of it, which is that he was, you know, he treated

02:56:02.920 --> 02:56:06.580
[Guest]: even the Supreme Court with some respect, he was careful about what he said.

02:56:06.580 --> 02:56:10.480
[Guest]: So he exemplified this larger democratic temperament.

02:56:10.480 --> 02:56:17.200
[Guest]: Now, Vajpayee and Advani sort of come on to the national stage at a time when two things

02:56:17.200 --> 02:56:20.880
[Guest]: are happening, which is giving, putting them on the defensive, which is forcing them to

02:56:20.880 --> 02:56:21.880
[Guest]: play back foot.

02:56:21.880 --> 02:56:26.280
[Guest]: One is that the Nehruvian consensus is completely dominant in parliament.

02:56:26.280 --> 02:56:32.040
[Guest]: And I don't just mean with the Congress party, you know, I think that's a mistake, you know,

02:56:32.040 --> 02:56:37.720
[Guest]: for people to see that even the non-Congress opposition bought many of the principles of

02:56:37.720 --> 02:56:38.960
[Guest]: the Nehruvian consensus.

02:56:38.960 --> 02:56:43.160
[Guest]: So you can say that Rajaji and the Swatantra party, you know, had a slight departure when

02:56:43.160 --> 02:56:47.800
[Guest]: it came to the role of the state in the economy, but many of the other precepts he agreed.

02:56:47.800 --> 02:56:53.120
[Guest]: So I would say that most of the parliamentary opposition to the Congress party agreed with

02:56:53.120 --> 02:56:55.920
[Guest]: about 70 to 80% of the Nehruvian consensus.

02:56:55.920 --> 02:56:57.600
[Guest]: It was that powerful.

02:56:57.600 --> 02:57:02.560
[Guest]: And today, when you see a Modi consensus or a Narsimha consensus in India, I think people

02:57:02.560 --> 02:57:08.200
[Guest]: will find it very hard to remember how much of a colossus Nehru was both in parliament

02:57:08.200 --> 02:57:09.200
[Guest]: and in India.

02:57:09.200 --> 02:57:13.000
[Guest]: You know, today they all say, oh, he's a, you know, UP Brahmin or a Kashmiri Brahmin

02:57:13.000 --> 02:57:15.960
[Guest]: who sort of moved to UP, what's his social base?

02:57:15.960 --> 02:57:16.960
[Guest]: Is he like Lalu Yadav?

02:57:16.960 --> 02:57:21.800
[Guest]: I mean, he had a national base and he really stood out as the hope of post-independent

02:57:21.800 --> 02:57:22.800
[Guest]: India.

02:57:22.800 --> 02:57:26.760
[Guest]: And I am critical of him in the book saying that, you know, his self-conscious elitism

02:57:26.760 --> 02:57:29.280
[Guest]: has brought the Congress party where it is today.

02:57:29.280 --> 02:57:33.260
[Guest]: So there's something conceptual in that idea, but nonetheless, he was a colossus.

02:57:33.260 --> 02:57:38.880
[Guest]: So Vajpayee and Advani had to deal with that and Vajpayee in particular, and Vajpayee therefore

02:57:38.880 --> 02:57:43.760
[Guest]: adopted the Nehruvian consensus because that's what it meant to be respectable in parliament.

02:57:43.760 --> 02:57:48.920
[Guest]: And as we've discussed before, Vajpayee, the thing he cared about the most was speaking

02:57:48.920 --> 02:57:50.960
[Guest]: in parliament, charming the opposition.

02:57:50.960 --> 02:57:55.560
[Guest]: He didn't really care who ran the party and he was very happy for Advani to do that.

02:57:55.560 --> 02:57:59.120
[Guest]: So that was the first impact on Vajpayee, the Nehruvian consensus.

02:57:59.120 --> 02:58:03.840
[Guest]: The second reason why the Jansangh of that period, now which is the Prakasa party to

02:58:03.840 --> 02:58:09.320
[Guest]: the BJP had to fall within the Nehruvian consensus was the murder of Mahatma Gandhi.

02:58:09.320 --> 02:58:15.400
[Guest]: As we discussed earlier, the Jansangh or Hindu nationalism more generally was on the ascendant

02:58:15.400 --> 02:58:20.060
[Guest]: after partition because what the Hindu Mahasabha and the RSS had been complaining about Gandhi

02:58:20.060 --> 02:58:24.720
[Guest]: and the Congress all this while, namely that the appeasement of the Muslim League would

02:58:24.720 --> 02:58:27.640
[Guest]: result in the breakage of India actually happened.

02:58:27.640 --> 02:58:30.240
[Guest]: And we don't have evidence for this in terms of elections.

02:58:30.240 --> 02:58:34.760
[Guest]: But if you just look at the increase in enrollment of Hindu Mahasabha, increase in enrollment

02:58:34.760 --> 02:58:41.720
[Guest]: of RSS between August 1947 and February 1948, which is when Gandhi is assassinated, it's

02:58:41.720 --> 02:58:47.320
[Guest]: definitely on the ascendant and people I speak to within the RSS and the Jansangh of that

02:58:47.320 --> 02:58:53.680
[Guest]: period really felt that this was their chance, that we had an 80% Hindu majority, half the

02:58:53.680 --> 02:58:56.960
[Guest]: Muslim population, no Britishers, this was their chance.

02:58:56.960 --> 02:59:03.120
[Guest]: The murder of the Mahatma, who was the leader of Hindus, ironically made the RSS and Hindu

02:59:03.120 --> 02:59:08.800
[Guest]: Mahasabha seem like a party that was opposed to the interest of the vast majority of moderate

02:59:08.800 --> 02:59:09.800
[Guest]: Hindus.

02:59:09.800 --> 02:59:15.480
[Guest]: And so, I mean, the RSS was banned, Hindu Mahasabha wasn't banned, but every time there

02:59:15.480 --> 02:59:19.720
[Guest]: was an election, you know, whoever was opposing the Jansangh candidate would bring up saying

02:59:19.720 --> 02:59:21.960
[Guest]: that they have the blood of Gandhi on their hands, right?

02:59:21.960 --> 02:59:24.720
[Guest]: And as I point out, that's not, the evidence is not there.

02:59:24.720 --> 02:59:29.400
[Guest]: So they always had the sense that they had to mainstream themselves and it took them

02:59:29.400 --> 02:59:30.840
[Guest]: a very long time.

02:59:30.840 --> 02:59:35.240
[Guest]: And the way to mainstream themselves, Amit, was to basically fall within the Nehruvian

02:59:35.240 --> 02:59:38.840
[Guest]: consensus on which 80 to 90% didn't disagree.

02:59:38.840 --> 02:59:42.960
[Guest]: They did disagree on the role of Hinduism in the state, but that was something they

02:59:42.960 --> 02:59:45.760
[Guest]: downplayed in the initial years.

02:59:45.760 --> 02:59:50.000
[Guest]: The third thing, Amit, that aided them in falling into the Nehruvian consensus is something

02:59:50.000 --> 02:59:56.200
[Guest]: that we discussed earlier, which is that on 80% of issues we call governance, Hindu nationalism

02:59:56.200 --> 02:59:57.840
[Guest]: doesn't really have a view.

02:59:57.840 --> 03:00:02.400
[Guest]: So when it came to foreign policy of Nehru, non-aligned movement, when it came to his

03:00:02.400 --> 03:00:07.040
[Guest]: economics, sure, you know, individual Jansangh members like Balraj Madhok had problems, Subramaniam

03:00:07.040 --> 03:00:12.960
[Guest]: Swami had a problem, but they couldn't rely on ideology to make that case and that made

03:00:12.960 --> 03:00:17.080
[Guest]: it much easier for Atal Bihari Vajpayee to go with that.

03:00:17.080 --> 03:00:22.040
[Guest]: And as evidence of that point that I give you is that once the central hall of parliament,

03:00:22.040 --> 03:00:26.960
[Guest]: which is sort of the heart of where the gossip and the chai is drunk in parliament, when

03:00:26.960 --> 03:00:31.720
[Guest]: that consensus changes after Narsimha Rao, especially with regard to the relationship

03:00:31.720 --> 03:00:36.680
[Guest]: between the state and the economy, Vajpayee changes too, you know, and that tells you

03:00:36.680 --> 03:00:38.480
[Guest]: that he doesn't have deep views on this.

03:00:38.480 --> 03:00:42.080
[Guest]: He just wants to go with whatever makes common sense in parliament.

03:00:42.080 --> 03:00:46.800
[Guest]: So that's the, you know, the relationship between Vajpayee and the Nehruvian consensus.

03:00:46.800 --> 03:00:52.800
[Guest]: The reason I'm giving you a long answer to this, Amit, is too many both admirers of Vajpayee

03:00:52.800 --> 03:00:57.240
[Guest]: as well as his right-wing detractors used to say, look, he's half a congressman, you

03:00:57.240 --> 03:00:59.800
[Guest]: know, he was bedazzled by the charm of Nehru.

03:00:59.800 --> 03:01:01.240
[Guest]: That's not the case at all.

03:01:01.240 --> 03:01:02.680
[Guest]: He was a wily politician.

03:01:02.680 --> 03:01:06.760
[Guest]: He understood very clearly that Nehru was the consensus and he didn't want to break

03:01:06.760 --> 03:01:07.760
[Guest]: from the consensus.

03:01:07.760 --> 03:01:13.280
[Guest]: And that's also why the RSS supported Vajpayee when it came to these quote-unquote left-wing

03:01:13.280 --> 03:01:14.280
[Guest]: views.

03:01:14.280 --> 03:01:15.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

03:01:15.280 --> 03:01:19.440
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, one like there is something in this journey of Vajpayee and his strategy

03:01:19.440 --> 03:01:23.880
[Amit Varma]: towards sort of dealing with politics that comes down all the way to the present day

03:01:23.880 --> 03:01:28.200
[Amit Varma]: to the, you know, even the way Modi and Amit Shah approach politics, which is, you know,

03:01:28.200 --> 03:01:32.760
[Amit Varma]: again, as you pointed out in your book, you know, in the first elections, the Jansangh

03:01:32.760 --> 03:01:38.760
[Amit Varma]: perhaps, partly because of Shama Prasad Mukherjee's charisma and all that, get 3.06% of the vote,

03:01:38.760 --> 03:01:41.600
[Amit Varma]: but that's more than Hindu Mahasabha and Ram Rajya Party.

03:01:41.600 --> 03:01:48.280
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, the Bharatiya Jansangh automatically becomes the primary Hindu party, so to say.

03:01:48.280 --> 03:01:52.640
[Amit Varma]: Now, one, you've pointed out how because of the political imperative of fitting within

03:01:52.640 --> 03:01:56.720
[Amit Varma]: the Nehruvian consensus, you know, they sort of moderate themselves.

03:01:56.720 --> 03:02:00.480
[Amit Varma]: But even later at different points in time, like one of the really fascinating parts of

03:02:00.480 --> 03:02:05.900
[Amit Varma]: the book is how the political wind is influencing Vajpayee.

03:02:05.900 --> 03:02:10.760
[Amit Varma]: And for example, you know, after the VHP comes up in 1964, and you have anti-cow slaughter

03:02:10.760 --> 03:02:16.600
[Amit Varma]: becoming an issue, they used that in the 1967 elections, a pivot towards that, you know,

03:02:16.600 --> 03:02:20.040
[Amit Varma]: with Vijay Rajesh India being a major patron of the party.

03:02:20.040 --> 03:02:24.120
[Amit Varma]: And in that elections, they have the second largest vote share after the Congress, but

03:02:24.120 --> 03:02:25.940
[Amit Varma]: third in terms of seats.

03:02:25.940 --> 03:02:30.560
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, then you point out about how Vajpayee, which, you know, fans of his prime

03:02:30.560 --> 03:02:35.400
[Amit Varma]: ministership may recoil a bit to see this, but he supported the bank nationalizations

03:02:35.400 --> 03:02:40.400
[Amit Varma]: of Indira Gandhi and many of the economic policies, because that's the way the political

03:02:40.400 --> 03:02:41.640
[Amit Varma]: wind was blowing.

03:02:41.640 --> 03:02:47.160
[Amit Varma]: And I'm struck by this very interesting article you cite, which was written in 1971, which

03:02:47.160 --> 03:02:52.820
[Amit Varma]: Vajpayee wrote, but under the sort of pen name of Urs William Sewak, where he spoke

03:02:52.820 --> 03:02:59.640
[Amit Varma]: about the need to balance ideology and power and to realize that if you wanted to go with

03:02:59.640 --> 03:03:05.480
[Amit Varma]: power, you had to, at some levels in the political sphere, compromise on ideology.

03:03:05.480 --> 03:03:10.200
[Amit Varma]: And you speak about how, you know, when Golwalkar reads this, he realizes pen name or no pen

03:03:10.200 --> 03:03:14.280
[Amit Varma]: name only Vajpayee can write like this and he calls Vajpayee over to chat with him.

03:03:14.280 --> 03:03:19.360
[Amit Varma]: And he realizes that Vajpayee in a sense is right, that the RSS needs to take a step back

03:03:19.360 --> 03:03:23.240
[Amit Varma]: and, you know, let Vajpayee kind of go down this route.

03:03:23.240 --> 03:03:28.480
[Amit Varma]: Now, this sort of leads me to this larger question that even in modern times, and this

03:03:28.480 --> 03:03:33.960
[Amit Varma]: is a question I've had, that on the one hand, we see the BJP today taking Hindutva almost

03:03:33.960 --> 03:03:39.720
[Amit Varma]: to its logical sort of conclusion, where many of the things that they aimed for in that

03:03:39.720 --> 03:03:45.240
[Amit Varma]: period of time, like the building of temple and the abolition of 370 and all that is gradually

03:03:45.240 --> 03:03:50.040
[Amit Varma]: being achieved, but at the same time, there is, again, a trade off to be made between

03:03:50.040 --> 03:03:54.920
[Amit Varma]: pure ideology and the will to power, so to say, which Amit Shah exemplifies.

03:03:54.920 --> 03:03:59.940
[Amit Varma]: So on the one hand, you see this ideological purity, which is finding more expression.

03:03:59.940 --> 03:04:04.480
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, you also have a will to power where, for example, under Amit Shah,

03:04:04.480 --> 03:04:08.240
[Amit Varma]: they'll do what I would call in the political sphere, mergers and acquisitions, where they'll

03:04:08.240 --> 03:04:15.160
[Amit Varma]: buy 50 MPs from this party or, you know, co-op leaders from some other party, and all of

03:04:15.160 --> 03:04:16.160
[Amit Varma]: that.

03:04:16.160 --> 03:04:21.840
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, in this balance, in this trade off between politics and ideology, where,

03:04:21.840 --> 03:04:26.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, Vajpayee realized that you have to, you know, you can't go too far towards

03:04:26.480 --> 03:04:29.920
[Amit Varma]: ideology, politics has to reign supreme, you have to respond to the incentives and the

03:04:29.920 --> 03:04:34.480
[Amit Varma]: atmosphere of the time, which is why relative liberalizers of the 70s, like Balraj Madhok

03:04:34.480 --> 03:04:38.480
[Amit Varma]: and Subramanian Swamy were eventually sidelined.

03:04:38.480 --> 03:04:43.880
[Amit Varma]: But you know, if we look at the party today, for example, how do you view this trade off?

03:04:43.880 --> 03:04:52.000
[Amit Varma]: Does a party risk losing its soul, so to say, if it compromises too much for political purposes,

03:04:52.000 --> 03:04:55.240
[Amit Varma]: like we can look at parties like the Congress and all and say they have no soul at all,

03:04:55.240 --> 03:04:56.240
[Amit Varma]: so it doesn't really matter.

03:04:56.240 --> 03:05:03.280
[Amit Varma]: But the BJP is a firmly ideological party, and yet it is this will to power and the accumulated

03:05:03.280 --> 03:05:06.760
[Amit Varma]: organizational wisdom of a century that has got them to where they are today?

03:05:06.760 --> 03:05:09.280
[Guest]: Well, I mean, that's a deep question, right?

03:05:09.280 --> 03:05:13.680
[Guest]: And first up, I want to remind your listeners that, you know, I don't think anyone has read

03:05:13.680 --> 03:05:18.480
[Guest]: the book as carefully as Amit, but that doesn't mean you only hear this podcast and not buy

03:05:18.480 --> 03:05:19.480
[Guest]: the book.

03:05:19.480 --> 03:05:22.920
[Guest]: That's what I'm worried about, Amit, because you've read it so carefully that, you know,

03:05:22.920 --> 03:05:26.120
[Guest]: the reader may feel, you know, why should we buy the book, please buy the book, it's

03:05:26.120 --> 03:05:27.560
[Guest]: available on Amazon.

03:05:27.560 --> 03:05:32.880
[Guest]: No matter how closely and in detail Amit has read the book, it's not a substitute to buying

03:05:32.880 --> 03:05:33.880
[Guest]: the book.

03:05:33.880 --> 03:05:37.640
[Guest]: So I must put an advertisement, Amit, because, you know, you know everything about the book.

03:05:37.640 --> 03:05:38.640
[Amit Varma]: So I have to.

03:05:38.640 --> 03:05:44.040
[Amit Varma]: I second, I second that and in the sense I second your recommendation, and I have to

03:05:44.040 --> 03:05:48.240
[Amit Varma]: point out that my listeners, you know, there is a meme on Twitter where people have seen

03:05:48.240 --> 03:05:51.840
[Amit Varma]: in the unseen bookshelves with all the books I've bought because of my episodes.

03:05:51.840 --> 03:05:53.440
[Amit Varma]: So don't worry about that.

03:05:53.440 --> 03:05:56.280
[Amit Varma]: Everybody's going to go out and buy the beautiful book.

03:05:56.280 --> 03:05:57.280
[Amit Varma]: But let's let's.

03:05:57.280 --> 03:05:58.280
[Guest]: Thanks.

03:05:58.280 --> 03:05:59.280
[Guest]: Thanks, Amit.

03:05:59.280 --> 03:06:03.640
[Guest]: Well, so look, here's why the question you ask is deep, right, which is that at the heart

03:06:03.640 --> 03:06:08.440
[Guest]: of Hindu nationalism is, you know, you call it will to power and ideology, right?

03:06:08.440 --> 03:06:14.000
[Guest]: Let me call it it's a conventional party seating power, which is your will to power argument.

03:06:14.000 --> 03:06:19.920
[Guest]: And two is it's a, you know, it's an ideological movement radically seeking to reshape society.

03:06:19.920 --> 03:06:21.760
[Guest]: And there is this tension.

03:06:21.760 --> 03:06:24.600
[Guest]: And this tension is always on yin and yang.

03:06:24.600 --> 03:06:28.200
[Guest]: So I wouldn't say that there's a, you know, we discussed this earlier, there's no, you

03:06:28.200 --> 03:06:32.600
[Guest]: know, movement towards radicalism necessarily that, you know, the nature of India is always

03:06:32.600 --> 03:06:36.760
[Guest]: you are moderate Hindus, you are radical Hindus, you know, you have plenty of people who don't

03:06:36.760 --> 03:06:41.520
[Guest]: think of themselves as Hindus, that a political party that you know, wins enormously, the

03:06:41.520 --> 03:06:43.840
[Guest]: word enormous only means less than 50%.

03:06:43.840 --> 03:06:48.480
[Guest]: So I think the highest vote share any Prime Minister has got is Rajiv Gandhi in 1984 on

03:06:48.480 --> 03:06:53.280
[Guest]: the back of his mother's murder, and even he got less than one in two voters, right?

03:06:53.280 --> 03:06:58.360
[Guest]: So you always have some other party, you know, the opposition, you have adequate unity, then

03:06:58.360 --> 03:07:02.480
[Guest]: that puts the you know, BJP or the Congress on the back burner and then forces you to

03:07:02.480 --> 03:07:04.760
[Guest]: be moderate to try to get allies.

03:07:04.760 --> 03:07:10.600
[Guest]: So the dynamic that you talk about, right, is a yin and yang is an up and down, right?

03:07:10.600 --> 03:07:13.080
[Guest]: It's never moving towards one particular direction.

03:07:13.080 --> 03:07:17.920
[Guest]: To give you one just one example, when it came to the Citizenship Amendment Act, there's

03:07:17.920 --> 03:07:21.080
[Guest]: a reason I think that it was Amit Shah who presented it.

03:07:21.080 --> 03:07:24.840
[Guest]: And if my memory serves, and I think your listeners can check that Narendra Modi made

03:07:24.840 --> 03:07:29.040
[Guest]: sure that he wasn't in parliament, you know, because he wanted to, you know, it was so

03:07:29.040 --> 03:07:30.040
[Guest]: radical, right?

03:07:30.040 --> 03:07:34.200
[Guest]: And he was afraid what the press what the foreign press would say, that Modi wanted

03:07:34.200 --> 03:07:35.360
[Guest]: to appear moderate, right?

03:07:35.360 --> 03:07:39.760
[Guest]: Now, Modi is not more moderate than Amit Shah, they both are cut off the same cloth.

03:07:39.760 --> 03:07:46.080
[Guest]: But that that the point being that the ideology of Hindu nationalism itself needs this jugalbandi,

03:07:46.080 --> 03:07:47.080
[Guest]: right?

03:07:47.080 --> 03:07:50.200
[Guest]: Which is why right in the beginning, you see the jugalbandi of Shyam Prashad Mukherjee

03:07:50.200 --> 03:07:54.280
[Guest]: and Dindya Lopadia, you can call it moderate and hardline, but the other way you can see

03:07:54.280 --> 03:08:00.040
[Guest]: it is one cares about the ideology, the other cares about what you call will to power, right?

03:08:00.040 --> 03:08:05.080
[Guest]: It's true that the BJP under Modi is able to kind of break political parties, but the

03:08:05.080 --> 03:08:10.820
[Guest]: ability of Vajpayee to reach out to parties in return like AIDMK wanted very opportunistic

03:08:10.820 --> 03:08:13.960
[Guest]: things that that predates Amit Shah and Modi.

03:08:13.960 --> 03:08:18.600
[Guest]: So this is a I mean, it's a good question that you asked, because the answer to this

03:08:18.600 --> 03:08:21.200
[Guest]: puzzle is jugalbandi, right?

03:08:21.200 --> 03:08:26.960
[Guest]: That jugalbandi provides a team ethic of teamwork, where given that you have this inevitable

03:08:26.960 --> 03:08:32.120
[Guest]: yin and yang, this radical, this moderate, this hardline, you know, soft line, you need

03:08:32.120 --> 03:08:33.560
[Guest]: to stick it together.

03:08:33.560 --> 03:08:37.560
[Guest]: Because in many other parties, when this happens, Amit, you end up with a split.

03:08:37.560 --> 03:08:41.600
[Guest]: So the other party, for example, where this happens very often is the Communist Party,

03:08:41.600 --> 03:08:45.560
[Guest]: which is both a movement seeking to reshape society as well as, you know, at least after

03:08:45.560 --> 03:08:49.920
[Guest]: the 1950s, tactically a believer in bourgeois democracy.

03:08:49.920 --> 03:08:54.800
[Guest]: But and you did like have some kind of this dynamic, I think you had when Jyoti Basu was

03:08:54.800 --> 03:08:58.880
[Guest]: in his height of his power in Bengal, you had Jyoti Basu running the government and

03:08:58.880 --> 03:09:03.280
[Guest]: I think you had Pramod Das Gupta running the party, again, the same dynamic.

03:09:03.280 --> 03:09:08.360
[Guest]: But you know, while that jugalbandi stayed, the communists in general have been plagued

03:09:08.360 --> 03:09:09.800
[Guest]: by a lot of splits.

03:09:09.800 --> 03:09:13.000
[Guest]: The biggest split Amit is between overground and underground.

03:09:13.000 --> 03:09:17.040
[Guest]: So if you look at the Communist Party in India in Bihar at the moment, a lot of people were

03:09:17.040 --> 03:09:21.920
[Guest]: surprised that the Communist Party did unusually well in the in the results last month.

03:09:21.920 --> 03:09:24.080
[Guest]: But you know, it has a very old history in Bihar.

03:09:24.080 --> 03:09:30.920
[Guest]: In fact, I think it's produced Communist Party CPI MLAs from Patna itself, I think Dr. Sen.

03:09:30.920 --> 03:09:35.760
[Guest]: So it has a whole history, but it would have done even better if it had been able to solve

03:09:35.760 --> 03:09:41.280
[Guest]: this very dynamic that you identify in Hindu nationalism, when the underground and overground

03:09:41.280 --> 03:09:42.280
[Guest]: get together.

03:09:42.280 --> 03:09:47.920
[Guest]: Why did the CPI split into CPM and the CPM has split into the Maoists because they simply,

03:09:47.920 --> 03:09:50.120
[Guest]: you know, they could not accommodate the radicals.

03:09:50.120 --> 03:09:51.120
[Guest]: They just couldn't, right.

03:09:51.120 --> 03:09:54.600
[Guest]: And there the definition of radical is that you believe in taking up arms against the

03:09:54.600 --> 03:09:55.600
[Guest]: state.

03:09:55.600 --> 03:10:00.840
[Guest]: And I think it has hurt the communist movement hugely, you know, the splits and this constant

03:10:00.840 --> 03:10:04.480
[Guest]: anxiety about whether you should be underground or overground, I think the underground movement

03:10:04.480 --> 03:10:07.840
[Guest]: has given a bad name to the overground communists.

03:10:07.840 --> 03:10:14.160
[Guest]: So the dynamic that you talk about is not peculiar to the BJP, because it happens in

03:10:14.160 --> 03:10:16.520
[Guest]: many parties that are also movements.

03:10:16.520 --> 03:10:21.100
[Guest]: The solution to that problem is peculiar to the to the BJP.

03:10:21.100 --> 03:10:27.000
[Amit Varma]: So let's kind of move on to, you know, what is the big rupture, you know, in the politics

03:10:27.000 --> 03:10:31.080
[Amit Varma]: of the Hindu nationalist movement and a big rupture in Indian politics as well, which

03:10:31.080 --> 03:10:35.360
[Amit Varma]: is the emergency where, you know, so many opposition leaders get jailed.

03:10:35.360 --> 03:10:39.680
[Amit Varma]: And what you see during that time is that all of these parties, you know, from Jayprakash

03:10:39.680 --> 03:10:45.080
[Amit Varma]: Narayan on where he stands in the spectrum and Vajpayee and so on are like, let's leave

03:10:45.080 --> 03:10:46.080
[Amit Varma]: everything aside.

03:10:46.080 --> 03:10:47.080
[Amit Varma]: Let's just unite.

03:10:47.080 --> 03:10:49.680
[Amit Varma]: And it's pure will to power there more than ideology.

03:10:49.680 --> 03:10:53.020
[Amit Varma]: And they all come together and you point out about how after the emergency, when the coalition

03:10:53.020 --> 03:10:58.080
[Amit Varma]: wins power, you know, the Bharatiya Jan Sangh realizes that we have the most seats of all

03:10:58.080 --> 03:11:00.320
[Amit Varma]: the parties, but we won't make a bid for PM.

03:11:00.320 --> 03:11:04.040
[Amit Varma]: And there are, of course, three candidates, Murarji Desai, Charan Singh and Jagjivan Ram.

03:11:04.040 --> 03:11:10.400
[Amit Varma]: And again, it's sort of the strategic astuteness of Vajpayee that, you know, he supports Jagjivan

03:11:10.400 --> 03:11:15.160
[Amit Varma]: Ram because his thinking is Jagjivan Ram is a Harijan and therefore, this whole project

03:11:15.160 --> 03:11:20.640
[Amit Varma]: of expanding the Hindu vote to include, you know, all castes and so on will be helped

03:11:20.640 --> 03:11:22.520
[Amit Varma]: if Jagjivan Ram comes to power.

03:11:22.520 --> 03:11:26.640
[Amit Varma]: But the Janata experiment, as we know, kind of fails.

03:11:26.640 --> 03:11:31.000
[Amit Varma]: And after that, you know, Vajpayee and Advani form the Bharatiya Janata Party, which is

03:11:31.000 --> 03:11:33.560
[Amit Varma]: suddenly committed to Gandhian socialism.

03:11:33.560 --> 03:11:40.200
[Amit Varma]: And the vision seems entirely different from whatever it was before, to the extent that,

03:11:40.200 --> 03:11:45.400
[Amit Varma]: you know, they disassociate themselves from, you know, religious imagery and language and

03:11:45.400 --> 03:11:49.720
[Amit Varma]: rhetoric and all of that, to the point where the RSS stopped supporting them, you know.

03:11:49.720 --> 03:11:54.240
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, you could say Vajpayee makes that shift at exactly the wrong time when

03:11:54.240 --> 03:11:56.120
[Amit Varma]: the political winds are shifting.

03:11:56.120 --> 03:12:01.000
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about that period and why are Vajpayee and Advani going into

03:12:01.000 --> 03:12:05.800
[Amit Varma]: this interesting direction and, you know, what do the changing political winds then

03:12:05.800 --> 03:12:06.800
[Guest]: mean for them?

03:12:06.800 --> 03:12:11.800
[Guest]: Amit, the direction that Vajpayee chooses is driven by one thing, which is that where

03:12:11.800 --> 03:12:13.960
[Guest]: he thinks the voter is headed.

03:12:13.960 --> 03:12:20.520
[Guest]: Vajpayee's analysis of the 1970s in India is even though the Congress is in decline,

03:12:20.520 --> 03:12:25.000
[Guest]: Congressism or the Nehruvian consensus has not been rejected by the voter.

03:12:25.000 --> 03:12:30.800
[Guest]: So while the voter in 1977 rejects Indira Gandhi, they don't reject the larger principles

03:12:30.800 --> 03:12:33.720
[Guest]: on which the Nehruvian consensus is built.

03:12:33.720 --> 03:12:39.440
[Guest]: More importantly, even the anti-Indira political parties, the BLD, Jai Prakash Narayan, they

03:12:39.440 --> 03:12:41.960
[Guest]: don't fundamentally reject the Nehruvian consensus.

03:12:41.960 --> 03:12:46.000
[Guest]: What they don't like is the authoritarian figure of Indira Gandhi.

03:12:46.000 --> 03:12:51.240
[Guest]: And Vajpayee realizes that for the Jan Sangh to become mainstream, there is no other, this

03:12:51.240 --> 03:12:52.880
[Guest]: is the only opposition in town.

03:12:52.880 --> 03:12:56.200
[Guest]: So if you want to take down the Congress, which is the hundred pound gorilla in the

03:12:56.200 --> 03:13:04.240
[Guest]: room, you have to merge yourself into a non-Congress opposition, which actually shares many of

03:13:04.240 --> 03:13:08.840
[Guest]: the precepts of the Nehruvian consensus, which is what he's able to do.

03:13:08.840 --> 03:13:14.960
[Guest]: And as you pointed out, Jan Sangh is the largest constituent of the Janata party in the 77

03:13:14.960 --> 03:13:15.960
[Guest]: elections.

03:13:15.960 --> 03:13:20.000
[Guest]: So logically, Vajpayee should have been prime minister, but they don't even begin to ask

03:13:20.000 --> 03:13:24.040
[Guest]: that question because they're like, look, we're grateful that we're part of you.

03:13:24.040 --> 03:13:26.960
[Guest]: You know, that's not even, let's not ask for more than we can get.

03:13:26.960 --> 03:13:34.360
[Guest]: And that again shows a certain sagacity and a certain ability to avoid the immediate greed

03:13:34.360 --> 03:13:35.360
[Guest]: of power.

03:13:35.360 --> 03:13:36.360
[Guest]: They're interested in the long game.

03:13:36.360 --> 03:13:37.360
[Guest]: They are marathon runners.

03:13:37.360 --> 03:13:39.760
[Guest]: They are not hundred meter runners.

03:13:39.760 --> 03:13:41.680
[Guest]: And I think that's something quite remarkable.

03:13:41.680 --> 03:13:45.200
[Guest]: And the other aspect that you pointed out, which is that not just Vajpayee, but even

03:13:45.200 --> 03:13:47.000
[Guest]: the RSS wanted Jagjivan Ram.

03:13:47.000 --> 03:13:49.160
[Guest]: Jagjivan Ram, by the way, is a complex figure.

03:13:49.160 --> 03:13:52.960
[Guest]: I mean, his father was a priest, you know, he knew Sanskrit.

03:13:52.960 --> 03:13:56.160
[Guest]: So he was scheduled caste, but he was highly Sanskritized.

03:13:56.160 --> 03:14:01.000
[Guest]: But they wanted the symbolism of a Dalit prime minister, India's first, and I think only

03:14:01.000 --> 03:14:04.840
[Guest]: Dalit prime minister would have come through because the Jan Sangh wanted him.

03:14:04.840 --> 03:14:08.200
[Guest]: And that was stymied by other parties, namely Charan Singh.

03:14:08.200 --> 03:14:11.680
[Guest]: But again, it tells you something about the party, right?

03:14:11.680 --> 03:14:16.880
[Guest]: While they are in power between 1977 and 80, they don't go outside the Nehruvian consensus.

03:14:16.880 --> 03:14:21.400
[Guest]: This is more classically the case when it comes to foreign policy that Vajpayee continues

03:14:21.400 --> 03:14:24.920
[Guest]: to follow the non-aligned movement in some sense.

03:14:24.920 --> 03:14:26.800
[Guest]: So they are very, very careful.

03:14:26.800 --> 03:14:31.720
[Guest]: And I think that again, that shows a certain ability to sort of run the long distance rather

03:14:31.720 --> 03:14:33.680
[Guest]: than short distance.

03:14:33.680 --> 03:14:37.480
[Unknown]: The problem again, not for India, which I leave your listeners to decide what is in

03:14:37.480 --> 03:14:38.480
[Guest]: India's interest.

03:14:38.480 --> 03:14:45.240
[Guest]: But the problem for Hindu nationalism is that this analysis that Vajpayee has of the Indian

03:14:45.240 --> 03:14:50.400
[Guest]: voter in the 70s, he carries over to the 80s, but a lot of changes are happening in the

03:14:50.400 --> 03:14:51.400
[Guest]: 80s.

03:14:51.400 --> 03:14:54.000
[Guest]: There's the breakdown of the Congress system.

03:14:54.000 --> 03:14:58.040
[Guest]: There's Hindu anxiety because of the Khalistan movement, which is targeting Hindus of all

03:14:58.040 --> 03:14:59.040
[Guest]: castes.

03:14:59.040 --> 03:15:04.200
[Guest]: There's an anxiety among upper caste Hindus in North India, for example, Gujarat, where

03:15:04.200 --> 03:15:06.840
[Guest]: there is an increase in OBC reservations.

03:15:06.840 --> 03:15:12.240
[Guest]: And there's a sense that Saudi petrodollars is expanding conversions of lower caste Hindus

03:15:12.240 --> 03:15:13.240
[Guest]: into Muslims.

03:15:13.240 --> 03:15:14.240
[Guest]: So there's a sense of anxiety.

03:15:14.240 --> 03:15:18.760
[Guest]: And again, not my job to judge whether it's a valid anxiety or not, but there is an anxiety

03:15:18.760 --> 03:15:20.440
[Guest]: and it's demand drawn.

03:15:20.440 --> 03:15:24.960
[Guest]: Now at precisely this time, Vajpayee, who one of the core arguments I make in this book

03:15:24.960 --> 03:15:26.760
[Guest]: is he's not a mass politician.

03:15:26.760 --> 03:15:28.320
[Guest]: He has his year to parliament.

03:15:28.320 --> 03:15:29.760
[Guest]: He doesn't have his year to the ground.

03:15:29.760 --> 03:15:33.480
[Guest]: And there's a difference between the two, because changes in the ground may take a little

03:15:33.480 --> 03:15:35.280
[Guest]: while to percolate to parliament.

03:15:35.280 --> 03:15:36.280
[Guest]: It's not immediate.

03:15:36.280 --> 03:15:39.880
[Guest]: Whereas I think someone like Indira Gandhi and Narendra Modi have a direct connect with

03:15:39.880 --> 03:15:40.880
[Guest]: the voters.

03:15:40.880 --> 03:15:42.160
[Guest]: So Vajpayee doesn't get it.

03:15:42.160 --> 03:15:47.760
[Guest]: So even in the early 80s, when the Bharatiya Janata Party is created in 1980, he actually

03:15:47.760 --> 03:15:51.640
[Guest]: wants it to be a continuation of Jayaprakash Narayan's vision.

03:15:51.640 --> 03:15:57.000
[Guest]: Hence, even the name, I think the most important relic of the Janata experiment that remains

03:15:57.000 --> 03:15:59.200
[Guest]: today is the name Bharatiya Janata Party.

03:15:59.200 --> 03:16:03.400
[Guest]: It's the same name, he just put Bharatiya in front of it.

03:16:03.400 --> 03:16:07.600
[Guest]: He made sure that there was a prominent Muslim leader, Sikandar Bhakta.

03:16:07.600 --> 03:16:11.680
[Guest]: He said very clearly that we don't follow, we won't follow Hindu nationalist ideology.

03:16:11.680 --> 03:16:14.960
[Guest]: We will follow Jayaprakash Narayan's ideology.

03:16:14.960 --> 03:16:20.040
[Guest]: What we will do is we follow Hindu nationalist discipline, because what he felt the Janata

03:16:20.040 --> 03:16:22.600
[Guest]: experiment lacked was just discipline and teamwork.

03:16:22.600 --> 03:16:27.400
[Guest]: So he wanted to take Hindu nationalist teamwork with Jayaprakash's ideology.

03:16:27.400 --> 03:16:31.160
[Guest]: And as I point out, you know, in the early 1980s, he's exactly wrong.

03:16:31.160 --> 03:16:36.520
[Guest]: Again, it's not anxiety that is created by the RSS or VHP, but the RSS and VHP see this

03:16:36.520 --> 03:16:40.880
[Guest]: and they see that the party of the Hindus, the BJP is actually turning left, is turning

03:16:40.880 --> 03:16:41.880
[Guest]: secular.

03:16:41.880 --> 03:16:46.840
[Guest]: So they then activate this Hindu anxiety even more and Indira Gandhi, who's a far better

03:16:46.840 --> 03:16:52.040
[Guest]: politician in that sense than Vajpayee, as a mass level, sees this Hindu anxiety.

03:16:52.040 --> 03:16:53.440
[Guest]: She plays to it.

03:16:53.440 --> 03:16:56.800
[Guest]: She goes to temples, she wears saffron saris.

03:16:56.800 --> 03:17:01.080
[Guest]: In the, I think 1982 or 83, there are elections in Jammu and Kashmir.

03:17:01.080 --> 03:17:06.840
[Guest]: And as your listeners know, Jammu has a lot of Hindus and the valley is exclusively Muslim.

03:17:06.840 --> 03:17:10.800
[Guest]: So she campaigns for the Hindu votes in the, and I mean Indira Gandhi, campaigns for the

03:17:10.800 --> 03:17:16.360
[Guest]: Hindu vote in Jammu in that election, using the bogey of national conference, Farooq Abdullah

03:17:16.360 --> 03:17:19.600
[Guest]: and the valley's Muslims, right?

03:17:19.600 --> 03:17:25.240
[Guest]: And she portrays herself as, you know, goddess Durga committed to keeping India united against

03:17:25.240 --> 03:17:29.840
[Guest]: the Khalistan movement and even gives her life for the movement, the RSS notices.

03:17:29.840 --> 03:17:35.320
[Guest]: And so in the 1984 elections held immediately after Indira Gandhi's murder, the RSS actually

03:17:35.320 --> 03:17:42.480
[Guest]: campaigns and votes for Rajiv Gandhi because, and I quote an RSS essay in their mouthpiece

03:17:42.480 --> 03:17:47.000
[Guest]: organizer just after the election saying that, look, Rajiv won because he was the Hindu party

03:17:47.000 --> 03:17:50.120
[Guest]: and Vajpayee lost because he was not the Hindu party.

03:17:50.120 --> 03:17:54.680
[Guest]: And that begins Vajpayee's long exile from the BJP beginning in 1986, all the way to

03:17:54.680 --> 03:17:55.680
[Guest]: 1995.

03:17:55.680 --> 03:18:00.880
[Guest]: So to answer your question, I think Vajpayee's analysis of where India was heading in the

03:18:00.880 --> 03:18:03.120
[Guest]: 1970s was right.

03:18:03.120 --> 03:18:05.760
[Guest]: Someone like Balraj Madhok was wrong in this regard.

03:18:05.760 --> 03:18:10.480
[Guest]: I don't think the Jansangh would have survived in the seventies by being the party of capitalism,

03:18:10.480 --> 03:18:12.840
[Guest]: much as many of your listeners would have preferred that.

03:18:12.840 --> 03:18:16.320
[Guest]: I just don't think the political mood was, was for that.

03:18:16.320 --> 03:18:20.120
[Guest]: And the eighties on the other hand, Vajpayee read it completely wrong and Advani read it

03:18:20.120 --> 03:18:23.120
[Guest]: better because he had his ear closer to the card.

03:18:23.120 --> 03:18:27.720
[Guest]: So Advani, I show him, you know, facing the biggest test of loyalty in his life because

03:18:27.720 --> 03:18:33.220
[Guest]: he doesn't want to reject Vajpayee the person, but he has to reject Vajpayee the ideology

03:18:33.220 --> 03:18:34.480
[Guest]: and he does it.

03:18:34.480 --> 03:18:38.840
[Guest]: And what is remarkable about the BJP is that this happens without a split to the party

03:18:38.840 --> 03:18:42.720
[Guest]: in any other party, Amit, this would have resulted in a split.

03:18:42.720 --> 03:18:48.000
[Amit Varma]: No, and I was struck by, you know, the words of the RSS where they called the 1984 elections

03:18:48.000 --> 03:18:54.340
[Amit Varma]: as a quote, massive Hindu mandate, end quote for Rajiv Gandhi, which is very telling.

03:18:54.340 --> 03:18:59.440
[Amit Varma]: And you talk about how that big growing Hindu vote bank between 1980 and 1984 just goes

03:18:59.440 --> 03:19:00.440
[Amit Varma]: for the Congress.

03:19:00.440 --> 03:19:07.080
[Amit Varma]: And, and you sort of point out another very sort of interesting meeting after that, where,

03:19:07.080 --> 03:19:09.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, the RSS is trying to figure out what do we do?

03:19:09.320 --> 03:19:12.600
[Amit Varma]: And obviously the BJP needs a new leader and all of that.

03:19:12.600 --> 03:19:17.800
[Amit Varma]: And they have, of course, revived the Vishwa Hindu Parishad as a sort of, you know, a counterpoint

03:19:17.800 --> 03:19:20.640
[Amit Varma]: to take the, you know, the hardline view forward.

03:19:20.640 --> 03:19:23.680
[Amit Varma]: But then they decide that Vajpayee has to go and you described this fascinating meeting.

03:19:23.680 --> 03:19:29.080
[Unknown]: I think it's in Gandhinagar, where the young Amit Shah has to, I think, grind paan for

03:19:29.080 --> 03:19:30.080
[Unknown]: Vijay Rajesh.

03:19:30.080 --> 03:19:31.080
[Amit Varma]: Beetle nut.

03:19:31.080 --> 03:19:34.600
[Amit Varma]: He has to grind beetle nut for Vijay Rajesh India, who's sitting in a room with Atal and

03:19:34.600 --> 03:19:40.760
[Amit Varma]: at one point where he's handing over the beetle nut, you know, that this message comes from

03:19:40.760 --> 03:19:44.680
[Amit Varma]: the RSS that Vajpayee has to step down and Vijay Rajesh has to take over.

03:19:44.680 --> 03:19:46.880
[Amit Varma]: And Vijay Rajesh, again, a very interesting figure.

03:19:46.880 --> 03:19:52.320
[Amit Varma]: I was, I wish you'd written more about her where she just doesn't want power.

03:19:52.320 --> 03:19:56.640
[Amit Varma]: She's an incredible patron, practically funds a party single-handedly for a long time, but

03:19:56.640 --> 03:20:00.720
[Amit Varma]: just doesn't want the spoils of power and she doesn't want to hurt Vajpayee.

03:20:00.720 --> 03:20:03.720
[Amit Varma]: So eventually she doesn't take it and it goes to Advani.

03:20:03.720 --> 03:20:07.740
[Amit Varma]: Now, tell me a little bit about how that shift happens.

03:20:07.740 --> 03:20:10.960
[Amit Varma]: Does it affect the personal relationship between the two men?

03:20:10.960 --> 03:20:14.800
[Amit Varma]: Does Vajpayee completely withdraw or is he a humble party servant?

03:20:14.800 --> 03:20:21.020
[Amit Varma]: And what's happening in the next few years as far as the Hindu vote is concerned?

03:20:21.020 --> 03:20:25.680
[Amit Varma]: Because those are tumultuous years for Indian politics, say, you know, leading to VP Singh

03:20:25.680 --> 03:20:26.680
[Amit Varma]: coming to power.

03:20:26.680 --> 03:20:30.160
[Amit Varma]: And of course, we'll, you know, discuss that phase in Ayodhya right after this.

03:20:30.160 --> 03:20:34.060
[Amit Varma]: But in that period, the second half of the 80s, what's the dynamic there?

03:20:34.060 --> 03:20:35.060
[Amit Varma]: What is going on?

03:20:35.060 --> 03:20:37.920
[Amit Varma]: Ramayana and Mahabharata also become really popular at that time.

03:20:37.920 --> 03:20:41.280
[Amit Varma]: Give me a sort of a picture of what the party is going through in that period.

03:20:41.280 --> 03:20:47.440
[Guest]: Well, I mean, for those of your listeners who are strong critics of the BJP and who

03:20:47.440 --> 03:20:52.480
[Guest]: are supporters of the Congress, or rather who see the Congress party as the only quote

03:20:52.480 --> 03:20:59.640
[Guest]: unquote secular possible opposition to the BJP, if you're that kind of person, I think

03:20:59.640 --> 03:21:03.520
[Guest]: you would agree with me that Rajiv Gandhi was absolutely the worst thing that should

03:21:03.520 --> 03:21:05.800
[Guest]: have happened during that period.

03:21:05.800 --> 03:21:11.160
[Guest]: Because and here's a tragedy, you know, he came across as Mr. Clean, the kind of euphoria

03:21:11.160 --> 03:21:16.240
[Guest]: that greets Rajiv Gandhi when he becomes prime minister in late 1984, you know, he's seen

03:21:16.240 --> 03:21:21.320
[Guest]: as it's very similar to, you know, the John F. Kennedy mania in the United States of the

03:21:21.320 --> 03:21:22.320
[Guest]: 1960s.

03:21:22.320 --> 03:21:23.320
[Guest]: He could do no wrong.

03:21:23.320 --> 03:21:28.160
[Guest]: He, you know, he's a modernizer, unlike his brother, younger brother, Sanjay, he kept

03:21:28.160 --> 03:21:29.400
[Guest]: away from politics.

03:21:29.400 --> 03:21:31.120
[Guest]: So he was seen as clean.

03:21:31.120 --> 03:21:32.600
[Guest]: He was seen as a reluctant man.

03:21:32.600 --> 03:21:37.600
[Guest]: A lot of the people who surrounded him were, you know, people from school who had private

03:21:37.600 --> 03:21:39.100
[Guest]: sector education.

03:21:39.100 --> 03:21:42.840
[Guest]: So there was a thrill that went in India, especially the middle class, that he was the

03:21:42.840 --> 03:21:44.680
[Guest]: right man at the right time.

03:21:44.680 --> 03:21:47.640
[Guest]: He actually turned out to be the wrong man in the wrong time because his extraordinary

03:21:47.640 --> 03:21:53.000
[Guest]: inexperience meant that his counter to this Hindu anxiety was to pander it.

03:21:53.000 --> 03:21:58.160
[Guest]: It wasn't to tamp it down the way Mahatma Gandhi had done, which is you see Hindu anxiety

03:21:58.160 --> 03:22:01.520
[Guest]: in the 20s and the 40s, but you actually, that's the leader, right?

03:22:01.520 --> 03:22:03.960
[Guest]: You see anxiety and you calm your people down.

03:22:03.960 --> 03:22:05.360
[Guest]: He exaggerates it.

03:22:05.360 --> 03:22:10.660
[Guest]: So he opens the locks for Babri Masjid for prayer in 1986, I think.

03:22:10.660 --> 03:22:18.000
[Guest]: And then in 1989, he, I think 1985 or 1986 for prayer.

03:22:18.000 --> 03:22:24.160
[Guest]: And in 1989, he opens, he allows Shilanyas or bricklaying ceremony in Ayodhya.

03:22:24.160 --> 03:22:29.240
[Guest]: And it's not a coincidence, Amit, that recently after the new temple was inaugurated in Ayodhya,

03:22:29.240 --> 03:22:33.160
[Guest]: I think it was the Madhya Pradesh Congress, which ran an advertisement saying that actually

03:22:33.160 --> 03:22:34.900
[Guest]: it was Rajiv Gandhi who did it.

03:22:34.900 --> 03:22:39.600
[Guest]: So if you buy the rhetoric that the BJP is a communal party, Rajiv Gandhi got there first,

03:22:39.600 --> 03:22:40.600
[Guest]: you know.

03:22:40.600 --> 03:22:46.600
[Guest]: And then he sort of, he did a jugalbandi of this, you know, Hindu communalism with Muslim

03:22:46.600 --> 03:22:47.600
[Guest]: communalism.

03:22:47.600 --> 03:22:52.720
[Guest]: He was, India, I think was the first country under Rajiv Gandhi to ban the satanic verses.

03:22:52.720 --> 03:22:58.640
[Guest]: He annulls the Supreme Court judgment when it comes to Shabanu by passing a law and,

03:22:58.640 --> 03:23:02.820
[Guest]: you know, which did the exact opposite of protecting Muslim women.

03:23:02.820 --> 03:23:10.520
[Guest]: So here was a man who sees these various Hindu and Muslim anxieties not of his making, responds

03:23:10.520 --> 03:23:15.520
[Guest]: not with high-minded liberalism, but pandering of the worst kind, you know, absolutely worst

03:23:15.520 --> 03:23:16.520
[Guest]: kind.

03:23:16.520 --> 03:23:22.280
[Guest]: And that is the box or the hole that the new party president, Lal Krishna Advani finds

03:23:22.280 --> 03:23:27.620
[Guest]: himself in, in 1986, that you have Hindu anxiety, but actually that Hindu anxiety is being sought

03:23:27.620 --> 03:23:30.480
[Guest]: to be monopolized by the Congress party.

03:23:30.480 --> 03:23:35.640
[Guest]: And if he doesn't move to the right of the Congress party, you know, he risks a repetition

03:23:35.640 --> 03:23:42.240
[Guest]: of the 1984 results where the Congress gets all the Hindu votes and that, it is this kind

03:23:42.240 --> 03:23:49.280
[Guest]: of context, Amit, in which the Lal Krishna Advani finally accepts the Ayodhya movement.

03:23:49.280 --> 03:23:54.480
[Guest]: The Ayodhya movement began by the RSS, BHP and I hope your listeners are listening to

03:23:54.480 --> 03:24:01.200
[Guest]: this two congressmen on stage in 1983 for the Ayodhya movement and very soon Rajiv Gandhi

03:24:01.200 --> 03:24:02.200
[Guest]: adopts it.

03:24:02.200 --> 03:24:07.080
[Guest]: It takes to 1989 for the BJP to adopt it under Lal Krishna Advani.

03:24:07.080 --> 03:24:11.360
[Guest]: And as I point out, you know, he gets on the Rath Yatra, it's an opportunistic reaction

03:24:11.360 --> 03:24:16.400
[Guest]: to the Mandal commission recommendations being implemented.

03:24:16.400 --> 03:24:22.800
[Guest]: And in many ways, the book argues that Advani's about right turn was actually a signal to

03:24:22.800 --> 03:24:28.240
[Guest]: his own cadre and his own movement that the BJP doesn't want to get left behind.

03:24:28.240 --> 03:24:32.680
[Guest]: And all through this period, Vajpayee feels that what Advani is doing is wrong.

03:24:32.680 --> 03:24:35.560
[Guest]: He feels that religion and politics shouldn't mix.

03:24:35.560 --> 03:24:39.800
[Guest]: And Amit, you had asked me this question earlier that, you know, which is the real Vajpayee?

03:24:39.800 --> 03:24:42.560
[Guest]: Is he, you know, is he the liberal or is he really wearing a mask?

03:24:42.560 --> 03:24:46.760
[Guest]: It's hard to say because at that time, his anger is quite genuine.

03:24:46.760 --> 03:24:49.640
[Guest]: He feels this is absolutely the wrong way to go.

03:24:49.640 --> 03:24:53.600
[Guest]: And in fact, he tells Advani that the problem with riding a tiger is that you can never

03:24:53.600 --> 03:24:54.680
[Guest]: get off.

03:24:54.680 --> 03:24:57.040
[Guest]: And I think he genuinely believes that.

03:24:57.040 --> 03:25:01.800
[Guest]: At the same time, I think Vajpayee is being ignored by the party.

03:25:01.800 --> 03:25:06.200
[Guest]: He travels on his own quite a bit in India, but most of the time he's spending time in

03:25:06.200 --> 03:25:12.760
[Guest]: the US with his, you know, or he's in his house in Delhi and he has a little bit of

03:25:12.760 --> 03:25:16.160
[Guest]: Kothari and they're eating, as I point out in the book, prawn curry, a little bit of

03:25:16.160 --> 03:25:17.160
[Guest]: whiskey.

03:25:17.160 --> 03:25:21.000
[Guest]: Vajpayee loved opium or Bhang pakodas.

03:25:21.000 --> 03:25:23.560
[Guest]: And you know, so this is the loser's quote.

03:25:23.560 --> 03:25:27.520
[Guest]: So Vajpayee is being sidelined and these are the people around him.

03:25:27.520 --> 03:25:29.760
[Guest]: People like Rajesh Mishra, Jaswant Singh.

03:25:29.760 --> 03:25:35.000
[Guest]: And the thing is that once Vajpayee comes to power in 96 and then 98, he doesn't forget

03:25:35.000 --> 03:25:38.520
[Guest]: these people because they stood with him when nobody else was standing.

03:25:38.520 --> 03:25:43.880
[Guest]: Now Advani is not invited to these sorries because he doesn't drink, he doesn't eat meat

03:25:43.880 --> 03:25:45.320
[Guest]: and he doesn't, you know, he doesn't gossip.

03:25:45.320 --> 03:25:47.000
[Guest]: He doesn't do that kind of thing.

03:25:47.000 --> 03:25:51.360
[Guest]: On the other hand, relations between the two, I think both make a huge effort to keep it

03:25:51.360 --> 03:25:52.360
[Guest]: going.

03:25:52.360 --> 03:25:54.640
[Guest]: So from Advani's side, I think it's loyalty.

03:25:54.640 --> 03:25:58.840
[Guest]: From Vajpayee's side, it's a recognition that his sidelining in the party is not because

03:25:58.840 --> 03:25:59.840
[Guest]: of Advani.

03:25:59.840 --> 03:26:02.680
[Guest]: It's because the party itself is going in a different direction.

03:26:02.680 --> 03:26:07.560
[Guest]: And Advani is his one insurance, then when things change, then Vajpayee is back in business.

03:26:07.560 --> 03:26:10.160
[Guest]: I also think, you know, I don't want to portray Vajpayee as too cynical.

03:26:10.160 --> 03:26:11.960
[Guest]: I also think he liked Advani.

03:26:11.960 --> 03:26:17.200
[Guest]: So while the professional relationship between them is ruptured, the personal relationship

03:26:17.200 --> 03:26:19.400
[Guest]: somehow manages during this period.

03:26:19.400 --> 03:26:26.240
[Amit Varma]: No, and I can't underscore the point you made earlier about the Congress's alleged secularism,

03:26:26.240 --> 03:26:29.960
[Amit Varma]: which you know, the BJP themselves used to use the term pseudo secularism, which was

03:26:29.960 --> 03:26:33.680
[Amit Varma]: very interesting because if you're against pseudo secularism, one would assume you're

03:26:33.680 --> 03:26:36.920
[Amit Varma]: against a pseudo part of it and therefore you don't mind secularism.

03:26:36.920 --> 03:26:39.800
[Amit Varma]: But they were against both pseudo secularism and secularism.

03:26:39.800 --> 03:26:42.960
[Amit Varma]: But you know, the point to underscore and what I feel strongly about is that the Congress

03:26:42.960 --> 03:26:45.880
[Amit Varma]: today on the ground is the party of Kamal Nath.

03:26:45.880 --> 03:26:49.400
[Amit Varma]: To call it a non-communal party is just a joke.

03:26:49.400 --> 03:26:54.240
[Amit Varma]: They've always been quoting the Hindu vote, which they continue to do today.

03:26:54.240 --> 03:26:59.280
[Amit Varma]: And for all of Rahul Gandhi's woke posturing on Twitter, the bottom line is that he has

03:26:59.280 --> 03:27:04.400
[Amit Varma]: never actually come to, you know, spoken about the horrors of the past or, you know, tried

03:27:04.400 --> 03:27:08.200
[Amit Varma]: to come to terms with them, not just what his father did, but also what his grandmother

03:27:08.200 --> 03:27:09.200
[Amit Varma]: Indira Gandhi did.

03:27:09.200 --> 03:27:13.080
[Amit Varma]: And I think for everything wrong that Modi has done, and he's a horrendous, horrendous

03:27:13.080 --> 03:27:16.440
[Amit Varma]: prime minister, and this is just my opinion, of course, I think Indira was worse.

03:27:16.440 --> 03:27:21.320
[Amit Varma]: Indira was just a moral monster for the kind of things that she did, which is why it's

03:27:21.320 --> 03:27:25.800
[Amit Varma]: difficult to take the Congress party seriously, as long as they have portraits of Indira Gandhi

03:27:25.800 --> 03:27:26.800
[Amit Varma]: on the wall.

03:27:26.800 --> 03:27:27.800
[Guest]: But that sort of...

03:27:27.800 --> 03:27:30.440
[Guest]: Can I interrupt you, if you don't mind?

03:27:30.440 --> 03:27:31.440
[Guest]: Sure.

03:27:31.440 --> 03:27:33.720
[Guest]: Look, I'm just being descriptive, right?

03:27:33.720 --> 03:27:34.720
[Amit Varma]: I know.

03:27:34.720 --> 03:27:38.840
[Guest]: So because I have views, I have pretty strong views and, you know, if you read my book,

03:27:38.840 --> 03:27:42.520
[Guest]: I mean, you know, I think you know that we agree on many things more than we disagree,

03:27:42.520 --> 03:27:43.960
[Guest]: but that's not the point here.

03:27:43.960 --> 03:27:50.640
[Guest]: I'm much more sympathetic about Indira Gandhi as a stunningly good politician.

03:27:50.640 --> 03:27:55.080
[Guest]: Whatever else you can say about her moral feelings, she was a very good politician.

03:27:55.080 --> 03:27:58.120
[Guest]: Her son was a bumbling politician.

03:27:58.120 --> 03:27:59.120
[Guest]: His sin is incompetence.

03:27:59.120 --> 03:28:03.520
[Guest]: It was, you know, he was a pilot who didn't have a heart in this and, you know, and he

03:28:03.520 --> 03:28:07.960
[Guest]: was confronting India, these massive crises in India, and he was just clueless despite

03:28:07.960 --> 03:28:09.360
[Guest]: having this mandate.

03:28:09.360 --> 03:28:11.400
[Guest]: I think that's a much worse sin, right?

03:28:11.400 --> 03:28:14.840
[Guest]: Or whatever, I leave your listeners to ask that question.

03:28:14.840 --> 03:28:20.320
[Guest]: And in that, I think Rahul Gandhi, you know, reminds me a lot more of his father rather

03:28:20.320 --> 03:28:24.320
[Guest]: than his grandmother, because, you know, from all accounts, he's a, you know, personally

03:28:24.320 --> 03:28:25.320
[Guest]: polite person.

03:28:25.320 --> 03:28:26.320
[Guest]: He's personally charming.

03:28:26.320 --> 03:28:30.920
[Guest]: You know, he's well brought up, but he's just, you know, for the kind of changes that is

03:28:30.920 --> 03:28:35.600
[Guest]: going on in India, he could not be, you know, worse place to deal with.

03:28:35.600 --> 03:28:38.800
[Guest]: And that definitely reminds me of Rajiv Gandhi during that period.

03:28:38.800 --> 03:28:44.240
[Amit Varma]: No, the reason I partly called Indira Gandhi a moral monster is includes what you just

03:28:44.240 --> 03:28:48.400
[Amit Varma]: said about her incredible politics, because she was such an incredible politician.

03:28:48.400 --> 03:28:53.760
[Amit Varma]: She took decisions and took the country in directions, which were going to be disastrous

03:28:53.760 --> 03:28:57.200
[Amit Varma]: for the people and were horrible in terms of governance, and she didn't give a damn

03:28:57.200 --> 03:28:58.200
[Amit Varma]: about that.

03:28:58.200 --> 03:28:59.200
[Amit Varma]: That wasn't even a factor.

03:28:59.200 --> 03:29:03.960
[Amit Varma]: Her only factor, much as in fact, it is for the current dispensation, is that how do I

03:29:03.960 --> 03:29:10.280
[Amit Varma]: craft the narrative to win elections, governance, you know, and in that sense, when, you know,

03:29:10.280 --> 03:29:14.200
[Amit Varma]: Narendra Modi did demonetization, which I call the largest assault on property rights

03:29:14.200 --> 03:29:15.200
[Amit Varma]: in human history.

03:29:15.200 --> 03:29:19.320
[Amit Varma]: The moment I heard about that measure, I thought, oh, this is, you know, just the kind of thing

03:29:19.320 --> 03:29:24.000
[Amit Varma]: Indira Gandhi would do, you know, just thinking of narrative and not giving a damn about what

03:29:24.000 --> 03:29:25.520
[Amit Varma]: actually happens on the ground.

03:29:25.520 --> 03:29:29.480
[Amit Varma]: But that aside, and I must point out to my listeners that this is me giving my opinion.

03:29:29.480 --> 03:29:32.360
[Amit Varma]: And you know, none of this is in the book.

03:29:32.360 --> 03:29:33.360
[Amit Varma]: None of this is in the book.

03:29:33.360 --> 03:29:34.640
[Amit Varma]: This is just me giving my opinion.

03:29:34.640 --> 03:29:39.720
[Amit Varma]: Vinay's book is only about facts and in that sense is incredibly rigorous.

03:29:39.720 --> 03:29:44.880
[Amit Varma]: Now, let's talk about that period after Rajiv Gandhi comes out of power.

03:29:44.880 --> 03:29:49.800
[Amit Varma]: Now, we already spoke earlier in the episode about what is happening when, you know, V.P.

03:29:49.800 --> 03:29:50.800
[Amit Varma]: Singh is in power.

03:29:50.800 --> 03:29:52.320
[Amit Varma]: Devi Lal is doing his little thing there.

03:29:52.320 --> 03:29:53.320
[Amit Varma]: V.P.

03:29:53.320 --> 03:29:54.440
[Amit Varma]: Singh feels insecure about that.

03:29:54.440 --> 03:29:55.440
[Amit Varma]: So he does Mandal.

03:29:55.440 --> 03:29:56.440
[Amit Varma]: Now, L.K.

03:29:56.440 --> 03:30:01.000
[Amit Varma]: Advani, who is, you know, in charge of BJP is now in a spot, how do I react to Mandal?

03:30:01.000 --> 03:30:05.240
[Amit Varma]: There are all these pressures and this could divide sort of the Hindu vote.

03:30:05.240 --> 03:30:06.800
[Amit Varma]: But I need to bring it together for me.

03:30:06.800 --> 03:30:07.800
[Amit Varma]: What do I do?

03:30:07.800 --> 03:30:08.800
[Amit Varma]: Oh, there's Ayodhya.

03:30:08.800 --> 03:30:10.600
[Amit Varma]: Let's do a Rath Yatra.

03:30:10.600 --> 03:30:15.120
[Amit Varma]: And you speak about, you know, Atal Bihari, Vajpayee, in fact, you quote him as saying,

03:30:15.120 --> 03:30:19.120
[Amit Varma]: quote, the difficulty of the Rath, once you ride it, you do not feel like getting down

03:30:19.120 --> 03:30:20.120
[Amit Varma]: from it.

03:30:20.120 --> 03:30:21.120
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

03:30:21.120 --> 03:30:22.120
[Amit Varma]: And at another point, he asked L.K.

03:30:22.120 --> 03:30:23.120
[Amit Varma]: Advani that don't do this.

03:30:23.120 --> 03:30:27.600
[Amit Varma]: He says, you know, quote, you're riding a tiger, stop quote, which is really interesting to

03:30:27.600 --> 03:30:28.600
[Amit Varma]: me.

03:30:28.600 --> 03:30:35.480
[Amit Varma]: I want to sort of point out that this changes Advani in a kind of fundamental ways, as I

03:30:35.480 --> 03:30:39.840
[Amit Varma]: think Swapan Dasgupta remarked that the Rath Yatra changes him in fundamental ways, almost

03:30:39.840 --> 03:30:44.880
[Amit Varma]: as if he has taken this direction and the Mukhota becomes a person, so to say, the mask

03:30:44.880 --> 03:30:45.880
[Amit Varma]: becomes a person.

03:30:45.880 --> 03:30:50.920
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about this phase of time leading up to Ayodhya and one of the

03:30:50.920 --> 03:30:54.840
[Amit Varma]: sort of, you know, when you go deep into that, when you go deep into the nuances of what

03:30:54.840 --> 03:31:01.400
[Amit Varma]: actually happened, what strikes me there is that just as in the 1980s, the whole resurgence

03:31:01.400 --> 03:31:06.120
[Amit Varma]: of the Hindu vote was a bottom up thing, which, you know, Vajpayee and Advani were first completely

03:31:06.120 --> 03:31:07.600
[Amit Varma]: taken aback by.

03:31:07.600 --> 03:31:11.640
[Amit Varma]: What is happening now also is that the movement is a bottom up thing.

03:31:11.640 --> 03:31:16.360
[Amit Varma]: And that Vajpayee and even Advani, from what seems to from the narrative, have much less

03:31:16.360 --> 03:31:21.640
[Amit Varma]: control than most people, including Narsimha Rao, appear to think they do.

03:31:21.640 --> 03:31:26.760
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about that phase, especially as this episode releases on the 6th of December,

03:31:26.760 --> 03:31:29.440
[Amit Varma]: which is, of course, a, you know, a sort of a historic day.

03:31:29.440 --> 03:31:33.440
[Amit Varma]: So tell me about the lead up to that, because what is really interesting is that you have

03:31:33.440 --> 03:31:40.080
[Amit Varma]: political Hindutva, the supply end of political Hindutva, gathering force at a time when,

03:31:40.080 --> 03:31:43.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, the people at the top aren't really in control of events anymore.

03:31:43.800 --> 03:31:46.160
[Amit Varma]: And there are things happening, which have a momentum of their own.

03:31:46.160 --> 03:31:47.160
[Guest]: Tell me a bit about that.

03:31:47.160 --> 03:31:48.160
[Guest]: I think that's exactly right.

03:31:48.160 --> 03:31:53.680
[Guest]: Because, you know, and it's not like, let's just take a step back, Amit, to focus a little

03:31:53.680 --> 03:31:57.320
[Guest]: bit on the period 1990 to 91.

03:31:57.320 --> 03:32:02.000
[Guest]: There are three different momentums or three different forces in India, which have a momentum

03:32:02.000 --> 03:32:03.320
[Guest]: of their own.

03:32:03.320 --> 03:32:07.400
[Guest]: One is, of course, the OBC reservations in North India, which then culminates in Mandal

03:32:07.400 --> 03:32:08.680
[Guest]: Commission report.

03:32:08.680 --> 03:32:13.080
[Guest]: But Mandal Commission report didn't begin OBC reservations in India, it actually ended

03:32:13.080 --> 03:32:18.880
[Guest]: it because in the 60s itself, in the states like Tamil Nadu, Kerala, Karnataka, etc.

03:32:18.880 --> 03:32:22.480
[Guest]: You had OBC reservation and by the 80s, this had entered North India.

03:32:22.480 --> 03:32:27.120
[Guest]: So the OBC reservations and the central level and central government job was the culmination

03:32:27.120 --> 03:32:28.400
[Guest]: of this force.

03:32:28.400 --> 03:32:32.000
[Guest]: The other, of course, is the Rath Yatra or Mandir.

03:32:32.000 --> 03:32:36.040
[Guest]: As I point out, there was a bottom up force that was activated by the RSS and VHP and

03:32:36.040 --> 03:32:40.720
[Guest]: the movement began in 1983 itself, seven years before the Rath Yatra.

03:32:40.720 --> 03:32:47.200
[Guest]: And the third, let's not forget, Amit, was the catastrophic failure of the Indian economy.

03:32:47.200 --> 03:32:51.400
[Guest]: And again, it was not fated that you would end up with liberalization, but something

03:32:51.400 --> 03:32:52.400
[Guest]: had to give.

03:32:52.400 --> 03:32:57.320
[Guest]: So Indira Gandhi herself tried with the LKJ commission report, the Alexander commission

03:32:57.320 --> 03:33:02.800
[Guest]: report on economic changes, Rajiv Gandhi tried a little bit, but it was really left to Narsimha

03:33:02.800 --> 03:33:03.800
[Guest]: Rao to open up.

03:33:03.800 --> 03:33:09.920
[Guest]: Now, the point I make in my book is that all of these three events, which is Mandal, Mandir

03:33:09.920 --> 03:33:12.800
[Guest]: and market, were not inevitable.

03:33:12.800 --> 03:33:18.760
[Guest]: When VP Singh comes to power, yes, there is an OBC reservation, they did talk about it

03:33:18.760 --> 03:33:23.800
[Guest]: in the manifesto itself, but had it not been for Devi Lal's attempt to upstage VP Singh,

03:33:23.800 --> 03:33:26.400
[Guest]: he may never have implemented the Mandal commission report.

03:33:26.400 --> 03:33:29.880
[Guest]: If the government had changed and the Congress come back, they would have never implemented

03:33:29.880 --> 03:33:31.320
[Guest]: it.

03:33:31.320 --> 03:33:35.280
[Guest]: Because the commission report was submitted in 1980 itself and for 10 years, the Congress

03:33:35.280 --> 03:33:37.480
[Guest]: government didn't want to touch it.

03:33:37.480 --> 03:33:42.760
[Guest]: This ditto with Mandir, if it hadn't been for the Mandal commission report, Advani was

03:33:42.760 --> 03:33:47.400
[Guest]: still in his Hamlet-like ability of should I, should I not, he wouldn't have decisively

03:33:47.400 --> 03:33:49.120
[Guest]: got on to the rut.

03:33:49.120 --> 03:33:53.320
[Guest]: And as I argued in my previous book, Half Line, if it wasn't for Narsimha Rao, you may

03:33:53.320 --> 03:33:56.480
[Guest]: not have been so decisive when it came to liberalization.

03:33:56.480 --> 03:34:00.680
[Guest]: And I just want to take your listeners back to a question we had right in the beginning

03:34:00.680 --> 03:34:06.960
[Guest]: of this podcast, which is the role that events and people play alongside structures and larger

03:34:06.960 --> 03:34:07.960
[Guest]: changes.

03:34:07.960 --> 03:34:11.800
[Guest]: And I think Mandal, Mandir and Markit are good examples of that, that yes, there were

03:34:11.800 --> 03:34:14.200
[Guest]: larger forces, but it was not fated.

03:34:14.200 --> 03:34:20.760
[Guest]: And all those three decisions which LK Advani makes on Mandal, Mandir and Markit, which

03:34:20.760 --> 03:34:26.560
[Guest]: is to support OBC reservations, support Mandal, to support Mandir and to support Markit was

03:34:26.560 --> 03:34:27.560
[Guest]: not inevitable.

03:34:27.560 --> 03:34:30.680
[Guest]: And I point out in the book, many pulls and pressures he had.

03:34:30.680 --> 03:34:35.440
[Guest]: And for good or for worse, those three decisions define the party today, which is that BJP

03:34:35.440 --> 03:34:39.960
[Guest]: is known as the pro-Mandir party, it is known also as an OBC party.

03:34:39.960 --> 03:34:45.360
[Guest]: And I know many of your listeners would disagree, but at least it plays a superficial mouth

03:34:45.360 --> 03:34:49.240
[Guest]: value to the benefits of liberalization.

03:34:49.240 --> 03:34:55.120
[Guest]: And that's very important because that 1991 period is a real pivot in Indian history.

03:34:55.120 --> 03:34:56.680
[Guest]: It could have turned out very differently.

03:34:56.680 --> 03:35:01.680
[Guest]: Yes, there were the larger forces, but only looking at a larger forces and saying that

03:35:01.680 --> 03:35:06.640
[Guest]: these were inevitable in India, or to put it differently, looking just as demand side

03:35:06.640 --> 03:35:11.520
[Guest]: explanations to say that supply will soon follow, it need not have turned out that way.

03:35:11.520 --> 03:35:13.880
[Guest]: So in that sense, it's an enormous pivot.

03:35:13.880 --> 03:35:17.760
[Guest]: And I want to end with the question you asked, because today, your listeners are hearing

03:35:17.760 --> 03:35:20.640
[Guest]: it on December 6, 2020.

03:35:20.640 --> 03:35:25.040
[Guest]: And on December 6, 1992, there was a very different event in India, which is the demolition

03:35:25.040 --> 03:35:26.040
[Guest]: of the Babri Masjid.

03:35:26.040 --> 03:35:30.720
[Guest]: And Amit, I got to tell you that the Babri Masjid haunts me in many ways.

03:35:30.720 --> 03:35:35.000
[Guest]: So as I told you, right in the beginning of the podcast, I remember the Bombay riots,

03:35:35.000 --> 03:35:40.520
[Guest]: I remember seeing the timber yards on the other side of Mahim Bay burning from the terrace

03:35:40.520 --> 03:35:41.920
[Guest]: of my building.

03:35:41.920 --> 03:35:45.760
[Guest]: But also in my Narsimha Rao book, I devoted a whole chapter to it.

03:35:45.760 --> 03:35:50.320
[Guest]: And once again, in this book, I devote an entire chapter to Babri Masjid.

03:35:50.320 --> 03:35:54.600
[Guest]: And broadly, you know, so I think I've done more research on the subject and talk to more

03:35:54.600 --> 03:35:57.960
[Guest]: people than most, I would say with some confidence.

03:35:57.960 --> 03:36:00.920
[Guest]: And you know, I don't want to reveal more to your listener, because you know, she and

03:36:00.920 --> 03:36:02.580
[Guest]: he should read it.

03:36:02.580 --> 03:36:08.720
[Guest]: But in short, I'm more convinced that things went out of control, rather than a well planned

03:36:08.720 --> 03:36:10.280
[Guest]: conspiracy from the top.

03:36:10.280 --> 03:36:11.320
[Guest]: There was a conspiracy.

03:36:11.320 --> 03:36:15.160
[Guest]: The question is, was the top leadership of the BJP involved?

03:36:15.160 --> 03:36:19.240
[Guest]: You would never know, because there's a lot of smokes and mirrors happening here.

03:36:19.240 --> 03:36:23.000
[Guest]: The trial court has actually exonerated everybody saying there's no conspiracy.

03:36:23.000 --> 03:36:24.440
[Guest]: I don't agree with that.

03:36:24.440 --> 03:36:32.420
[Guest]: But it seems certainly plausible that someone like Advani and Vajpayee were blindsided by

03:36:32.420 --> 03:36:38.200
[Guest]: things getting out of hand, rather than, you know, well planned conspiracy from the top.

03:36:38.200 --> 03:36:42.160
[Amit Varma]: In fact, one of the sort of memorable sentences from your book and earlier, you claim that

03:36:42.160 --> 03:36:44.360
[Amit Varma]: you are not into good sentences and all of that.

03:36:44.360 --> 03:36:46.120
[Amit Varma]: And that's completely untrue.

03:36:46.120 --> 03:36:50.320
[Amit Varma]: And one of my favorite sentences from the book is when you're describing Advani and

03:36:50.320 --> 03:36:54.720
[Amit Varma]: Joshi at the site where, you know, things are going out of their hand and you write

03:36:54.720 --> 03:37:00.300
[Amit Varma]: quote, they look like prisoners rather than wardens, stop quote, which to me, like sums

03:37:00.300 --> 03:37:04.860
[Amit Varma]: up so much not just about that event, but possibly a lot more than that.

03:37:04.860 --> 03:37:08.800
[Amit Varma]: And then you also write about how, you know, Atal Bihari Vajpayee, of course, chose not

03:37:08.800 --> 03:37:12.760
[Amit Varma]: to go to Ayodhya and was apprehensive about what would happen there.

03:37:12.760 --> 03:37:14.000
[Amit Varma]: And he's in Delhi.

03:37:14.000 --> 03:37:19.360
[Amit Varma]: And you know, when the demolition starts, N M Khatate, his old friend goes to meet him.

03:37:19.360 --> 03:37:23.560
[Amit Varma]: And you quote Khatate as saying quote, he was all alone watching TV.

03:37:23.560 --> 03:37:25.000
[Amit Varma]: He was very, very angry.

03:37:25.000 --> 03:37:28.600
[Amit Varma]: He could not believe what had happened, stop quote.

03:37:28.600 --> 03:37:33.120
[Amit Varma]: And there's sort of, and that's just a very interesting dynamic, you know, we don't have

03:37:33.120 --> 03:37:34.120
[Amit Varma]: much time.

03:37:34.120 --> 03:37:36.520
[Amit Varma]: So I want to get to sort of closing question in a sense.

03:37:36.520 --> 03:37:42.200
[Amit Varma]: But again, I would say that I have barely touched upon sort of the depth and nuance

03:37:42.200 --> 03:37:43.200
[Amit Varma]: that is in your book.

03:37:43.200 --> 03:37:48.280
[Amit Varma]: So you know, even the period after this through the 90s, Vajpayee becoming Prime Minister,

03:37:48.280 --> 03:37:53.360
[Amit Varma]: the sort of the two short terms, and then that one longish term, and then Modi and Shah

03:37:53.360 --> 03:37:55.400
[Amit Varma]: coming back, all of it is fascinating.

03:37:55.400 --> 03:37:59.760
[Amit Varma]: And it's like a thriller unfolding in front of you and an ongoing thriller as it were.

03:37:59.760 --> 03:38:03.280
[Amit Varma]: So it's impossible to kind of put it down.

03:38:03.280 --> 03:38:09.880
[Amit Varma]: I want to sort of end with something that you said in a recent interview for Scroll

03:38:09.880 --> 03:38:18.240
[Amit Varma]: with Rohan Venkat, where in response to something that he said, you spoke about how quote, a

03:38:18.240 --> 03:38:23.120
[Amit Varma]: Hindu group consciousness that you are Hindu, I am Hindu, let's vote for the same party

03:38:23.120 --> 03:38:24.640
[Amit Varma]: that has to be constructed.

03:38:24.640 --> 03:38:28.600
[Amit Varma]: That's a hundred year project of Hindu nationalism, which is why when you look at the wording

03:38:28.600 --> 03:38:33.120
[Amit Varma]: of Hindu nationalism is politically liberal in that it is premised on the idea of one

03:38:33.120 --> 03:38:35.000
[Amit Varma]: person, one vote, stop quote.

03:38:35.000 --> 03:38:39.080
[Amit Varma]: Now, you've spoken about the Hindu group consciousness, you are Hindu, I am Hindu, let's vote for

03:38:39.080 --> 03:38:40.080
[Amit Varma]: the same party.

03:38:40.080 --> 03:38:44.840
[Amit Varma]: Now, obviously, people contain multitudes, which has become a cliche on my show.

03:38:44.840 --> 03:38:50.720
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, and it might be the case that, let us say that I am a Hindu, and you can

03:38:50.720 --> 03:38:55.440
[Amit Varma]: appeal to that part of me, when you're trying to build this Hindu group consciousness.

03:38:55.440 --> 03:39:01.320
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, what canny politicians would always look out for is that other other parts

03:39:01.320 --> 03:39:06.920
[Amit Varma]: of people's personality, which we can appeal to, which they can care about enough to vote

03:39:06.920 --> 03:39:09.880
[Amit Varma]: for it, that don't go down this axis.

03:39:09.880 --> 03:39:16.960
[Amit Varma]: So for example, a lot of the ideas of Congress are just abstract ideas and often insincerely

03:39:16.960 --> 03:39:22.560
[Amit Varma]: expressed by them to begin with, like concepts of secularism or all the abstract ideas of

03:39:22.560 --> 03:39:24.000
[Amit Varma]: India that come about.

03:39:24.000 --> 03:39:28.680
[Amit Varma]: And I would argue that in our lived reality as well, besides a Hindu consciousness, there

03:39:28.680 --> 03:39:34.320
[Amit Varma]: is also a sort of, there is something syncretic to it, there is something, you know, while

03:39:34.320 --> 03:39:38.040
[Amit Varma]: our society in many ways is deeply liberal, there are many ways in which it is deeply

03:39:38.040 --> 03:39:43.440
[Amit Varma]: liberal in the way that we embrace influences from everywhere and make this delightful khichdi,

03:39:43.440 --> 03:39:47.760
[Amit Varma]: like Vajpayee himself in his own personality, if not in his politics.

03:39:47.760 --> 03:39:54.720
[Amit Varma]: So my sort of rambling question to you right at the end is that, you know, in all your

03:39:54.720 --> 03:40:00.280
[Amit Varma]: studies of sort of political theory, not just in India and elsewhere, is it something that

03:40:00.280 --> 03:40:05.240
[Amit Varma]: would give you the sense that assuming that this Hindu consciousness has been captured

03:40:05.240 --> 03:40:10.760
[Amit Varma]: by this one party at the center, and it's done for, and it would appear that even other

03:40:10.760 --> 03:40:15.440
[Amit Varma]: parties like the Aam Aadmi Party and the Congress are very cognizant of it.

03:40:15.440 --> 03:40:20.400
[Amit Varma]: And they work within the bounds of, you know, they don't want to displease this Hindu consciousness,

03:40:20.400 --> 03:40:26.120
[Amit Varma]: so to say, you know, are there other aspects to our nature that also unite us, other things

03:40:26.120 --> 03:40:31.920
[Amit Varma]: that we care about, that can in future become a locus of political movements?

03:40:31.920 --> 03:40:36.560
[Guest]: So that's a deep question, I mean, like your other questions, but this is a deep question.

03:40:36.560 --> 03:40:42.160
[Guest]: And let me just rephrase it in my language, which is the following, which is that if you

03:40:42.160 --> 03:40:46.880
[Guest]: just buy this idea that India is a Hindu majority country, and you had this one party that has

03:40:46.880 --> 03:40:51.880
[Guest]: been able to activate Hindu group consciousness, is politics as we know over?

03:40:51.880 --> 03:40:55.760
[Guest]: Because there's no other way in which you can localize, you can kind of find another

03:40:55.760 --> 03:40:57.760
[Guest]: loci of identity.

03:40:57.760 --> 03:41:03.480
[Guest]: So one is that it's true that India is a Hindu majority country, but India is also a peasant

03:41:03.480 --> 03:41:04.480
[Guest]: majority country.

03:41:04.480 --> 03:41:07.880
[Guest]: It's a majority peasant country, it's a majority of workers and peasants.

03:41:07.880 --> 03:41:10.440
[Guest]: Why doesn't the Communist Party come to power?

03:41:10.440 --> 03:41:14.880
[Guest]: India is a majority Bahujan country, you know, non-Apakasa 80%.

03:41:14.880 --> 03:41:16.980
[Guest]: Why didn't Kanchiram come to power?

03:41:16.980 --> 03:41:25.640
[Guest]: So the first answer to your question is that rather than look for other identity access,

03:41:25.640 --> 03:41:28.720
[Guest]: maybe the real answer lies in better organization.

03:41:28.720 --> 03:41:33.200
[Guest]: You know, rather than trying to find a magic that, you know, to counter Hindu group consciousness

03:41:33.200 --> 03:41:38.740
[Guest]: by something else, how about like picking parties which just focus on better organization

03:41:38.740 --> 03:41:42.720
[Guest]: and in that learn something from the BJP, don't split, right?

03:41:42.720 --> 03:41:44.400
[Guest]: Believe in teamwork, right?

03:41:44.400 --> 03:41:48.680
[Guest]: Even when there's disagreement, kind of stick around because things may come your part.

03:41:48.680 --> 03:41:54.040
[Guest]: That's the purpose of this book, that look, the inevitability of the BJP's rise is not

03:41:54.040 --> 03:41:55.040
[Guest]: true.

03:41:55.040 --> 03:41:56.040
[Guest]: There's hard work there.

03:41:56.040 --> 03:41:57.040
[Guest]: There's teamwork there.

03:41:57.040 --> 03:42:01.280
[Guest]: Yes, it's a majoritarian ideology, but there's no shortage of majoritarian ideologies in

03:42:01.280 --> 03:42:02.280
[Guest]: India.

03:42:02.280 --> 03:42:04.360
[Guest]: Why did this particular one win?

03:42:04.360 --> 03:42:07.680
[Guest]: So that's the first sort of answer to the question that you asked.

03:42:07.680 --> 03:42:14.200
[Guest]: The second answer, Amit, is to ask the question that is the only way to defeat the BJP through

03:42:14.200 --> 03:42:19.400
[Guest]: another group identity or is there another way to conceptualize the individual?

03:42:19.400 --> 03:42:25.880
[Guest]: Unfortunately on this question, I'm a pessimist, which is that the beginning of Hindu nationalism

03:42:25.880 --> 03:42:30.960
[Guest]: is the introduction of one person, one vote to a group-based society where Indians think

03:42:30.960 --> 03:42:35.740
[Guest]: in their social and economic lives are entirely in terms of groups.

03:42:35.740 --> 03:42:40.560
[Guest]: What makes Indian politics flexible is that the group definition keeps changing.

03:42:40.560 --> 03:42:44.200
[Guest]: Sometimes you vote on the basis of your region, sometimes your caste, sometimes your religion,

03:42:44.200 --> 03:42:47.280
[Guest]: but you're still voting on the basis of groups.

03:42:47.280 --> 03:42:53.840
[Guest]: Now the question is, will Indians ever start voting on the basis of individual freedom?

03:42:53.840 --> 03:42:54.840
[Guest]: That's really the question.

03:42:54.840 --> 03:42:58.960
[Guest]: And if that happens, that's a genuine counter to the BJP.

03:42:58.960 --> 03:43:02.360
[Guest]: Stop telling me how to celebrate Valentine's Day.

03:43:02.360 --> 03:43:04.400
[Guest]: Stop telling me what to eat in my house.

03:43:04.400 --> 03:43:07.640
[Guest]: These are all based on the idea of individual freedom.

03:43:07.640 --> 03:43:13.840
[Guest]: The reason, Amit, that those critics of the BJP don't have popular purchase, they just

03:43:13.840 --> 03:43:20.320
[Guest]: don't have popular purchase, is in India we yet don't have a constituency which is liberal.

03:43:20.320 --> 03:43:25.120
[Guest]: And I define liberal in the very limited sense of putting individual freedom at the center

03:43:25.120 --> 03:43:26.620
[Guest]: of your politics.

03:43:26.620 --> 03:43:32.960
[Guest]: So that's a pretty pessimistic answer because that is a fundamental counter to the BJP.

03:43:32.960 --> 03:43:38.400
